Title: Through the Language Glass: Why the World Looks Different in Other Languages
Author: Guy Deutscher

Title: Damascus Station
Author: David McCloskey
My Review:
interesting modern espionage thriller, it was great reading some of the intricate details and the cat and mouse games being played out in volatile zones.

Sadly the good parts were overruled by the cringe bs romance, and all the ongoing story threads simply being rendered useless towards the end: the caricature like villains have a sudden change of behaviour, of heart, of motivations, just to help fit the rushed ending and wasted space in the middle.

Good potential, but let down massively.

Title: Nightside the Long Sun (The Book of the Long Sun, #1)
Author: Gene Wolfe
My Review: The cranial fissure that appeared over the course of reading this pretentious dross was a mystery to me until I realized I had been bored out of my mind.

Title: The Forsaken Throne (Kingfountain, #6)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
Deus exponential machina, is how I'd describe it.

The Fountain is already a Deus Ex - it is a convenient thing that happens to give the right info at the right time. That would be bad except it is woven into the story well enough to not be overwhelming. Adding any more would be too much though, and that's what happens. Sinia returns just in time with all the right knowledge and cures and everything is wrapped up nicely in a neat bow. Some characters are killed off to make room for a happy ending, but it results in poor storytelling and unexplored threads of story and world building.

Overall it made for a weak ending to an a already weak series. I was familiar with muirwood but wasn't interested in the major parts of the story that takes place there. Too much was sacrificed for it.

Title: The Silent Shield (Kingfountain, #5)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
As I feared, the main character is a Mary Sue. She's the star of the show, she's the pining princess, she's the warrior, she's the magician, she is the politician, she can do it all.

There are too many inconsistencies in behaviours and actions going on. Some people behave suspiciously and suddenly don't. Then do again. There are so many threads that some of it just seems forgotten or an afterthought.

The ending felt rushed and inappropriate in the face of the amount of deaths and destruction that was described. It was so strange the about turn that happens in just a few pages. Oh our enemy is our friend now, cool let's go get some drinks, yeah ignore the dead bodies of your closest friends and family, said he was sorry didn't he?

Title: The Hollow Crown (Kingfountain, #4)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
I'm picking up this one years after reading the previous and forgetting events from the past books didn't get in the way. There's a new cast of characters, with some references to the old ones, and the same familiar settings of mixed mythologies and places.

The new protagonist seems to have a lot going on, quite a few interesting plot points, and is in danger of becoming a Mary Sue.

Title: Señorita Cometa Vol 1 Español Latino

My Review: Decent story but has pacing issues and kind of drags.

Title: Corktown (Abby Kane FBI Thriller, #1)

My Review: If shame were a currency, I'd have used it to purchase this book, since it's clear the author is desperately in need of some.

Title: I Cheerfully Refuse
Author: Leif Enger
My Review: A mixture of a dystopian scene with a somewhat spiritual journey, which results in many events happening but not much explained. I'm not a fan of these types of vibes based stories, if I can even call it that. The pace is slow which isn't too bad, it's just not leading to anything.

Title: Neuromancer (Sprawl #1)
Author: William Gibson
My Review:
After reading the book, I decided to look at the reviews. I have learned the following:

1. A lot of people had to read it several times to "get" it. If I knew this were the case, I wouldn't have started in the first place.

2. It's a lot about context - you had to know that this book is considered a classic and you had to know that it's the book that started the whole cyberpunk genre. But since I didn't know any if that, I treated it as any other book. Since I've read a lot of scifi before this, and keeping in mind that other authors got their ideas from this book, Neuromancer felt stale and unoriginal. There was nothing special about it, save for the excessive cliches in every paragraph.

3. You have to buy into the hype - else all you have is a normal book with flat, dimensionless characters, a poorly flowing storyline set in a world of computers that authors are so eager to visualize and build upon with little to no understanding of it. It's like akira (anime) or 2001 (movie). They are now famous for being famous. Some will love it, some won't get it because it has no relevance to them. That's how I started Neuromancer as well, only finding out later that you're supposed to love it or clearly yours is not an opinion worth having.

I'm sure I would have liked it if it were one of my earliest books. Alas, it comes in after years of the same kind of thing.

To use an analogy, it would be like watching the first live action Batman series after having seen the Dark Knight movies.

Title: Yellowface
Author: R.F. Kuang
My Review:
Not a bad one at all. I have no idea how accurate it was as a depiction; it felt like a glimpse into the world of authors, and their minds and insecurities and jealousies. Some of it was a great reflection of ourselves as readers and how we judge authors too.

I liked the writing style, it felt realistic enough and unhinged enough that it was the author's own thoughts being expressed here, and perhaps even a confession in the mix? That's just speculation of course, I have no idea about the author themselves, I tend to do my best to avoid getting to know about the people who write the things I read. The reason being that if you dig, then at a certain point you will learn that everyone is a raging asshole scumbag, and if you try to avoid books by authors for reasons of morality around any-given-subject, you will never read anything at all.

It felt pretty funny to know that somewhere, an author will have read some of my scathing 1-star reviews of their books and perhaps even reread it a few times like poking at a scab, their agents telling them not to obsess over the opinions of a nothing random like me, and yet they simply cannot help it. We, the swarm that infest the online world, are not worth paying attention to, we on Goodreads, Xitter, Tumblr, Reddit, wherever we gather like vultures to a feast. Moral outrage is a manufactured industry to keep attention in social media, ultimately it's the platform owners seeking to profit, not foster useful dialogue.

Anyway about the book — good story, it drags a bit in the middle, and some of the brand and product name mentions felt cringy to me, IMO there should always be an effort to not name the brand, just name the device.

Title: The Great Catsby (A NOLA Tail Mystery #1)
Author: B.K. Baxter
My Review:
The cat barely features at all. That was already a major tell and I should have stopped reading there.

Unfortunately to me, the main character was not endearing at all, she was rude, invasive, pushy, and kept justifying it since it was OK for her to be doing so, not others though. In short, a through and through asshole. The other characters came off like that too, there is nothing charming, cozy, or quaint about the town.

In the end even the revelation wasn't worth it.

Title: 나 혼자만 레벨 업 4 [Solo Leveling] Novel
Author: Chugong

Title: The Spy Who Came In from the Cold (George Smiley, #3)
Author: John Le Carré
My Review:
Really well written spy/espionage novel. There's no action, there's a lot of talking that reveals the story and intrigues as it progresses, and it just kept me guessing about what was actually going on. There were some parts I was able to guess, second guess, third guess, (well, it took a few tries) but the interesting part was in the how of it. In that sense, pretty good.

I didn't enjoy the raging alcoholism that most characters were — they seem to consume alcohol more than water — and the creepy wish fulfillment that Liz served. Many of the characters though, seemed really interesting, each one unique in the short glimpses we got of them.

It helps to have a brief recap over the history of East and West Germany, as some of the names and locations do play a part. I just skimmed the Wikipedia page for Berlin Wall.

I think overall it's worth reading for the intrigue and the way it leaves you guessing until the end.

Title: Slow Train (Slim Hardy Mysteries, #4)
Author: Jack Benton
My Review:
It seems that in order to become any kind of detective worth writing about, the detective must also be a raging alcoholic. I keep wondering why this specific trope seems to pervade all detective novels, and perhaps it's just a cheap crutch to show "oh look, he's flawed". Perhaps it works sometimes, but having read many novels, it's just tiresome.

What's more, it felt completely unnecessary; it could have been edited out and not really affected the story. If only that were the end of it, there's also a bit of creepy wish fulfillment in the form of Lia, who served little purpose.

But I could also, maybe, see why these elements were introduced. Without it it's a slow, methodical burn, and there would have been 'breaks' needed as the mystery just kept getting stretched and stretched. There were so many names and places to remember that I lost interest about half way through and had to slog through it, all for an unsatisfying conclusion.

What kept me was the location, I really like the Peak District and the Hope Valley where the story was set. There are periods of reflection and appreciation for the scenery in the area which I enjoyed.

Was it a coincidence.. right after this I read what should have been a separate genre at the same time, [b:The Spy Who Came In from the Cold|19494|The Spy Who Came In from the Cold (George Smiley, #3)|John Le Carré|https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1327719782l/19494._SY75_.jpg|1177001] and imagine my surprise when it too had another raging alcoholic and a wish fulfillment named Liz, and so the issue stuck out all the more.

Title: The Wandering Earth: Classic Science Fiction Collection
Author: Liu Cixin
My Review:
Sci-Fi short stories are a great way for authors to explore ideas without investing too much into a fully expanded world and timeline. It keeps things short and sweet, but they can't just call it 'sweet stories', and 'short and sweet stories' isn't short, so 'short stories' makes sense. Anyway it's a good insight into the author's creative mind.

This collection is among the best I've read in recent memory, each idea unique and revealed in detail over the course of seemingly strange events. The enjoyment I derived from it was novel, and reminded me of the first time I delighted in reading The Complete Robot.

One of my favourite parts of the writing is the unique approach to characters: they are irrelevant, merely names attached to the vessels that carry out the ideas and observations and conversations. In fact I barely remember any of the names and was able to enjoy each story fully. I actually like this feature as it's a breath of fresh air in a sometimes samey landscape — to focus on some core ideas.

And if you pay attention you will find links between some of the stories, which is an icing on the cake (not fondant though).

Title: The Seeds of Time
Author: John Wyndham
My Review: Underrated IMO. The stories are simple and low key, the sci-fi part is just there without much exposition, it forms a natural part of the world in which the actual stories are focused on. I liked the simplicity of the stories. Really nice read.

Title: Strange Universe: The Weird and Wild Science of Everyday Life--on Earth and Beyond
Author: Bob Berman
My Review:
I did make an effort to like this, and the contents themselves were entertaining. It was a few things that got in the way though.

I don't think I've encountered a science book that makes use of the outdated imperial system. It was constantly jarring to encounter awkward numbers of inches, Fahrenheit, and pounds being quoted.

There's even a chapter dedicated towards pointing out standard units, but then spending most of the time justifying imperial. Which is bad enough in itself, but it makes use of a few almost (but not exactly) coincidental numbers to make it sound like an intuitive system... and this is done shortly after telling us that coincidences themselves aren't proofs at all!

Anyone who grows up with any bizarre system will consider it intuitive. There was really no need to waste this ink on such a pointless topic.

The other thing that got in the way were, let's say, some embellishments. While I'm not an expert in all areas, the ones where I did go and do further reading, I realized stories had been exaggerated or retold for entertainment and were just on the side of being wrong.

Title: She Who Became the Sun (The Radiant Emperor, #1)
Author: Shelley Parker-Chan

Title: The Pelican Brief
Author: John Grisham
My Review:
it's a legal thriller, which starts with two supreme court justice being assassinated. A law student has a theory regarding the why, which is where it all kicks off.

The running around and cat and mouse games weren't bad. The characters are a bit, hmm, dated. The main character Darby Shaw is actually interesting and intelligent, but the author keeps commenting on her appearance and it is kind of creepy and hasn't aged well. The romantic angles are forced and unnecessary.

The final conclusions are unsatisfactory, some of it makes sense but some is just a bit hand wavey.

Title: The Rose Field (The Book of Dust #3)
Author: Philip Pullman

Title: Nine O'Clock Bus To Brompton (The County Mounties, #1)
Author: Kevin Fitzpatrick
My Review:
At one point in the story, Don's wife Rosemary packs up and leaves him, scribbling a 'how could you' type message on a mirror in lipstick. When this happened, I had thought that the story, which until then was dully blundering along, was about to pick up a notch, this 'extra' layer of mystery on top of the ongoing murder investigation was unexpected.

Later, we learn that Rosemary had packed up and left because of some dumbass assumption she made on seeing someone Don had once had an affair with... that was; actually it wasn't even explained well at all. It turns out the drama was added for the sake of it. One of my least favourite tropes in all media is situations which could have been resolved if two people talked to each other. In this case it was vital that they did not talk to each other, or the pointless drama would never have occurred.

I should have stopped reading there, but since I enjoy punishing myself so much, I carried on.

It seems Don has learned nothing at all as he encounters other women. But perhaps Don isn't to blame entirely, he's just a fictional character. I noticed that the author insists on describing all the women in this story in a creepy level of detail.

Genuinely, I don't care if the book was _set_ in the 60s, the book was _written_ in the 2000s, and this kind of treatment shouldn't be a feature.

The one saving grace might have been the lawyer encountered towards the last part of the book, a clever one who runs circles around everyone; sadly this lawyer is a 'she' and given the same diminishing, reductive treatment.

Title: The Doors of Eden
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
This definitely falls into speculative science-fiction so it's not for everyone. There are several layers of 'what if' scenarios about parallel worlds that are woven into one overarching story. The various disparate scenarios seem disjointed, but stick around and the patience is rewarded.

That said, there is some patience needed. Some parts are a slog and I feel (like I do with many of this same author's books) that it could have done with some trimming down.

The characters are OK, but it takes too long to explain them. Some of them, like Rove, feel completely pointless. Some, like Khan, felt like a caricature - I kept thinking that Khan was what non English people think English people talk like.

Characters aside, the science feels really well done here, you can tell that a lot of research has gone into the various ideas to make it just speculative enough for that suspension of belief.

Solid 3.5 for me but some things did work in its favour. I'm glad this is a standalone book and not a needlessly stretched trilogy (I'm not a fan of the 3rd book of any of his series). Also, I really enjoyed the cat planet. Peak planet.

Title: A Window Breaks
Author: C.M. Ewan
My Review:
No amount of barbed wire on tall fences was going to be enough against Tom's constant insecurity and suspicion of his entire family.

i nEEd tO pROteCT mY FAmIly, he would exclaim, only to do nothing and spend more time introspectively over analysing every situation and casting suspicion. If I wanted to observe an impotent character, I'd just narrate my own life.

The rest of the family wasn't endearing either. Rachel and Tom together were helicopter parents taken to extremes, suffering from self inflicted marriage healing drama for no good reason at all, no logic whatsoever.

The contrived reasons for stretching the plot out were too obvious. Tom I need to tell you something. Not now Rachel, for plot reasons.

That said the way the pieces of the story fit together was well done, small details and threads were related to each other somehow. It was just a slog getting there.

Title: Unfinished Witchness (Haunted Haven Book 1)
Author: Ada Bell
My Review: A decent cozy paranormal mystery taking place in a small town. Some interesting characters but the story seems a bit fetched, and several important parts were just skipped including the actual moment of resolution.

Title: In the Silence of Decay (Pinter P.I., #1)
Author: Lisa  Boyle

Title: The Other Valley
Author: Scott Alexander Howard
My Review:
A slow burn mystery-esque scifi that's written in a natural setting. The characters are well written, nobody, not even the protagonist, feels remarkable or extraordinary or mundane or boring. They seem very, very human, in that they are selfish one moment and selfless the next, and with good reasons.

The setting is pretty well done too — the valley is next to duplicates of itself, only the neighbours are 20 years ahead and behind in time. The story takes place, of course, over 20 years, and is naturally woven in as we follow the protagonist's life, thoughts, ambitions.

It's definitely a unique setting which made reading through worth it. I think this is meant to be one of those "let it wash over you" stories; spending too much time treating it like a hard scifi where everything needs a complex accurate explanation will ruin it, and I'm glad it didn't go there. There was only enough to keep the world building, and the story moving along.

Title: Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy (George Smiley, #5; Karla Trilogy, #1)
Author: John Le Carré

Title: James
Author: Percival Everett
My Review:
I think I'm glad I went in to this not remembering much of the original Huckleberry Finn, as evidenced by the more negative reviews, the comparison seems to be taking away from this book by itself.

That said, the content is disturbing at times and serious and ventures into bits of philosophy. I liked their "other language" introduced early on, very interesting as a premise, and it sets the scene for the rest of the book.

Title: A Choice of Gods
Author: Clifford D. Simak
My Review:
Very interesting speculative science fiction, I'm surprised this wasn't more popular. It's cozy reading, simply presented, and uses accessible language (though not all of it has aged well).

At the same time it covers so many different concepts and topics such as philosophy, space, technology, humanity, the galaxy, aliens, and probably more. There's an overarching slow burn mystery that permeates as the story progresses, but don't expect a rush, it definitely takes its time getting there, we are instead treated to the joys of a slower more appreciative life pace.

Title: Days of Shattered Faith (The Tyrant Philosophers, #3)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
Sentence fragments. The prose, difficult. Wading in treacle made of headaches. Writing his review, the obliging need to. Everyone talked the same. "Couldn't tell people apart," he said. Couldn't tell the narration apart, from the dialogue.

A good story, somewhere in there. Perhaps.

Stops. And realised. "Another third in a trilogy, another let down".

Title: 賭ケグルイ双 14 (Kakegurui Twin, #14)
Author: Homura Kawamoto
Publisher: スクウェア・エニックス

Title: The King in Yellow
Author: Robert W. Chambers
My Review:
Published in 1895, it's a set of short stories that I think are a precursor to horror/macabre stories of today, and with bits of alternative history on top.

The writing style is very different from today's, obviously, and I noticed that several of the stories were introspective in their horror instead of the more gorey slop we are served today. It's nothing over the top, but just enough over a realistic day to day that gives it a wonderfully creepy quality.

The first few stories are horror with a common theme between them, the last 3 or so are unrelated and don't feel like they belong here, they're just dull as paint whimsical artsy fartsy ones that the collection could have done without.

It was available for free on Standard Ebooks (public domain).

Title: ATRI -My Dear Moments-(1) (角川コミックス・エース)
Author: Unknown Author

Title: Machine Vendetta (Prefect Dreyfus Emergency, #3)
Author: Alastair Reynolds
My Review:
A fitting end (I think it's the end) to the series. The author didn't try to stretch anything out, just told a set of stories from start to finish without trying to milk anything or resorting to cheap tropes like bringing people back from the dead. The stakes felt all the more real for it.

The supporting cast is fantastic too, each one is principled and stoic in their own way without being too cheesy.

The author's worldbuilding helps set the scene in which the story plays out. And the series name is correct... there's always an emergency!

Title: Not Till We Are Lost (Bobiverse #5)
Author: Dennis E. Taylor
My Review:
Too many threads of activity going on, and most of it was filler material, with little consequence. I struggled to remember who or what was who or what, which didn't help.

This should have been much shorter. I hope this isn't the future of the series though. It started well enough has devolved into excess jargon.

Title: Mystic River
Author: Dennis Lehane
My Review:
A glittering sprinkle coated fondant heap that gently enrobes a tiny odorless turd.

This reads like an extended internet recipe. The author meanders, wanderers, takes long walks, into the realms of irrelevant flashbacks before getting to the mediocrity of the actual point.

Despite the author's best attempts, there is a mystery there, trying to make itself known, but the passages of snobbish "grit"and the internal monologues and slang references to a hardened lifestyle that probably pass for pseudo literature do their damnedest to keep it away from you. I genuinely felt my time being wasted away as I worked my way through the self insisting tripe, the mundane conversations trying to show how matter of fact and wizened everyone was with life lessons.

That's what the passages are like. Nobody could get through a coffee order without going through some childhood trauma or other irrelevant stories for no reason other than filler. It was like watching paint dry on a rainy day. You're not even sure the paint is drying, but you’re still sitting there, staring at it, wondering why you started in the first place, waiting for it to dry and when it finally does you realise it wasn't worth the wait.

The reason for that became pretty obvious as the "story", such as it was, progressed: without the reams of literary fondant coating it, the plot is just shit. Major plot points were so obvious early on that it felt like a relief when they finally happened (biggest of all Jimmy and Dave). The actual mystery though, unsatisfying in its useless revelation, gets hand waved away in a couple of paragraphs as an afterthought and self justifying mental gymnastics. Yep really. Nobody cared.

It wasn't even stinkingly bad shit, it was just the dry dessicated husk of shit, a long forgotten memory of a passing fox or a dog, left after a long, unrelanting summer, the kind where your skin's baking and everyone's roasting, inducing a general malaise and community lethargy, but everyone's maintaining a sense of civil niceness, since we're all humans after all and just two square meals and twenty degrees away from a barbaric breakdown of society.

Title: 戦う司書と黒蟻の迷宮　ＢＯＯＫ３ (集英社スーパーダッシュ文庫) (Japanese Edition)
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: Tatakau Shisho to Shuushou no Kemono
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: What Feasts at Night (Sworn Soldier, #2)
Author: T. Kingfisher
My Review: Interesting series to get into. Somehow I would call it a cozy horror, which sounds contradictory but still fits, in my opinion. The horrors aren't cheap jump scares, for whatever its equivalent would be in a book, they're sometimes slow and sometimes mundane but they build up into something more than their sum and feeling creeped out over.

Title: The Armor of Light (Kingsbridge, #4)
Author: Ken Follett
My Review:
The series has devolved into retelling the exact same story in each book. The magic and uniqueness of Pillars of the Earth is lost and this is now a comfort retelling of all the other books with the names changed, and a dose of ongoing historical events. In fairness the description of the historical events and their effect on society was really good, in turn though they made the characters seem flat, and everything is a trope. All ugly people are bad and do bad things; pretty people do bad things but that's acceptable; there's a few clever misunderstood people ahead of their time, and they talk like middle schoolers. Much of the writing didn't help... a lot of the dialogue was stilted, and there seemed to be manufactured drama. I also think that this author along with Brandon Sanderson need to stay away from romance. Please, just stop. Get some help.

I kept wondering if the author would just keep repeating the exact same story in every historic age possible, going all the way back to the Neolithic era.

Gronk like Klee.
Klee married to Ugli.
Klee secretly like Gronk, they meet and bonk, oh no.
But it OK because Klee pretty.

Ugli man bad. Ugli man not like Gronk.
Gronk clever and smart and ahead of his era and possesses the mores of an individual from $CURRENT_YEAR unlike his contemporaries because they're stupid hunter gatherers unlike Gronk.

Many years pass.
Gronk invent farming and upends all of society.
Gronk finally overcome Ugli.
Gronk marry Klee, they live happily. On farm which Gronk invent.

Title: The Rose Rent (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #13)
Author: Ellis Peters

Title: The Raven in the Foregate (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #12)
Author: Ellis Peters

Title: Roadside Picnic
Author: Arkady Strugatsky
Additional Authors: Boris Strugatsky, Theodore Sturgeon, Antonina W. Bouis
My Review: Interesting concept, difficult to follow narrative. The main character is always drunk and angry. It's very difficult to connect with the characters and story.

Title: 戦う司書と恋する爆弾　ＢＯＯＫ１ (集英社スーパーダッシュ文庫) (Japanese Edition)
Author: Ishio Yamagata
My Review:
Review for the entire series.

I picked this up as I'd heard it could fill the void that was left behind by the never to be completed Rokka no Yuusha. I'm glad I did.

A really good series that combines mysterious world building, strange powers, grey characters and a long overarching plot together, with an atmosphere of a long hidden history over it. It is more psychological, strategy, maneuvering, and story, than it is action oriented, though the action is all the more meaningful for it.

The series doesn't feel drawn out and is just the right length. I was disappointed in the final volume as it was more action and fan service than anything else but didn't regret my time spent.

Worth noting it really needs to be read together in one go. There are a lot of characters with a lot of intertwining stories and details that are relevant player. Skipping any can mean easily forgetting and not understanding what's happening.

Title: Tatakau Shisho to Sekai no Chikara
Author: Ishio Yamagata
My Review: Weak ending to a great series. The action is drawn out way too long and becomes monotonous. The series strength was in its buildup to the confrontations, not the actual fights themselves. The cameos were pointless and clearly there just for fan service.

Title: Tatakau Shisho To Zetsubō No Maō
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: Tatakau Shisho to Kyogensha no Utage
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: Tatakau Shisho to Aranawa no Himegimi
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: Tatakau Shisho To Tsuisō No Majo
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: Tatakau Shisho to Kami no Sekiken
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: Tatakau Shisho to Kuroari no Meikyu
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: 戦う司書と雷（いかずち）の愚者　ＢＯＯＫ２ (集英社スーパーダッシュ文庫) (Japanese Edition)
Author: Ishio Yamagata

Title: 괴담 호텔 탈출기 (Escaping the Mystery Hotel)
Author: 쿠크루

Title: House of Open Wounds (The Tyrant Philosophers, #2)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review: A decent plot that's stretched thin over a lot of unnecessary filler material. Yasnic from the first book is one of the main characters here and can't help but interfere with everything for poorly contrived reasons. A lot of in between stuff happens with little to no consequence and honestly could have done with a ruthless editor. The prose was difficult for me too, it's somehow dense and also written in a terse noir style. Incomplete fragments. Makes reading harder. Than necessary.

Title: JIN―仁― 1 (ヤングジャンプコミックスDIGITAL) (Japanese Edition)
Author: 村上もとか
Author l-f: 村上もとか, 村上もとか

Title: Classroom of the Elite: Year 2 (Light Novel) Vol. 8
Author: Syougo Kinugasa
My Review:
Remember when Classroom of the Elite used to have a plot, mystery, intrigue, and battle of wills? And didn't waste time on dragging things out, fillers, and interpersonal drama?

Well, I think the author's forgotten.

Title: A Cheesemonger's History of The British Isles
Author: Ned Palmer

Title: The Library at Mount Char
Author: Scott  Hawkins
My Review:
I too found it weird but derived none of the enjoyment from it. It's poorly written and some parts seem forcefully bizarre for the sake of being bizarre with little to no purpose.

The writing and dialogue are stilted and the characters have no character except for the bizarre weird part.

Title: うみねこのなく頃に散 Episode 5: End of the golden witch 1
Author: Ryukishi07
Publisher: スクウェア・エニックス

Title: A Wounded Realm (The Blood of Kings #2)
Author: K.M. Ashman

Title: The Mercy of Gods (The Captive's War, #1)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review:
The setting is quite interesting in that the humans are the underdogs, there is a vast alien context at play, which they are struggling to piece together. Alkhorn is a really interesting character in his analytical capabilities, questioning why things are, and occasionally showing some insights and discoveries, which makes for a great read.

The aliens were a bit difficult to understand, which is kind of the point, though I did get the gist of what was happening.

Title: The House in the Cerulean Sea (Cerulean Chronicles, #1)
Author: T.J. Klune
My Review:
Sort of a whimsical, cutesy, farcical mix. The story is an orphanage case worker sent to investigate a specific orphanage. The story is predictable in the sense that you know what's going to happen but you're just there for the journey.

A few moral lessons do get explored but not too much in depth, a few situations get hand waved away, and the main focus is the characters on the island.

Title: Light from Uncommon Stars
Author: Ryka Aoki
My Review:
This was a struggle to read. There are so many themes and topics being mixed in together - gender, reality, fantasy, sci-fi, music, violins , food, race, communities - that none of them get proper time and attention, and the end result is a watered down, diluted treatment where the book can't decide what it's trying to do. It's almost like a 'story' based on a checklist.

The writing style seems to change often, some parts like the violin related passages are nearly incomprehensibly floating in clouds of pretentiousness, the food parts are often long winded and stay long past their welcome, the sci-fi parts feel like they belong to some other novel but were shoved in, the other parts have a scattering of styles. It's as though these were all written by different people and shoved together.

The writing itself gets confusing too, there are sudden POV changes without warning, frequently. I've had to reread several passages to figure out who was doing what, I think some kind of separation or even lots of mini chapters, would have been useful here. Although there seemed to be relevance to all the characters, in the end they all just felt inconsequential and were just 'there' to occupy space.

There was for sure, potential for a good story here but it's overridden by too many other things going on.

Title: Juice
Author: Tim Winton
My Review:
Most of the story is about the main character, as he relates his backstory to his captor.

The style of telling (1001 nights style framing, that is) is just bad, every few chapters there is a brief exchange between the captor and narrator, and it just doesn't work. It's tedious, trite, and tiresome, nothing of value or consequence happens. I wish it could have been just told as a regular story.

The actual tale, the main character's backstory, starts tepid but becomes more interesting as it goes. I found I was just enthralled by the reveals as they came, learning more and more about the world and the people he came across. There were some bits that just weren't explained which confused me, such as the interaction or unspoken agreement between his mother and wife, or how someone would be upset about something but not say why, and I'm just not socially cued enough to pick up on it.

I'm a hater of heat and summer, so the actual theme of the story was relevant to me, and the way humanity adapted around the disasters of climate change and our callous disregard or dare I even say our celebration of it. I was "horrified" when he called 35C a pleasant winter day, which struck a chord with me, as I regularly see people in my sphere happy when there is unseasonably hot weather here.

Late in the story there is introduced a... set of people whose existence I found unfathomable and disjointed from the rest of the world. Humanity has resorted to primitive technology in most areas, yet the sims somehow exist and are fully functional, articulate, perfect for the new world and its excessive sun, and yet are so human like. It feels like it came out of nowhere and wouldn't fit.

Overall minus the narrative bits, it was an interesting story even if it's dystopian.

Title: The Anthropocene Reviewed: Essays on a Human-Centered Planet
Author: John Green
My Review: Not so much the Anthropocene Reviewed, more like the American Scene Reviewed.  While it tries to draw observations about the human condition from the regular day-to-day, it is very much centered around American place names, culturalisms, and references.  Because of that, many of them made little to no sense and failed to elicit the spark of understanding that the author was trying to draw out.

Title: Dome: Rebellion (Dome, #1)
Author: Johnathon Nicolaou
My Review:
If they simply attached servo motors to everyone's eyeballs then the dome would have no energy problem, considering the amount of eyerolling they do.

There's a bit of good world building that makes the setting interesting. There's a dome, as the title says, in which tiers of humanity live in, protected from the outside world and managing diminishing resources. A group of friends discover the truth about the elites though.

So far so good. What isn't so good is the cliched characters. The main character is just an asshole. He has main character syndrome and is somehow always the victim, yet constantly sizing others up and fighting for no good reason. His friend Allie is little more than a cardboard cutout, she exists only as his crutch. Romeo is a comedy relief and punching bag. There is only one reaction people have, eyeroll. It gets noticeably repetitive.


The dialog is a bit cringe at times but not terrible. What's jarring is the forced anachronistic phrases. One person didn't know what a museum was, but later tells someone they're not supposed to know about winter because they live in a regulated atmosphere. The trouble with a group knowing some words and not others just doesn't work. They keeps appearing in phrases and expressions. It's better to just not engage in it at all.

Similar issue with the 'code' that they are cracking. I don't know if these two main characters are braindead or suffering some vitamin deficiency, but they made it look like reading the first word of every sentence was a code that needed cracking. Is this for real? Again, perhaps it was better not to show too much at all.

Overall an ok book, kind of short but needs work on editing.

Title: What Moves the Dead (Sworn Soldier, #1)
Author: T. Kingfisher
My Review:
It's a small setting, which I prefer, just a few characters in a small rural area and a dismal house. The writing is simple but descriptive and not much time wasted at all.

The writing is quite good, you know what's coming but it's still just as horrific and chilling when described.

I didn't know that this was based on a short story by Edgar Allan Poe, but it definitely stands on its own and much better IMO.

Title: The Fall of the House of Usher
Author: Edgar Allan Poe

Title: The Full Cupboard of Life (No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency, #5)
Author: Alexander McCall Smith
My Review:
A decent entry in the series, sprinkled with calls to traditions, culture and yearning for human connections and community. The people are all written, the setting is just the right balance of comfortable and hard work. It's great to see glimpses into the lives of the main characters and how they've grown. I love how much pride they have in their country while acknowledging its issues.

Which is all wonderful, but I've been reading this for the mysteries of which this time there was very little to speak of. It is after all, the number one ladies detective agency, not the number one slice of life.

Title: Three Eight One
Author: Aliya Whiteley
My Review:
At some point it becomes pretty clear that the "mysteries" being presented aren't there to be resolved. 381, corresponding to the letters cha, the strange pig like creatures, why the breathing man keeps following, the boxes with the buttons. They're just filler material with an air of meaning only meant for literary snobs to invent for themselves.

The characters are unengaging despite what could have been an interesting premise: someone from a far distant future reading a person's travelogue, trying to understand it. Instead we just get a great big nothingburger.

Title: In the Company of Cheerful Ladies (No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency, #6)
Author: Alexander McCall Smith

Title: Calypso
Author: Oliver K. Langmead
My Review:
Quite a unique book, when I first opened it I thought it was a giant poem. Thank goodness, it isn't. It's just a writing style with the lines one after the other, the author then uses that style to sort of shape the chapters and the narrative point of views. The shapes start to make sense as you go through the story and sometimes are used with amazing effect.

The story is a standard "someone's woken up from their capsule and oh no something has gone wrong" which isn't uncommon in scifi. It's the writing style and prose that make the story though, it's told in a somewhat 'odyssey' sense and feels like a fever dream at times.

Title: Hench (Hench, #1)
Author: Natalie Zina Walschots
My Review:
Unexpectedly enjoyed this, from start to finish. The main character is a flawed hench who gets to execute on a larger scale of vengeance against so called superheroes. The scheming and planning is fun to go along with and the outcomes satisfying. It maintains an air of comedy and seriousness at the same time, there's camaraderie and raw enmity together too. Best of all, nothing is predictable.

It also delivers its core message well without being on the nose about it, hero worship is endemic to us and we are willing to overlook all of its flawed outcomes and collateral damage to maintain and cling to our sense of ideals.

Title: Binti: Sacred Fire (Binti, #1.5)
Author: Nnedi Okorafor
My Review:
Look, I understand interstellar travel. Alien species. Communicating with said aliens. I'll even accept faster than light communication.

But using Fahrenheit to describe the weather, are you serious? Just agitates my hair tentacles!

Title: Binti (Binti, #1)
Author: Nnedi Okorafor
My Review: Unique and ethereal. I really like sci-fi that's almost realistic and human but one step removed into the mystical magical realm. The concepts presented such as the hair, the edan, the mathematical harmonising, that amazing ship...  were alien to me but I was able to somehow understand just enough. Really well written and very creative.

Title: An Excellent Mystery (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #11)
Author: Ellis Peters
My Review:
Probably my favourite in the series so far, I think it's one of the few in these chronicles without a murder. Masterfully written, the plot twist is actually given away early on, I think deliberately, and yet the story written around it keeps the air of the unknown going, I felt somewhat on the edge of a comfortable seat right until the end.

Although I came for the excellent mystery, I stayed for the prose. The descriptions of an English summer are so rich and imaginative, it felt like I was there and appreciating its beauty and effect on the land and people. Just reading some passages was such a pleasure I went back and read them again. Who knew that just describing some trees, overripe fruit, and fields could be so evocative.

I wonder if this is it, the peak of the series.

Title: Solaris
Author: Stanisław Lem
My Review:
Bit of a tough read but so unique and creative. It's a hard sci-fi which explores an actual alien, a truly alien alien, that defies explanation and understanding. The characters are on a planet where it's speculated that the entire ocean is the alien entity but it conforms to none of the expected standards. What even are the standards.

The characters spend quite some time in speculation and philosophy of the very concept, but without any concluding answers. Those passages are almost like an encyclopedia entry and do need patience to get through.

Title: The Night Masquerade (Binti, #3)
Author: Nnedi Okorafor
My Review:
Wow, this was a crash and burn. The series itself started with a pretty well fleshed out character, nothing over the top and nothing too bad, she actually felt and acted mature, and the world building was a delicious layer of mysticism and scifi on top of what seemed realistic, it was very refreshing.

This entry is thoroughly YA, and I mean that in the most derogatory sense. Two love interests for no reason that contributes absolutely zero to the story, check. She's clumsy but somehow supertalented, check. Angry all the time, check. Someone died... but wait they didn't actually. And that happens twice. Oh what's that, she's just gained some new power? No time to dwell on it, she's about to be handed yet another alien power because she is the special one. Towards the end it felt like she had collected pretty much every secret or alien power there was. There were way, way too many new developments stuffed into a short period of time for no good reason. It only felt rushed and muddy and was like something out of a "YA protag" checklist.

In retrospect I would recommend only reading Book 1 and then dropping the series. It's pretty good as a standalone and just imagine the 'rest of the story' yourself.

Of course each book contains one minor world building annoyance that the author seems to insert as an easter egg perhaps. In this one, we are back at a classic scenario: several alien civilizations, interstellar travel, faster than light communication... and then someone goes and quotes distances in miles. Just... no.

Title: Home (Binti, #2)
Author: Nnedi Okorafor
My Review:
I feel like the author likes to insert one micro-annoyance in each book. The last one had the use of Fahrenheit which I still haven't gotten over. In this one, they describe a house that has no doors, and shortly afterwards the protagonist is angry and slams her bedroom door. I mean, what are we to believe, that this is some sort of a magic house or something?

That aside, I'm really enjoying this series. Binti is growing a lot, and has returned to her village where she discovers a bit more about herself. The human interactions feel quite natural and straightforward, without the layer of pomp and ceremony around it, so it's an easy read.

Title: The Last Hour Between Worlds (The Echo Archives, #1)
Author: Melissa Caruso

Title: Don't Believe It
Author: Charlie Donlea
My Review:
This was going really well until about halfway, a great mystery gradually told, with important bits being uncovered, I felt like the audience of the real time documentary, it was good masterful suspense.

About halfway through, things start to fall apart after the 'big reveal'. It was pretty clear the ending as well as the circumstances of the main murder hadn't been thought through, the focus of the book was the big reveal with little more beyond it. Several bits of evidence from the initial investigation are simply forgotten in the hopes that readers don't notice it (looking at other reviews, they didn't), but if you do remember those threads then they stuck out badly.

The "solution" to this was a poorly rushed ending; when the true killer is discovered, the story takes a poor cop out and kills off the main character, so as to avoid having to think up an actual conclusion to the investigation. It's just rushed through in the hopes that readers aren't actually paying attention. Within the story, several people knew exactly where she was and not a bit of this comes up in the 'trials'? This isn't exactly like the beach murders with nobody around. It insulted whatever lack of intelligence even I have. The whole thing is just strange and felt so hand-wavy.

Title: 賭ケグルイ双 13 (Kakegurui Twin, #13)
Author: Homura Kawamoto
Publisher: スクウェア・エニックス

Title: 賭ケグルイ双 11 (Kakegurui Twin, #11)
Author: Homura Kawamoto
Publisher: スクウェア・エニックス

Title: City of Last Chances (The Tyrant Philosophers, #1)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
Very interesting setup and I liked how everything is congregated around this one town which is just packed with different mysteries and going-ons; the Reproach, gods, factions, all kinds of weirdos.

The writing I felt was quite dense so it takes longer to read and it's sometimes easy to miss something happening. But it was overall rewarding. It's definitely a departure from this same author's other stories.

The world building is really good, nothing feels over-the-top, despite all the competing and contrasting things going on, it just feels like a natural fit. The characters are gray and at the same time also fit in to the world.

Title: ケンガンアシュラ（１） (裏少年サンデーコミックス) (Japanese Edition)
Author: Sandrovich Yabako

Title: Obvious Adams: The Story of a Successful Business Man
Author: Robert Rawls Updegraff

Title: The Final Detail (Myron Bolitar, #6)
Author: Harlan Coben
My Review:
The mystery itself quite decent, how the mystery presents itself and is slowly solved.

Everything else though, was kind of meh. The characters felt like stereotypes and in some cases outright assholes, some with zero purpose... overall I found them insufferable. But they seem to be regulars in the series, which makes me think that I might not like the rest of the books. What didn't help was the too on-the-nose monologues about whichever certain topic of the day was on the author's mind. All of this combined made for odd pacing and mixed personalities; one minute there's an urgency and action, the next there is a slice of life and humorous exchanges. All of it culminating in the timeless crutch of mysteries: a long set of monologues to explain how all the mysteries tie together.

It just didn't work for me. There was not much in the way of investigating, more of sudden epiphanies and coin drops. There was also too much focus on appearances and boastful prowess or being an alpha male, which made me uncomfortable.

Title: The Orphans of Raspay (Penric and Desdemona, #7)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold

Title: Never
Author: Ken Follett
My Review:
Excellent geopolitical thriller, showing how a series of small events around the world can escalate rapidly into confrontation. The events felt realistic and well thought through, and relatable for our era, and highlighted well just how much of human history has always been little more than gang warfare behind a veil of diplomacy.

I was completely immersed in it and enjoyed most of it, some parts felt tense and hopeful and dismaying at the same time. The ending felt rushed and abrupt, but I think that might also have been a deliberate choice by the author. It's very tempting to expect some kind of unrealistic Hollywood ending, some last minute twist that's clever so that everyone can go back to normal and carry on meddling with each other, but an ending like this one is its own message.

I say enjoyed most because the interpersonal lives of the characters sucked, as did their dialogue, it was so bad it was getting in the way of the real story, no exaggeration.

At some points I couldn't tell if these people had personalities or parodies. "WiTh aLL hER heARt SHE BEliEvEd IN freEdom, dEmOCracy aNd JUstIce". On the other hand I've often heard that authors write characters that are simply a reflection of society and the way we think, so maybe it's us who are the clowns.

From start to finish I simply could not give a shit about any of their relationships or romances or situations, these aspects were a nuisance, the author should have kept them at a dispassionate distance. Use them to carry out the story, that's all.

Title: The Book That Wouldn’t Burn (The Library Trilogy, #1)
Author: Mark  Lawrence

Title: Hero Killer (히어로 킬러)
Author: Kkulbeol
My Review:
Excellent artwork, great premise, good storytelling, but one that falters as the series goes on.

The hero killer barely does any killing.

In fact, barely anyone dies here. Even when they appear to have died, they haven't.

Everyone seems to strut about overflowing with confidence in their knowledge and power, and attack on the slightest provocation. It gets boring pretty quickly.

It's the artwork and action scenes doing all the heavy lifting.

Title: Recursion
Author: Blake Crouch
My Review:
Read the full review here

Interesting premise exploring memories, time travel and making us think about what we perceive as reality. It starts several threads about separate people that are tied together quite well. The first half felt quite 'natural' in its progression.

The second half felt strange to me, there's sudden forced relationship melodrama between two of the characters and it is duller than bricks; I felt no connection or care for it, but it dominated most of the storytelling, all while the author upped the cringe factor as they dodge swat teams and nuclear armageddon.

Title: Pattern Recognition (Blue Ant, #1)
Author: William Gibson
My Review:
This reads like "Ready Player One" but with pretentious people.

The story is written in a present-kitschy-tense and is absolutely inundated, flooded, with poorly aged or lost and meaningless brand names, not to mention a desperate attempt at flaunting knowledge about Japanese place names and culture...

The author has convinced themselves that doing is all very sophisticated, but all they achieve is an anachronistic cringe fest and takes away from any actual story being told.

Title: Demon Copperhead
Author: Barbara Kingsolver
My Review:
It was a slog, reading through chapter after chapter of Demon down in the dumps in different ways. The initial opening is quite good though, but rapidly loses its magic. There are occasional hints of interesting characters or potential events but nothing really pans out, which arguably could be part of the whole setting and atmosphere.

In the end I didn't feel it had been worth sticking around to finding out how he ends up, it was as unremarkable as the rest of the events. The only thing that keeps it going is the nice writing style, just there isn't much of a story. I did however enjoy poisonwood bible a lot, I'd recommend that.

Title: Ascendance of a Bookworm: Part 5 Volume 2
Author: Miya Kazuki
My Review:
A struggle to read after taking a break of a few years. There are so many characters and retainers and duchies and threads that it's hard to keep track.

The gist of the story was understandable though, some bits just flew by me.

I did however remember my age old complaint about the series: there's not that much about books or bookworm like behaviour. However, the story is in its final (very long) arc so the series might get interesting.

Title: The Rook (The Checquy Files, #1)
Author: Daniel O'Malley
My Review:
This book could have been really good, but it's painfully clear that the author knows nothing about the UK but is somehow intent on using a British setting from some bizarro universe.

Conspiracy theories I can forgive, secret societies, magical powers, teleportation, all of that. But portraying Brits as a bunch of Americans crosses the line.

The story is set in London, but it’s full of mistakes that make it hard to enjoy. Characters tip everywhere, which isn’t common in the UK, and the main character keeps talking about tipping, a bit too much. There’s a freezer full of Lean Cuisines, which isn’t typical either. There are phrases like being "sent down to Wales," a geographic impossibility in London, and the fact that nobody says that. Also, people here don’t describe others as "Arab-Britons" or "Anglo-Saxons." These are derivatives of a very specific Americanism, one that I find uncomfortable and unwelcome.

These self-inserts are distracting and make the characters seem American, not British. In fact, the entire country seems to be full of Americans saying American things and doing American things. I wish the setting were US based so that I wasn't constantly being taken out of the immersion.

To add to the distraction, there is a lot of infodumping. There's so much infodumping that there are characters who have been brought in for the express purpose of being additional infodumpers to add on to the infodumping, and nothing else. About midway through the book there is a sudden veer in the direction of the plot which just appears out of nowhere and nowhy.

The story has potential, there's some nice world building and premise that could exist here, I'm genuinely still trying to look forward to see what happens, but these errors and bizarre directions ruin the experience.

Another 'quality' Goodreads choice award.

Other notes:

* Lead mining was in decline in the 1700s. Nobody was being 'sent to the mines' then.
* "I'm switchin' the cameras to night vision" said a nerd with a thick Cockney accent. Are you serious.
* Sidewalk, blueberry pancakes, cell phone, couch... what??

Title: The Desert of Souls (The Chronicles of Sword and Sand #1)
Author: Howard Andrew Jones
My Review:
I enjoyed this more than I expected to. It's a simply written and linearly narrated mild fantasy adventure.

It's a refreshing departure from the standard fantasy, instead of being set in the usual alt-medieval-Britain, it's set in 8th century Iraq and Empty Quarter, so a lot of the journey, conversations, actions and motivations are quite different than you'd expect. The occasional aphorism isn't too bad either.

"it is ever simpler to be kind to individuals than to groups."

The characters are likeable, in their actions and observations, and nobody too overbearing or cliched. Overall a fun and simple adventure in a not that common location for fantasies.

Title: The Archive Undying (The Downworld Sequence, #1)
Author: Emma Mieko Candon
My Review:
I'm convinced that this tub of word coleslaw is a deliberate attempt at making some readers question their own literary comprehension skills and for others to revel in their confusion, draping themselves entirely in the emperor's new clothes.

There is a lot of potential for good world building and well written characters here, but the author instead chooses to adopt a "oh, do you not know?" approach to descriptions, and perpetuate pointless plot points based entirely on two people not talking to each other.

Title: Mammoths at the Gates (The Singing Hills Cycle, #4)
Author: Nghi Vo

Title: Like a Mighty Army (Safehold, #7)
Author: David Weber
My Review:
Not terrible, definitely kept me interested for more.

I'm no longer able to keep track of the characters and have to rely on contextual clues to figure out which side they're on.

I had hoped that the move from naval warfare to land would make it more understandable to me, sadly it turns out there's a world of terminology here that are new to me too, that was interesting in its own way.

There are a lot of other simultaneous threads going on around the world, and we're at book 7. I'm interested in continuing to see where this goes as related to the original premise.

The world building is expansive as ever and feels well thought out. I just hope the author isn't caught up in it and unable to move on from it.

Title: The Brides of High Hill (The Singing Hills Cycle, #5)
Author: Nghi Vo
My Review: Something different this time. It's a bit of a mystery and not much involving the usual storytelling. It still works out well.

Title: The Frugal Wizard’s Handbook for Surviving Medieval England (Secret Projects, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
It is certainly an interesting premise and well presented in the first half. Details about the world as well as the protagonist's past are drip fed to keep things interesting. But, as this person slowly regains their memories it turns out they're actually a very mixed and inconsistent. They're a great fighter but also a coward but also timid but also brave but also dumb but also clever.

The plot is a bit jumbled up too, as are the revelations and the rushed story threads introduced.

What seem like would be significant plot points simply pass by in a blink. There are contrived manufactured situations for trivial purposes for no good reason (Johnny antagonizes another person on purpose and then gets upset when the person is successfully antagonized. That's just asshole behaviour).

The romance is forced and pointless. A mysterious old lady is revealed and suddenly everyone knows about her. It's small bits like this that really let the entire story down, even though the other parts including world building, the mystery, comedy, are well done.

OK/decent overall.

Title: 伊藤潤二傑作集３ 双一の勝手な呪い
Author: Junji Ito

Title: Tears of the Giraffe (No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency, #2)
Author: Alexander McCall Smith
My Review: Another nice cozy mystery, and it manages to go surprisingly some distance into the morality things and just how messy life can be even if you live by a set of rules.

Title: The Kalahari Typing School for Men (No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency, #4)
Author: Alexander McCall Smith
My Review:
Best entry in the series so far. The characters have developed and matured since the first book, and there is a sense of progress in general, in career and lives and thinking.

There is a deep affection for Botswana that shines through in their appreciation for what's labelled the old ways, small conversations, the sky, the land, the little observations and the philosophies they lead to. It makes for good comfort and wholesome reading.

I think it could have been done with a little more detective work, although the numerous threads seem to have tied together really well and so naturally I barely noticed. It does remain to be seen if the theme of the 'group of friends' is what dominates or if it's the detective work, or a balance of both.

Title: Morality for Beautiful Girls (No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency, #3)
Author: Alexander McCall Smith

Title: The No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency (No. 1 Ladies' Detective Agency, #1)
Author: Alexander McCall Smith
My Review:
I'm always pleased when I find a rare unexpected gem like this one. I go in not knowing anything, and occasionally find something I didn't realise I'd enjoy. I think it's a nice way to approach books.

The story has quite a few things going for it. The main one is that it's set in Botswana, a different land and people than I usually read about. There aren't the usual tropes and trends that I'd expect from a western setting so that alone gives it a fresh feeling. I also learned some of the terminology that looked similar but had differing references: Botswana the country; Motswana, a person; Batswana the people, Setswana the language.

The story itself is a detective novel yes, but it's not a sherlock set in Africa, it's its own presentation. Interspersed with the detective work are slice of life stories of various characters. It gives them a certain weight along the journey. It gives a glimpse into the daily lives, the mundane, the peoples, their thoughts, fears, and motivations.

Most of all I liked the pride that the people had in Botswana, they expressed their love for their country without it coming across as nationalistic.

Overall well presented detective/slice of life/cozy mixture.

Author: Iori Miyazawa

Title: The Women
Author: Kristin Hannah
My Review:
Human: You are a writing assistant I found on AliExpress. You will help generate a story outline for a book called The Women. The aim of the book is to be generically appealing enough, and to masquerade as a sweeping faux-epic, that it will net a goodreads choice award from people who can't tell good writing from a butterfly, like the meme (if they could read this they'd be mad). Actually, they might not even be able to tell that this is a novel, so please append "a novel" to the title so it is clear it is a novel.

Despite the misleadingly pluralised title, it needs to be mostly about one woman, the protagonist. Ensure that she has zero personality, attributes, morals, and motivations, so that her narcissistic shallowness can act as a self insert for readers.

Her primary skill should be standing around looking helpless and sorry for herself so that everyone is compelled to assist her and hand her plot devices on silver platters. Every man must fall in love with her and every woman must be her best friend, ready to drop everything and assist her in every way possible. Naturally, she must not reciprocate or help others, she exists only to be served.

To make her relatable to modern audiences, portray her with the vibes of an "Instagram influencer before her time, on an egotourism holiday"; have her act as a saviour to the hapless village people of the country she is in. Their existential plight as props is inconsequential against her need to virtue signal her sadness for the orphans. Similarly, the issues around the effect of wartime on people and psyches are to be given less emphasis next to her need to lurch from one farcically contrived soap opera melodrama to the next shoehorned romance.

Apply generous doses of plot armour so there is never a sense of danger or conflict. However we do need to showcase a sense of grittiness, so remind readers of the smell of shit when there is a need to walk around the camp. Shit is grit.

To achieve the appearance of a sweeping epic, the story must cram together every war story cliché imaginable. It would be very helpful if the passages were written like a screenplay, to ensure ease of adaptation and of course future royalties from the trite movie that Hollywood generates from it.

Assistant:

Title: A Short Walk Through a Wide World
Author: Douglas Westerbeke
My Review:
A great premise wasted in favour of pseudo intellectual nothing burgers.

The main character is interesting enough in how she encounters and begins her journeys. Almost everything after that seems like it's leading towards a resolution or even a minor little thread being tied up, but nothing. Nothing of note or resolution really happens. That's pretty much the biggest disappointment.

I kept wondering if this was trying to be the next "The Alchemist" in its sludgey porridge of truisms, trying to appeal to a very similar audience of the easily influenced.

The characters met along the way seem interesting but the writing suffers from Hollywood-tropey forced romantic plot tumour, she is literally unable to meet someone that's just a platonic friend. It gets overdone and boring quickly.

The one person she does meet, who has some insight and where it looks like something of consequence might happen... is quickly taken care of by also abandoning that thread abruptly.

Title: Elder Race
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
I've always felt that the author isn't very good at ending a series, everything tends to fall apart or lose momentum in the third book. But they're really good at new and interesting scenarios and ideas, if only they could keep it short. This is the first non trilogy by this author, and I think they might be good at standalone entries.

A post tech society exists on a colonial world and are dimly aware of the ancestors who are of course very high tech. Lyn needs their help and the story basically covers their perspectives on their journey, how they fail to understand each other and lack confidence in themselves.

Not a long book and I thought it was solid.

Title: Gibbet Hill
Author: Bram Stoker
Additional Authors: Brian Cleary, Paul Murray, Roddy Doyle, Paul McKinley

Title: The Familiar
Author: Leigh Bardugo
My Review:
Romantrashy set in 16th century Spain, but the setting is of little consequence, as the story's focus is a series of insufferable characters, each one more insufferable than the next.

The people in this book seem to be incapable of holding a simple conversation, where instead each line is delivered as a quip, threat or barbed insult. It gets tiresome quickly.

The main character exists in a state of knowing nothing yet conveniently knowing exactly what needs to be known when the story needs it, while everyone else becomes a delivery mechanism for whatever dilemma our plucky heroine needs to suffer next.

Title: The Travelling Cat Chronicles
Author: Hiro Arikawa
My Review:
It's short and well written, starts out as a simple road trip, a guy and his cat, visiting various places and people. A very well behaved cat. How is that even possible. Anyway.

As it progresses, the story as well as aspects of various relationships reveals itself, mostly from the cat's perspective, and comes to a pretty satisfying conclusion.

However the best part is the sarcastic derision with which the cat explains and observes things, while still managing to convey affection. That's good writing.

Title: A View from the Stars: Stories and Essays
Author: Cixin Liu

Title: The Silent Patient
Author: Alex Michaelides
My Review:
I'm so glad the author found it necessary to evaluate each character's attractiveness, because it's a good idea to portray and reinforce notions of attractive people as good and ugly people as bad.

Except that doesn't work too well here, because every character is basically an asshole and hates everyone else. Even the 'friendships' shown are antagonistic.

The 'professions' are so bad it's verging on comedy, the way they monologue, the way these 'professional' behave with each other and discuss things, the way they analyze people, it's all from a corny TV script (which might be the end goal here (just checked IMDB, turns out there is some shitshow in development)) desperate to craft a memorable quote...

"lOVE tHAT DOeSN't InCLuDe hOnesTY doESN't DESeRVE tO Be Called loVe"

Author: Becky Chambers

Title: The Will of the Many (Hierarchy, #1)
Author: James  Islington
My Review:
Really interesting world building, there are bits of it that are relayed at a time, its effects seen or demonstrated in various ways. The writing and storyline is quite readable and can be more-ish, there are enough twists and revelations throughout that makes you want to know more about the world as well as continue the story and find resolutions.

Make no mistake. This is young adult, through and through. While the writing is good, the dialogue can be terrible. Especially when our special snowflake is put into a 'school' atmosphere and now has to contend with dozens of other snowflakes, cliques, and a constant obsession with rankings, and the special snowflake is revealed to have all these bits of knowledge and languages and skills that very few others have.

In fairness there are more often well thought out and dramatic-without-being-cheesy scenarios, there are the occasional supercringe dialogues or dumbass actions that the protagonist engages in for no good reason other than the author seemingly couldn't find a better way out. Those stupid moments mar what's otherwise a not that terrible YA novel.

Retrospectively, I would have waited for more books in the series before starting with this one as the conclusion is kind of 'meh', but the story does make me want to continue.

Title: Children of Memory (Children of Time, #3)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
After having read a number of books by this author I'm now convinced that they cannot handle book#3s in a series. They always start really strong with an interesting premise, there's a decent follow up that kind of lags but isn't terrible. Then the third which for some reason needs to delve into the metaphysical and abstract trying to differentiate itself.

This third entry, like other third entries, sucks. It's such a pointless slog as it tries to appear mysterious and ephemeral.

The author seems to have forgotten what made each of the other stories so interesting. It's not that there are aliens, or strange stuff is happening. It's that there are a group of individuals trying to figure it out and you're taken on a journey of discovery with them. Here, there is no discovery, just an unending set of people being mysterious.

Title: Children of Ruin (Children of Time, #2)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review: It was a bit of a struggle to keep up with the multiple threads going on, and their completely different ways of thinking. There's humans, spiders, Kern, octopus and ooze. Each one with a different communication and thinking. A lot of history has happened by the time they got here, with those threads to follow. It got a bit confusing towards the end as a result. I think I've seen a similar situation in the Architects series but the same author. It gets a bit metaphysical and turns into a slog. We do get there eventually. On to the next "adventure" then.

Title: Children of Time (Children of Time, #1)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
Didn't think I'd like it this much. I last read it 7 years ago, and it was 'good' then, but I had forgotten most of it. I just re-read it, and somehow I was getting excited to find out what happens next. The science is hard and at times difficult to follow but making the effort to go back and follow it is rewarding.

It's a very intersting perspective on evolution and the interaction of species, it goes into misunderstandings, language, perspectives, orientation, society, genetic expression. Just about everything.

Title: Midst Toil and Tribulation (Safehold, #6)
Author: David Weber
My Review:
Enjoyed this one, for once the battle was on land rather than the sea. I thought that might make it easier for me to understand the jargon, but nope, I still had to spend time summarizing and looking up definitions.

Still pretty exciting, the 'evolution' of war and the strategy employed. I'm hoping that the story can make some greater strides and actually move towards the next stage, but I do still like the somewhat slow pace between all the detailed descriptions of progress.

A thought did occur to me... might be an oversight or simplification or something being saved for later. With all these amazingly intelligent people, each one able to think beyond their circumstances, it's odd that there are no atheists.

Title: Off Armageddon Reef (Safehold, #1)
Author: David Weber
My Review:
It's a really interesting mix of science fiction and fantasy, dressed up as a historical fiction, with many isekai themes. And best of all it's also got a theme of "forgotten" history.

The world building is vast and detailed, and spans hundreds of years. There are a lot of people and places mentioned. You absolutely need to have its map open alongside to get a good idea of where the people are and what they're up to. The people's names can get confusing as well, as they are names we'd recognize today but spelled different to indicate a vowel and pronunciation shift; my advice there would be to subvocalize or even vocalize some of the names so that they make sense.

With these points and tools in mind, the story can be really enjoyable; the buildup, the bits of history, the mixtures of science fiction in the fantasy world, and ideologies are really well woven together.

Without these, I think I can see why many reviewers didn't like it, there are indeed a lot of names and a lot of places, and this isn't meant to be a casual read at all. Put the time and effort towards it, and it will reward you.

In my case I moved from reading it on an ereader to straight on the computer; I had the book open on one monitor, the map open on another, and a local LLM helping me understand a lot of the nautical phrases and terminology.

Title: The Seven Husbands of Evelyn Hugo
Author: Taylor Jenkins Reid
My Review:
I think this would be a good read if you're already interested in Hollywood and celebrity culture. Without that context — if you aren't "into" Hollywood, movies, and popculture/celebs — it's a pretty bland story that does more telling than showing. I got the feeling that I was missing out on parts that I'm supposed to be starry eyed with.

The lesson I've taken from this is that a Goodreads Choice Award is about as meaningful and relevant as the Oscars the vapid characters were venerating.

Title: The Gate of the Feral Gods (Dungeon Crawler Carl, #4)
Author: Matt Dinniman
My Review:
A huge improvement over the previous in the series; there's good character development as well as the chaos and shenanigans that go with the group of crawlers. In terms of storytelling the author is finding his feet quite well now and there is a lot stuffed in here. It did occur to me that if I had a gap in between the books, I'd have completely lose the chain of events and wouldn't remember who or what is who or what.

The story's weak point is once again the structure of the 'dungeons'. The author keeps trying to scale dungeons in which each floor's events take place but it's not always easy to follow. That said, this entry was easier to follow than the previous as it was enough to understand that they were in the sand area or water area, etc. But not much more than that, and it was still a tangled mess.

I'm still sticking with the series because it's not that terrible, but not looking forward to another complicated layout, if there is one. I've seen this handled in similar books with helpful diagrams throughout the pages (as opposed to just the beginning), as the scenes shift, which helps orient the reader.

Title: The Dungeon Anarchist's Cookbook (Dungeon Crawler Carl, #3)
Author: Matt Dinniman
My Review:
Far too much time wasted on the confusing and difficult to imagine train system. It's sort of handwaved away which made me wonder, why even spend time on all this pointless exposition.

Not enough on the story itself and the humour and characters which is what made the series endearing. Still, I'll try out the next book.

Title: House of Salt and Sorrows (Sisters of the Salt, #1)
Author: Erin A. Craig
My Review:
Tries to be a mystery, tries to be a horror, fails miserably at both.

The only interesting thread of intrigue in this entire mess is the investigation into the mysteries which were somehow always interrupted by clichéd dismissals (no time for that now!) (or the braindead MC bringing it up in the middle of another important event), chuckles (what a silly thing you have just said, I shall now chuckle and dismiss it and refuse to listen further), and contrived, forced outbursts from the accompanying one dimensions characters whose only purpose seems to be spending time looking at party clothes, which the book describes in excruciatingly torturous minutiae.

I gave it the benefit of the doubt and assumed these interruptions were all part of a larger conspiracy, but no, the story was deliberately doing anything except look at the actual plot. It didn't help that the main character is portrayed as a scatterbrain prone to hysterics, and the eventual 'deus-explanation' had to be spoonfed by an antagonist for no reason other than "welp, might as well tell you what's going on".

I judged a book by its cover and was deservingly punished for it.

Title: The Priory of the Orange Tree (The Roots of Chaos, #1)
Author: Samantha Shannon
My Review:
A really interesting premise and a solid first half, let down by a weak and rushed second half.

The world seems to be quite well done and there are a lot of 'factions', each one with their own motivations and histories. The characters are really well written too, I didn't find any of them annoying or too cliched. Even the antagonists, I liked.

Some of the details don't make sense at the beginning but little bits of the context is revealed as the story progresses, and lends itself towards some really good world building. It is interwoven nicely with the plot and impending crisis.

Around the halfway mark, the plot seems to lose coherence, and in the last quarter, just about everything seemed rushed. I couldn't decide if this book was too long, or too short. At many times it felt like the author was writing for a TV show rather than a book.
