Title: Babel
Author: R.F. Kuang
My Review:
It's an alternate history with a light sprinkling of fantasy on top. The fantasy parts are based on language and etymology, and through that the book spends a decent chunk of time talking about words and their origins, but delivered in an engaging way.

The characters are varied, from different backgrounds, and it's great to see the dichotomy that they carry around, living in a place where they are accepted but don't feel like they belong, where they understand the implications of yet participate in a system that they don't agree with. Through this story I saw several parallels to our own current society, which makes it interesting to relate to, and realize, we haven't changed that much!

Despite delivering lectures and philosophizing on the moral implications of their actions at the drop of a hat, none of the people in the book feel like cardboard cutouts, everyone seems to have their own backgrounds and motivations; nobody feels like a terrible person despite the interpersonal conflicts which thankfully aren't over-the-top.

The setting is somewhat based on Oxford, the romanticized Oxford of the before times. The setting of the Babel institute feels symbolic and is a constant presence throughout the book, and if you squint you can make out that same symbolism throughout events in the story.

Wholly recommended, but remember to read slowly.

Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
But why are they insects, I just kept wondering that the whole time. And why would some of them be flies, it's kind of gross. But I assume this is done as substitutes for races or nations.

I like the idea of a looming threat that nobody believes, and the characters are still good. The fighting scenes are a drag though and so are the interpersonal relationships. Might still give the sequel a try.

Title: The Sanctuary Sparrow (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael #7)
Author: Ellis Peters
My Review:
The author's prose for this Brother Cadfael series is unlike any other I've come across. The sentences are dense with vocabulary but manage to efficiently convey a wealth of meaning. I have to read these slowly so as to not miss important bits, and I don't mind.

Also enjoyable are the descriptions of the environments that the various characters are in, it's quite evocative and lends an air of reality to the 12th century murder-mystery settings. This 7th in the series was quite enjoyable because there were a set of seemingly disconnected threads that are seamlessly woven together to form a coherent whole. It happened so naturally but at the same time I could see it taking shape, and got excited for it.

Title: Bliss Montage
Author: Ling  Ma
My Review:
"Bliss Montage" tries so hard to be pretentious, it comes in the form of a popup book where each page turn results in a sip of tea with a pinky finger permanently raised.

The entire focus of the short stories seems to be on trying to be as aloof from any hint of a coherent thread; as though any semblance of a narrative direction would be so jejune, and may get sneered upon by postulant goodreads charlatans for having the very audacity.

The scattered puzzle pieces of dross yarn, masquerading as belletristic conte, did not even have the courtesy of forming a coherent picture.

Reading through these felt like trudging through waters as deep as its contents — so lacking in depth, it only succeeded in producing the effect of a dampened sock.

If you're looking to fall into a deep coma of literary excitement, this book is the berceuse you seek.

Title: The Betrayed (The Dawning of Muirwood, #3)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
With the amount of talking and guiding and nudging and whispering and voicing the medium did this time, they should have just made it the main character.

Maybe even given it a nickname like "Crutch" because of the way the entire story seemed to lean on it for solutions to just about any problem.

Or maybe call it "Simon" because the so called protagonist's entire set of actions is a game of Simon Says.

Title: The Wise Man's Fear (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #2)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review:
aka: Harem Potter and the Chamber of Wish Fulfilment

This series was doing so well. The first book has our protagonist struggling through life, always just managing to get by whatever circumstances have been thrown his way. He got by on his wits and his skill alone.

This second book starts the same way. And it sets the same level of expectations, but then a few things happen.

Our protagonist spend almost all of his time moping over the woman who has put him in the friend zone. He is a champion of the friend zone and revels in it and absolutely loves it He has actually convinced himself how special his place is in this magical friendzone of this beautiful girl Denna who goes through men like Kvothe doesn't go through underwear.



Also she has this mysterious power which allows her to randomly disappear and reappear conveniently in different cities on the continent, even isolated hamlets, where Kvothe just happens to be.

Meanwhile he is also this amazing guy whom every woman has taken a shine to, but of course he doesn't even realize it! As he often says, he knows nothing about women.

Right. But that's OK, a bit of misplaced attention as a teenager in love and a bit of attention for our cute, pretty, oblivious protagonist.

One can live with that. The story moves on. He goes out into the world, has a bit of an adventure, defeats some bandits.

And that's where we witness the literary form of "jumping the shark."



He meets a super nympho and nymphs her for several chapters,



meets an all knowing entity,



gains powers,



travels to a distant land of mysterious warrior people with strange customs



and free love,



passes their test of courage,



gains the respect of his teacher,



and sleeps with her of course, gains a sword, dallies with every woman he meets along the way, kills a troupe, saves women, gets rich, becomes famous... You get the idea.

Basically it turns into every generic story theme that's ever been told in fairytales for alpha-male simpletons. Powers have been handed to him. He doesn't have to struggle or work for anything. This is not the same storyline or protagonist you've started with. It's like the author got bored or couldn't figure out how to write the story of his progress, how to get him to where he is today. Instead, use a shark, jump over it, and veer off into another direction as you please.



Of course he's still in the friend zone of this one girl. No reason to change that.



It's probably the only thing left which should retain interest in the third novel.

Not all was bad, though. The author's writing is great and really sucks you in. Even a mediocre paragraph was made eloquent by his skill. Just that the poor storyline became so blatant and obvious that it distracted from the immersiveness and was no longer bearable. It was so unbearable that the 4-star rating that I felt at the beginning became a 1-star at the end for the sake of propriety.

tl;dr: This was a fantasy series which was promising to be unlike any other, only to fall back to old tricks and generic plotlines.

Author: Syougo Kinugasa

Title: Classroom of the Elite: Year 2 (Light Novel) Vol. 5
Author: Syougo Kinugasa
My Review:
A fresh return back to the original class. The main part of the story, the suspenseful mind game parts, takes place in a single classroom. It's fantastically written, with a few important threads from the past coming to a head.

I liked most of all that the conclusion was not foregone, nor was it expected, nor was it happy, and yet flowed naturally.

Title: The Thursday Murder Club (Thursday Murder Club, #1)
Author: Richard Osman
My Review:
Actually enjoyed this quite a bit. The premise is really interesting, a group of quirky pensioners in a retirement home solving mysteries. It's great watching them at work, each personality injecting a bit of humour and charm to each scene. It was enjoyable watching them at work. The setting is England and comes with all its charms of regular life.

I think the overall writing could have done with some trimming. There are too many characters, not all relevant. If was kind of difficult keeping up with the several perspective shifts. But the final part of the story where everything was supposed to be explained, got quite confusing and I think the author was trying too hard to make it cinematic. It really could have done with a straightforward explanation.

Overall enjoyable and I'm going to try another in the series.

Title: The Farthest Shore (Earthsea Cycle, #3)
Author: Ursula K. Le Guin
My Review:
What's wrong?
Dunno.
Where are we going?
Dunno.
How will we get there?
Dunno.
Vague mysticism and pretend allegorical events for >150 pages.
Done now.

Title: Wanderers
Author: Chuck Wendig
My Review: This would make a great anime because it's got so much pointless filler material.

Title: IN KOREAN WILDS AND VILLAGES.
Author: Sten (trans Frederic Whyte). Bergman
My Review:
Unexpectedly enjoyable, I found this on the Internet Archive as it's in the public domain now.

It's basically a travel tourism blog from the 1930s, before tourism was a thing, and before travel blogs were far more common as they are today. A Swedish man makes his way on the trans Siberian express, and stays a while in Korea.

He collects various species of birds, and in his travels, records his observations of Korean people and customs and culture. It's certainly a different telling compared to what we know of it today: the peninsula was still united, it was under Japanese occupation, and the economy was greatly agricultural. It's a far cry from the modern Korea that comes to mind.

The telling is very matter of fact and sometimes unfiltered (but reflective of common attitudes of the time) and the author doesn't offer personal opinions frequently which is quite refreshing. Still, it's quite clear just how much he was appreciating the beauty of the country side.

Because it was the early days of tourism (not even mass tourism), his travels were a kind of a big deal, he was able to get many people to pose for photographs, which are included in the book.

The author's hobby is bird collecting and he spends time in between describing his finds. There were a few passages where he describes some hunting trips... which doesn't hold the same prestige today that it might once have, but those passages are skippable.

It felt quite relatable to see that even back then, people liked the idea of travelling, and travellers, and photography, and hobbies. We see the past with a distant lens, but reading something like this made quite clear just how similar we are.

I'm very glad to have found this, it would have been another interesting memoir lost to time and I'd be none the wiser. It also makes me wonder what other gems I might be missing.

Title: Eden* They Were Only Two, On The Planet
Author: minori

Title: Harrow the Ninth (The Locked Tomb, #2)
Author: Tamsyn Muir
My Review:
The story does not exactly pick up from the first book and instead presents a very confusing set of events where nobody knows what is going on, and nothing is explained to the reader. Which is normally fine, it's a writing tool after all; except this carries on for most of the book. And the payoff is not worth it.

There's a rich vocabulary which can be enjoyable in its own way. What isn't enjoyable is excessive usage of archaic synonyms which lend nothing at all to the overall story, and are being used for the sake of being used. And still, doesn't make up for a poor story.

It's like the author decided to take the best parts of the first book (good characters, setting, storytelling) and delete them. Then take the worst parts and dial it up to stratospheric feculence.

Title: Mr. Churchill's Secretary (Maggie Hope Mystery, #1)
Author: Susan Elia MacNeal
My Review: This was so bad, I'm surprised it's not a Goodreads Choice Award winner.

Title: Doomsday Match (The Dresden Codex, #1)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review: Overall pretty weak. There are periods of repetition, and certain convenient coincidental plot points are telegraphed so far in advance it might as well be a prequel. I only gave it an extra star for references to Promised Neverland and Undertale.

Title: ようこそ実力至上主義の教室へ 2年生編4.5 [Youkoso Jitsuryoku Shijou Shugi no Kyoushitsu e 2nd Year 4.5]
Author: Syougo Kinugasa
Additional Authors: 衣笠彰梧, Tomoseshunsaku, トモセシュンサク

Title: Lords of Uncreation (The Final Architecture #3)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
I'm not convinced this is a good ending to the series at all. The first part of the book is padded with irrelevant and inconsequential filler material. It's the same tired route of humanity's factions turning on each other yet again, until there's yet again the external threat.

The scenes in the "unspace" are too metaphysical to be interesting, and I think the attempted descriptions of the action in this place where things "are" but not really, are difficult to follow. The frequency with which they are entering and being pulled out of that place to deal with yet more inconsequential filler turned the book into a slog.

What's worse is how utterly useless everyone else becomes in the face of the external unspace metaphysical threat, they are pretty much just standing around as the author struggles to find stuff for them to fill the pages. It doesn't help their case that there are a huge number of characters and species (often poorly explained) that are interspersed and interacting.

Idris the lone hero is very conveniently ignored so that he can do his thing. But the absolute silliest, stupidest part was when the "great voice" starts speaking to them and Kris uses her lawyer skills to argue with omnisentient beings who so far have been thinking beyond human thought but are now suddenly caught in a shitty word trap as they hand wave away all explanations. Really.

Overall this should have been a two part series and the mystery not dragged out so much. The answers behind the mysteries are weak and in many cases not worth the effort it took to get there.

Title: Ascendance of a Bookworm: Part 5 Volume 1
Author: Miya Kazuki
My Review:
A weak start to the latest arc. A lot of nothing happens, everyone becomes even busier, and revel in being overworked, everyone passes all their classes, everything is good.

Very little in the way of actual progress with the bookworm. I think the passages are now a lot harder to follow as the number of characters are increasing without any real purpose. This story could do with an editor.

Title: The Glass Hotel
Author: Emily St. John Mandel
My Review:
It's a bit difficult to decide.

The writing itself, the prose, is very good, there is an semi-ethereal writing style for every character which is compelling to follow, and I kept wanting to know what happened next.

The overall story itself though, is messy. There is a lot going on, there are a lot of characters, several different PoVs, and there are a lot of intersecting threads (almost too many coincidences)... but they don't necessarily mesh well. Some of the bits are abrupt, but explained later, and some are not.

Still an interesting read and it goes well with the author's style. The author's best is still Sea of Tranquility, this is probably skippable.

Title: The Hunted (The Dawning of Muirwood, #2)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
Nice easy continuation in the series. Not a huge amount happens but it is significant progress. The main character Eileann definitely grows as do her friends.

The romantic subplot is unnecessary and forced. Sadly it was to the point of silliness as she behaved inconsistently for the sake of that ass Hoel. I think authors need to understand, if there is a boy and a girl, they don't have to get together. It's OK to treat them as two separate entities.

Title: Tower of Babylon
Author: Ted Chiang
My Review: An imaginative re-telling of the Tower of Babylon story, from a different perspective with a different outcome.  It's short and amusing and interesting.

Title: Stories of Your Life and Others
Author: Ted Chiang

Title: Fugitive Telemetry (The Murderbot Diaries, #6)
Author: Martha Wells
My Review: Short and back to the classic, weird format of the first few in the series.

Title: Vicious (Villains, #1)
Author: V.E. Schwab
My Review:
Actually not bad for a young-adult novel; the pacing is quick, and the story wastes no time on melodrama, thank you author! The characters are well defined, and importantly their backstories and motivations are explained well.

It's definitely not a cookie cutter setup of good vs evil, instead both Victor and Eli, and their friends, sit firmly in that gray area. The name of the series is therefore quite fitting; they could all be considered villains after all.

The format of chapters alternating between past and present was slightly confusing at first, but then clicked together quite well just a few chapters in.

Title: Heaven's River (Bobiverse, #4)
Author: Dennis E. Taylor
My Review:
The author is using this book to set up one or possibly more ongoing series in the Bobiverse. And to do that, there are multiple plot sub-stories happening at the same time.

As a result, there's too much happening, and none of the stories get the attention they deserve, the outcome isn't great. There are multiple PoVs, and each character is also context switching all the time. I do enough context switching at work, and if I wanted more of that I'd just work more. Here it just becomes tiring.

The Quinlan part of the story was the most interesting to me, but it quickly became repetitive and then just dragged. It was padded with lots of pointless filler material.

Finally, the ending was just rushed. It felt like the Quinlan part was a backdrop to get various other stories and events in place, after which it was time to just 'wrap up' and start working on the next book.

None of the 'magic' of the previous 3 books was present here, but I'll take a chance and hold out for the next in the series.

Title: All My Darkest Impulses (House of Crows, #1)
Author: Lisa Unger
My Review:
The story itself is interesting. It's a story with flashbacks to explain some the pasts of some of the people involved, and slowly uncovering a mystery. The flashbacks are interspersed with the present day narrative and the switching back and forth is sometimes confusing.

I also cannot see why each book is so short. The whole series ought to be combined into one. In assuming this is related to some statistics based sales optimization, though it doesn't help with the flow of narration.

Title: Love the Way You Lie (House of Crows, #4)
Author: Lisa Unger

Title: Song of the Forever Rains (Mousai, #1)
Author: E.J. Mellow
My Review:
The book starts out well. There's somewhat interesting world building. There's a decent protagonist, with an interesting family, especially the sisters. The story is overall engaging too, but only the first half.

It then gets railroaded by the unnecessary, pointless romance in every way. The villain became a mediocre villain and was reduced to a mediocre ending. Several plot points and the magic system simply lost coherency. The formerly interesting sisters became a comic relief role which was the biggest disappointment for me.

Title: Invisible Planets: Contemporary Chinese Science Fiction in Translation
Author: Ken Liu

Title: The End of Everything (Astrophysically Speaking)
Author: Katie  Mack
My Review:
This book covers various end-of-universe scenarios that could occur, along with the science, concepts and explanations behind them. In doing so, this book also manages to naturally cover a lot of concepts from physics and cosmology, and shows how important it is to understand the beginnings of the universe in order to understand the endings.

What's refreshing is that it also includes a lot of the more recent discoveries and observations including dark matter and the observation of the Higg's boson. This was a great tour of the culmination of knowledge of our understanding of the universe, and if you have any interest in popular science I'd recommend this.

It was also quite sobering to realize how little we know about dark matter itself, and how much hand waving goes on around it. At least this spurred me to go and read more about it, only to realize that it's just a whole lot of us hand waving.

Title: The Exiled Fleet (The Divide, #2)
Author: J.S. Dewes
My Review:
The author does a good job of building an interesting universe, but the story is brought down by a set of characters who can only interact with each other using a limited, repetitive set of facial animations, and for some reason it's mostly centered around the jaw.

---

"Void, Rake, not again!" Cavalon ground his teeth.

Mesa quirked an eyebrow.

Rake clenches her jaw, "This is the only way."

Jackin quirks an eyebrow "Only to do what?"

Cavalon, jaws flexing, "She's martyring herself for the 2nd time in this book!"

"Void, Rake, this is getting tiresome" Jackin glowered.

"See?" Cavalon retorted, cheeks ablaze.

Mesa quirked her eyebrow above her overlarge eyes, "Excubitor, considering that I am the Spock of this story, may I make a logical statement for no reason?"

Adequin flexed her jaw as she leveled a look at them, "As I've explained before, the plot armor will ensure my survival. Now, leave me behind, that is an order!"

Title: The Prince
Author: Niccolò Machiavelli
Additional Authors: Rufus Goodwin, Benjamin Martinez, W.K. Marriott, Denis Daly, Μαρία Κασωτάκη

Title: Age of Myth (The Legends of the First Empire, #1)
Author: Michael J. Sullivan
My Review:
Actually a decent fantasy series with some unique ideas. Too often a series will show the humans as a complex society with various factions and goals, but present the other side as a uniform entity with zero depth. Here that's not the case, both sides are complex and in that gray area, with flawed characters.

The storytelling is let down by the weird language anachronisms. For example even though most people speak in that fantasy way, which is an older simpler English without slang, occasionally a character will use a phrase that feels out of place like "weird" and "know what I'm saying?". Which is weird, know what I'm saying? There are also fantasy names of people, with the occasional modern name for some people which again breaks that immersion.

Looking forward to the next book and hopefully it's not too immersion breaking this time!

Title: Age of Swords (The Legends of the First Empire, #2)
Author: Michael J. Sullivan
My Review:
Suspending disbelief can be expected when reading fantasy, but suspending ridiculousness cannot.

The first in the series, Age of Myth, was low key, middle ground, and somewhat enjoyable. It did have a few flaws here and there but nothing terrible, it was a good read.

This, the second, has jumped some kind of shark, in that it has invented jumping and also discovered sharks. The author has taken a few quirks of several level headed characters, and leaned into them hard. Like, really, really hard.

What we end up with is a set of characters who are now these amazing artistes of the mind... they are suddenly inventing things and accelerating their little corner of civilization. In a few days they invent writing, pockets, shelter, and the wheel. They invent things and then reason it out like seasoned anthropologists. What's further ridiculous about this is that these communities know trade, they trade with other civilizations that have those things that they are 'inventing'. It's just wrong. Inventions do not emerge spontaneously, they are developed through the very act of trading and interacting with others.

Sadly a huge chunk of the story is devoted to this completely pointless trite and could have been done away with, or at least greatly diminished. In trying to convey just how unique these characters are, they became caricatures.

Title: A Darker Shade of Magic (Shades of Magic, #1)
Author: V.E. Schwab
My Review:
The introductory meeting between Kell and Lila is some of the cringiest dialogue I have encountered in a long time. It's probably supposed to sound snappy and clever but it falls flat before it even started and then repeatedly falls flat in order to drive the cringiness home. Two flat, boring characters with nothing driving them together except for "because reasons".

That this was a Goodreads Choice award says more about the voters than it does about the story.

Title: From Blood and Ash (Blood and Ash, #1)
Author: Jennifer L. Armentrout
My Review:
I've been working my way through "Goodreads Choice" winners from the past few years, and have to say, I'm not having a great time. I now associate this 'award' with poor quality, bad writing, and that it reflects nothing more than a popularity contest.

This book is no exception. The writing and exposition are so bad, the characters so badly done, the villains so cartoonish, the dialogue so rotting cheese, I had to go back and figure out why I added it to my Want To Read list.

So this 1-star rating isn't just for this book, it's for all of us on Goodreads who couldn't pick a good book out of a line up of one. We couldn't pick a good book if someone shoved a Booger Prize winning work up our nose. We couldn't find a good book in a small padded cell that had nothing in it except a good book, we'd smack our heads repeatedly against the wall, impair our cognitive process even further (an impossibility) and rate it 5 stars. We genuinely suck.

Title: The Night Circus
Author: Erin Morgenstern
My Review:
A zero tension story, where everyone is acting mysterious without explanation.

There is a 'game' between two people. There is no real reason for the game to exist except that it's mysterious and it must happen. Even at the end there's nothing revealed about it.

In fact the whole story has no point or purpose. It's a whole lot of events but nothing much happening.

The real magic here is how this nonsense got past the editors.

Is it any surprise that this is yet another Goodreads choice award? This 1-star rating isn't just for this book, it's for all of us on Goodreads who couldn't pick a good book out of a line up of one.

Title: The Rise of Endymion (Hyperion Cantos, #4)
Author: Dan Simmons
My Review:
An unsatisfying end to what could have been a great series. The protagonist Raul, that once started as a mature, balanced individual, now turns into a whining petulant set of hormones. It doesn't help that he is also suddenly a complete dope, not knowing what's happening around him even though somehow everyone else seems to know and yet never share... and not helped either with the object of his obsession, Aenea, whose only response to questions is to say that everything will be explained later. After a certain number of repetitions of this scenario it gets real tiring.

Worst of all, his whining, snivelling, petulance constantly gets in the way of an actual interesting story being played out amongst literally every other character and place in the book. There will be various people who are sitting and explaining monumental details regarding the reality of things, or speaking to the philosophy of what we know, and there will sit Raul, sulking and fuming over Aenea not talking to him or not telling him something.

Looking back at the title of the book, the Rise of Endymion, there is no rise whatsoever. Only the cantankerous collapse of a cranky cretin.

A "surprise twist" the author was trying to keep up his sleeve was so badly hidden, so telegraphed, that it was already obvious the moment it was first hinted at. Whatever cleverness or twist the author may have perceived was definitely not there.

If I have a time tomb I'd go back and warn myself to stop at book two. That's as far as one needs to go, this retrofitted fanfic can be forgotten.

Title: Endymion (Hyperion Cantos, #3)
Author: Dan Simmons
My Review:
In some ways I enjoyed reading this more than Hyperion itself. The events of Hyperion are now a bit fuzzy to me, as it's been several years, and no regrets about it. Because, in this story, it's been several hundred years since those events, and they are now the stuff of legends. So that hazy recollection plays quite nicely with the way those 'legendary' events are talked about or summarized.

I'd describe it as a bit of slice of life with action, bits of fun, travel, and philosophy, with good memorable characters. There absolutely is a story, and it unfolds in parts as they go on their journey.

I really enjoyed the role of the church here, its powerful, sacrosanct, intriguing and frightening nature; and what it has become in the intervening centuries, along with the little important details that are revealed about them.

Title: Mountain
Author: Liu Cixin
Publisher: Beijing Guomi Digital Technology Co., Ltd

Title: Sun of China
Author: Liu Cixin
Publisher: Beijing Guomi Digital Technology Co., Ltd.

Title: A Memory Called Empire (Teixcalaan, #1)
Author: Arkady Martine
My Review:
This was a tough one to start, but got smoother as I continued. The names of the various places and people are difficult to understand at first, but slowly over time it starts to make sense, in other words, there's no handholding going on to explain certain things. It's not action packed, it's a medium burn story, but a good one, set in a mystery backdrop. The main character Mahit is an ambassador from a tiny little station-world, to the great empire, and she is uncovering missing information about her 'predecessor'.

I actually liked all the characters, nobody seemed annoying, their conversations weren't cliched. Each person had a distinct personality and friendship dynamics with each other.

Title: Station Eleven
Author: Emily St. John Mandel
My Review:
It's less of a plot driven story and more of a set of threads, of people who are connected in certain ways, unknown to each other initially. The backdrop is post apocalyptic and just before , during, and long after a great disaster strikes.

The author's writing is pretty evocative and often insightful. The characters felt distinguishing enough, each with their own drive and backstory and motivations. Those passages alone were enough to keep me going as I greatly enjoyed everyone's inner thoughts.

The book was written 5 years before the Covid19 pandemic so it's interesting to see a speculative fiction regarding such an event at a much more devastating scale.

The author mostly manages to keep descriptions of items generic enough that the story can survive the passage and decay of time, with some exceptions. The author was often confusing phone with iPhone and calling game consoles Nintendo.

One other minor correction that nobody will ever see: pigeons necks aren't luminescent (lit up), they're iridescent.

Overall a decent work, though I think Sea of Tranquility was much stronger and I found myself comparing to it all the while. After all it's also about similar disjointed threads, going back and forth in time, but so much better.

Title: Too Like the Lightning (Terra Ignota, #1)
Author: Ada Palmer
My Review:
A dense read, that was difficult to follow at times. It's not really a sci-fi book even though it takes place in a 'future'. It's a politics and philosophy story, which happens to be in a 'future'.

What makes it difficult to follow is the numerous characters, many of whom share the same name intermittently, and the constant breaking of the fourth wall. I'm not complaining about it, it's an interesting aspect of the story, just made it difficult.

The society represented here has a taboo on people's genders, but spends a lot of time talking about it; I think this could have done with a generous helping of "show, don't tell", instead it spends a lot of time telling. Interesting and unique at first, boring after the 100th repetition.

There is an ongoing mystery/story but it's not very monumental, it just comes down to a bit of political celebrity gossip. There are various twists and turns that come up in the story, and several interesting ideas regarding concepts of citizenship and 'belonging' and family structures. But it's all immediately tempered by the resumption of the slow burn philosophy. It's not for everyone so apply the ⅓rd rule.

I lost interest quickly and forced myself through it, and should really have abandoned it.

Title: English History (Collins Little Books)
Author: Collins UK
My Review: It's a useful condensed version of English history, with lots of interesting events and topics. I'd call it a reference book in a story style — each small story or page serves as a rabbit hole of information go down if you're interested.

Title: The Iron Ship (The Gates of the World, #1)
Author: K.M. McKinley

Title: Transmigration (Warlock of the Magus World, #1)
Author: Wen Chao Gong
My Review:
If stories were spices, this would be flour with weevils in it.

Quite possibly one of the dullest, most pointless LNs I've had the misfortune of being subject to. Nowhere in this stream of consciousness, whose appearance is closer to that of a torrent of diarrhoea, is there any semblance of a coherent story, progression, or motivation.

Reading this represents a low point in my history and my existence is all the more mundane for having done so.

Title: Ascendance of a Bookworm (Light Novel), Part 4 Volume 9
Author: Miya Kazuki
My Review: Much better than the disappointing previous entry, a good mixture of interactions and storylines are progressed.

Title: Ascendance of a Bookworm (Light Novel), Part 4 Volume 8
Author: Miya Kazuki
My Review: A pretty poor entry in the series overall. I'm quite disappointed that the entire focus was on social aspects and marriage, and none on Rozemyne's talents. In fact the "bookworm" was just an afterthought. Most of the contents just seemed to be filler.

Through my secret network of spies, I have found out what the title of this book will be, as well as the year it's going to be released in.

Title: Blackflame (Cradle, #3)
Author: Will Wight
My Review:
This series isn't going well for me. The first book was very obviously a 'transition' piece to set people up for the second book. That was OK. But the the second book, sadly, was also a transition piece, setting people up. I finally thought there would be a story here, but not much luck again, it's transition, setting up, and a tiny bit of story.

The problem is that everyone is mysterious and powerful and hiding things, and it's meant to keep the draw for the story going, but this particular series goes overboard with the number of things kept mysterious to the point that I stopped caring. Many of these people are also a lot of bark with no bite as one after another they rapidly come into contact with even more powerful people which takes away the awe.

The magic system is a bit too clinical and sterile, there are strict ranks with names, and you're meant to level up, and it's meant to take years (but of course not for our plucky protagonists, oh no, they are too special but the why is a mystery, obviously). Even certain characters for whom said system should be irrelevant, they still speak about those specific level names.

Lindon is actually a pretty decent character as far as YA protagonists go, he's actually well mannered and not haughty, which I found to be quite refreshing. Sadly he is let down by the writing: he keeps gathering new secret items for later use, and everyone keeps handing him shortcuts to new powers (while saying that there's no such thing as shortcuts... like whatevs), and free training. As a result, Lindon doesn't have any character progression, he's just, like, some guy.

In fact, it feels like most of the book is training. Nothing much happens. The few bits of story that do happen, happen "because reasons". Again, not a terrible thing in itself, but overused, has a way of spoiling enjoyment.

Really unsure whether to proceed with this series or not, it's been 3 books of not much happening and very little expained.

Title: Chatter: The Voice in Our Head, Why It Matters, and How to Harness It
Author: Ethan Kross
My Review:
Mendhak didn't realize this was a self help book until it was finished, he had started reading assuming it was a psychology book, but it turned out to be a mixture of both, but staying engrossing enough to keep going. While reading he felt that even issues around his own anxiety and chatter had gained perspective and a little bit of help.

That's how these things go, you don't often realize what insights you might gain from unexpected sources.

The book itself was well structured and felt practical. Each topic was given a good dose of anecdotes, explanations and the explanations around it.

Now if you'll excuse me I must go and touch my GPU precisely 4 times before I eat my dinner. I think I ought to visit the Alps soon...

Title: 六花の勇者 (Rokka no Yuusha, #1)
Author: Ishio Yamagata
My Review:
One of the best "battle of wits" series I've read in a long time. This one is particularly well done as it's not just inferences, intelligence and wiles, but all this being done in increasingly dangerous situations. The author is really good at setting up situations of increasing urgency. There's a great cast of characters, no real good guys, and an amazing villain that became my favourite.

The story takes place in the backdrop of another thousand year story, the details of which are revealed in small doses. Just enough to keep you wanting more.

Only thing I didn't like, which was minor, was the artwork. It's hard to follow, so I clumsy really appreciate it, and the characters drawn too frilly, actually they all look the same. I wish they could have shown more of the villains and some of the landscapes too.

It's a shame that the series has ended on volume 6, but it ends in a somewhat decent place with something of a semi conclusion, so, not too disappointing.

Title: At First Light (Dr. Evan Wilding #1)
Author: Barbara Nickless
My Review:
Imagine just for a moment, you're investigating a serial killer.

The serial killer has been leaving clues and messages in a form deeply intertwined with Viking language and mythology.

During the course of your investigation, mysterious figurines keep appearing at some of the different locations that you go visit, including your own home.

Do you,

A) Investigate this right away as it's quite clear that the killer knows your whereabouts and is sending you further messages.

or

B) Exclaim, "OH IT'S PROBABLY NOTHING JUST A PRANK NOTHING TO SEE HERE LET'S MOVE ALONG AND TOTALLY IGNORE THIS COMPLETELY ON-THE-NOSE PIECE THAT THE STORY KEEPS BRINGING UP HAHA KIDS THESE DAYS AMIRITE."

Title: Poisonwell (Whispers from Mirrowen, #3)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
This was a difficult yet interesting read. The revelation and mysterious kept me turning the pages, but the actual execution of the story was a slog.

There were so many battles that they just blurred into each other. There was no sense of tension or stakes.

There were almost no consequences to actions. Almost everyone who was in danger would usually be rescued or healed immediately so there was never a real sense of danger and finality to people's situations.

There was too much exposition and plans within plans. Though in the end they were of little consequence and a series of happy endings just neatly wrapped everything together into neat little packages. No loss, no sacrifice, just a series of miraculous conveniences.

So overall, a decent story with sloggy execution.

Title: Entangled Life: How Fungi Make Our Worlds, Change Our Minds & Shape Our Futures
Author: Merlin Sheldrake

Title: Aftershocks (The Palladium Wars #1)
Author: Marko Kloos
My Review: Mostly world building and character introduction. The pace is slow, which isn't bad, it just doesn't have much of a story. So the ending is abrupt. It's like they took a full length novel and physically cut it, to get more sales.

Title: War of the Wolf (The Saxon Stories, #11)
Author: Bernard Cornwell

Title: Sword of Kings (The Saxon Stories, #12)
Author: Bernard Cornwell
My Review: Not the best entry in the series. There is suddenly a lot of sailing and ship related terminology. The ending is rushed and some characters are killed off for an obvious convenience.

Title: War Lord (The Saxon Stories, #13)
Author: Bernard Cornwell
My Review:
Final entry in the 13-book series. Book 13 comes with a satisfying conclusion, nothing too happy nor too sad, it's just satisfying and decent.

Overall the series is a very good one for historical fiction fans. It chronicles the early history of the formation of England, the nature of life between various nationalities and religions, with the main character serving as a semi-important character in many important moments.

I highly recommend it!

Title: The Crown Tower (The Riyria Chronicles, #1)
Author: Michael J. Sullivan
My Review:
Trying my best to get through this. The story and world building is pretty good.

But the dialog is so bad. It's sooo downright awful, it breaks the immersion and enjoyment. The characters can't decide if they want to talk in fantasy 'English', or in American slang. It's completely inconsistent The conversations are unnatural as well, several times I've stopped and thought, 'nobody talks like that', it's sometimes expositionary, part cringey movie quips, and sometimes like something from a 'that happened' post.

Oof. And I think I'm the only person noticing this. So... it's not you, it's me.

Edit: finished. Well, it was consistent at least. It never got better. There is a bit of a cliffhanger at the end, which isn't a nice thing to do in a series that the author isn't sure of continuing. I might give the next book a try though.

Title: The School for Good and Evil (The School for Good and Evil, #1)
Author: Soman Chainani
My Review:
This book has all the the depth and personality of a Disney movie: It's wide as an ocean in over 500 pages of filler material which are sparkly on the surface but end up being a vast interminable void of nothing. And it is as deep as a puddle in the content, characters, and messages that it delivers.

The biggest disappointment for me was that there is just enough world building and premise within this story that it could have been turned into something with a lot of potential. But it doesn't. It drives home a very clear message with consistently. If you are ugly, you are evil. If you are evil, you are ugly.

There are moments when this very consistency is questioned, or played upon ever so slightly, but a few moments later, with consistency, that line of questioning is discarded in favour of the ever pervasive shallowness. Perhaps it was not entirely a loss, for I learned a lesson that I have learned many times in the past, to not judge a book by its cover. I chose the book based on its beautiful cover illustration, only to learn later what an evil its contents are...

The story cannot decide what it is trying to do, at times it seems there is going to be some kind of lesson or event on the horizon, at times there are events happening for no reason and purpose. The characters flip flop more than a fish out of water in their motivations and actions, and it gets tiring to keep up with these new threads that lead nowhere.

At some point the story realizes that it has overstayed its welcome and rushes the ending in a completely unsatisfactory way. I felt a fool for having stuck with the book in the hopes that there would be some turnabout, some twist, some lesson I didn't see coming, some nuance.

This is absolutely not a healthy book for young adults and middle graders to be reading, it is toxic and damaging, and I was appalled that it has been tagged as such and is being reviewed so highly.

Title: The Mammoth Book of Golden Age Science Fiction: Ten Classic Stories from the Birth of Modern Science Fiction Writing
Author: Isaac Asimov

Title: Home: Habitat, Range, Niche, Territory (The Murderbot Diaries, #4.5)
Author: Martha Wells

Title: The Midnight Line (Jack Reacher, #22)
Author: Lee Child
My Review:
If B movies were a book, this would be it. I usually abandon bad books, but this is so over-the-top and unnecessary that I couldn't help but keep going out of morbid curiosity.

I even started updating progress (below) and I don't usually take notes. This Reacher guy seems to be some sort of modern day superhero but he reads like a caricature. He's almost 7 feet tall with hands like chicken. He has perfect analytical tactical and situational awareness at all times and is able to process everything within milliseconds including people's psychology and any legalities involved.

Then there's the... Strange writing style. Author's quirk. Tiny sentences, few words. Usually incomplete. Writing for toddlers perhaps. Or people without attention spans. Tik tok generation. Or was it minimalism.

The dialog and characters were lazy, everyone just sounded the same, and everyone talks in boringass cliches and evaluates things through lens of courtrooms and legalities.

The overall story was just boring, and I'm not sure if this is meant to be a good or bad example of a Jack Reacher book but it certainly hasn't set a good impression.

----

Progress notes.

8.0% "Weird writing style. Short sentences. Sometimes fragments. Average 5 words per sentence. Why is that. Do people have short attention spans."

18.0% "So this guy is almost 7 feet tall but is worried that the 'Bigfoot' description is what's going to give him away, not an almost 7 ft tall person trying to walk around surreptitiously. He's also got split second tactical analysis skills. And he has perfect memory. And his hands are like chickens."

38.0% "So this guy's some kind of detective as well. And likes to get into a dick measuring contest with everyone he meets. And he's generally unpleasant and demanding when talking to anyone he meets. A dick measuring dick dick."

48.0% "Finally meet a character that can speak more than 2 sentences at a time, and it's an entire chapter of exposition completely irrelevant to the question that was being asked."

58.0% "Instantaneous tactical analysis, perfect situational awareness, every law memorised. This guy is like the comments section on reddit."

78.0% "This is like reading a car crash in slow motion. Now everyone has leveled up and become a tactician and knows every law there is and they are all talking in terms of long term strategies, except of course for Reacher who has powers to see far into the future. The main part of the story has fizzled out but it's like they're grasping around for reasons to stick around."

88.0% "The last part of this book is just a bunch of people figuring out where to park."

98.0% "What a useless bunch of people, evaluating every scenario as though it's about to take place in a courtroom. Pointless, most unnecessary, totally uneventful ending."

Title: The Druid (The Dawning of Muirwood, #1)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
A new entry in a new series, set in the Muirwood world. It's a comfortable return, and I'd recommend reading this only after having read the Legends of Muirwood and Covenant of Muirwood series. Although this is a prequel, as the name indicates, there are some spoilers regarding future series, and several details that you'll only appreciate after having read those others.

It's a comfortable return because the author has an evocative way of describing the world, its nature, and its relationship with the people of the world. That same evocative prose continues here, so if you liked it before, you'll like it here.

The protagonist, Eilean, feels like a well-rounded and compelling character, and I enjoyed reading their dialogue with the others, especially Morduant. There's definitely a lot of character development, and watching them stumble and rise felt rewarding. There is also a cast of supporting characters who aren't exactly cardboard cutouts, nor are they overtly good or bad, everyone's sitting in a gray area. That tiny bit of dimensionality also really helps bring together life at the abbey.

The story is a gradual buildup of events, and it does a great job of gradually introducing new twists and pivots as it gradually reveals more of the greater context of what is happening in the world.

Oh, at the beginning of each chapter is a little quote or entry from a journal (called epigraphs), don't skip those, they're relevant.

The book doesn't exactly end on a cliffhanger, but in retrospect, I wish I had waited a little longer for the 2nd book to come out, as I am eager to know what happens next.

Title: The Tattooist of Auschwitz (The Tattooist of Auschwitz, #1)
Author: Heather   Morris
My Review: Decent retelling of an awful time in history, and some human connections amidst it. Didn't really understand why Gita's name and origins needed to be kept a mystery.

Title: A Brief History of Everyone Who Ever Lived: The Stories in Our Genes
Author: Adam Rutherford

Title: An Eye for an Eye (Detective Kate Young, #1)
Author: Carol Wyer
My Review: It's an interesting story, with some of the usual detective clichés, but not overwhelmingly so. Biggest trouble for me was the dialogue. Everyone sounded unnatural, like they were reading from a Wikipedia page or writing an email. Ends on a cliffhanger.

Title: Forgotten (The Forgotten, #1)
Author: M.R. Forbes
My Review:
A colony ship shrouded in secrecy. What's the best way to keep secrets in such a place?

I know. A single master password for EVERYTHING. Even the secret stuff.

Title: A Psalm for the Wild-Built (Monk & Robot, #1)
Author: Becky Chambers
My Review:
Really enjoyed this, it's sort of a slice of life, with a journey, set in a sci-fi fantasy planet. It has its unique customs and history and bits of it are revealed over the course of the story. The characters are simple and endearing and is enjoyable to read their interaction. A good relaxing read that aims to be comforting.

I did have to deduct 1 star for a portion of the story that calls onions "delicious". Disgusting us more like it.

I didn't realize that this is by the same author as one of my least favourite books ever, Long way to a small angry planet. I'm glad that I've not written off a subgenre.

Title: The Evening and the Morning (Kingsbridge, #0)
Author: Ken Follett
My Review:
I really like the Kingsbridge series. This one should be read after 1, 2, and 3. It serves as a prequel to the little world that we get to know in the mainline series.

The author does a really good job in the story format, even if it's formulaic. There's always a set of good people who are just trying to get on with their lives or accomplish something. The characters are always well written and it's good to get to know them over the course of the story. And there's always a set of wicked people who are unscrupulous. They are usually powerful, and are always getting away with everything, I take great delight in reading about these evil people too. There's an unending battle between the good and evil sides, and just when you think justice will be served, evil manages to wriggle and escape.

Now normally in the stories, justice does eventually get served towards the end. However in this book, it's not quite the case. There is no real justice served, there was only happenstance, or old age, or chance, which manages to provide some measure of 'victory' to the protagonists, but it's not justice in the sense of being right. In other words, everyone just had to kind of wait things out, the end. So that was a bit of a disappointment.

Title: The Metamorphosis
Author: Franz Kafka
My Review: This is the kind of vague insubstantial story which gets put on school reading lists so that teachers can feel smug in their unnecessary interpretations of it, and instill a deep sense of hatred of reading in kids.

Title: Ascendance of a Bookworm (Light Novel), Part 4 Volume 5
Author: Miya Kazuki

Title: Ascendance of a Bookworm (Light Novel), Part 4 Volume 6
Author: Miya Kazuki
My Review: Actually quite a lot happens, and some of them have an ominous tone to them. One of the better volumes in recent times

Title: Ascendance of a Bookworm (Light Novel), Part 4 Volume 7
Author: Miya Kazuki

Title: 1587: A Year of No Significance: The Ming Dynasty in Decline
Author: Ray Huang

Title: The Fall of Gondolin (Middle-Earth Universe)
Author: J.R.R. Tolkien
My Review:
You have to be a hardcore LOTR collector/hoarder to enjoy this. A hoardcore.

It's basically the same short story retold in a few different ways. Although it's a decent short story, in no way does it justify the price. The repetitiveness makes it feel like a cashgrab on Tolkien's name.

Title: The Tea Girl of Hummingbird Lane
Author: Lisa See
My Review:
Started quite nicely, with decent storytelling, and a decent overview of tribal life and its place and relationship with the greater scheme of things. The main character's struggle is shown in an engaging and realistic portrayal.

The second half becomes a wtf, suddenly they're rich and everything is changed and there's betrayal and it feels like a cheap Chinese drama or light novel. I do not understand the praise this is receiving and don't agree with it.

Title: A Morbid Taste for Bones (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #1)
Author: Ellis Peters
My Review:
It's a good mix of historical fiction, murder mystery, and not often mentioned, comedy too! It's not outright comedy, but it's just the right dose of humor mixed in with the serious ecclessiastic setting.

The prose, writing, is rich in its descriptive power. You can't skim over the paragraphs, every sentence holds quite a bit of content in it.

The rich prose combined with the rural Welsh setting make for a comfortable and entertaining read.

The main character, Brother Cadfael, is both a protagonist and a background character at the same time and it's great watching him work his mind.

Main character aside, all of the others, including the 'villainous' ones were enjoyable too.

Glad to have found a new series, will definitely be trying out a few more.

Title: One Corpse Too Many (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #2)
Author: Ellis Peters
My Review:
I think I've found a series I'm going to enjoy for a bit. "Brother Cadfael" is something like a medieval detective. The book delivers a compelling story with dense prose and vocabulary I haven't encountered in years, it had me constantly long pressing words for their definitions.

Really good characters, similar to the first one, there were 'antagonists' but I liked everyone encountered, especially Hugh Berringar. Enjoyed the competition between Hugh and Cadfael.

Title: Monk's Hood (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #3)
Author: Ellis Peters
My Review:
Really enjoying this series so far.

The writing is so good, the descriptions are so evocative and rich. I took my time reading the sentences because they carried so much with them.

I enjoyed the parts that took place in Wales among the people, though I had trouble distinguishing some of the people's names and places, it was still my favorite.

Title: Circe
Author: Madeline Miller
My Review:
I went in knowing nothing of the Circe stories and a rudimentary familiarity of Greek mythology.

The characters are mostly interesting and their interactions a source of good tension and storytelling.

The main character is sometimes interesting and sometimes inconsistent and sometimes confusing but more than any of that, she is mostly boring.

What seems to save the book is the little bits of mythology that are sprinkled in between, and the new characters introduced.

Overall it's okay.

Title: Daughter of the Moon Goddess (The Celestial Kingdom, #1)
Author: Sue Lynn Tan
My Review:
This is so hilariously bad that I thought the other reviewers are writing satire. I thought this book was a parody of something. They aren't, and this isn't.


Xingyin (which translates to Mary Sue) is extra special. Everything is handed to her, as she is incapable of doing things on her own. Except sometimes she is extra magical and extra powerful. She can overcome obstacles in days that take other years because they are inferior. She is always biting back retorts, because others are dumb. Many are just comically evil. Many people do things for contrived or nonexistent reasons as it's needed to get the story from A to B.

There is no tension, chemistry, or buildup. Things happen, but in most cases she is 'carried'. The story reads like a cheap drama.

Title: Soulsmith (Cradle, #2)
Author: Will Wight
My Review:
In which the main character is a Soulsmith for all of five minutes.

The rest of the story is lots of powerful people posturing and one whose mysterious act goes on for so long the mystery becomes a bore.

While it's a decent story at times, there's too much setup going on, and bits of knowledge and artifacts being collected without explanation.

Title: Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell
Author: Susanna Clarke
My Review:
This was quite a unique book to go through. The style is written like an author from, and with a style from the 1800s. It has long, dense sentences with words that I don't normally use. People don't talk quickly, they talk in long meandering sentences, and people listen with patience and respond with long meandering sentences. The world building is amazingly realistic, think of "England with magic" but it's presented in such a matter of fact way, with descriptions and footnotes and side stories that it's easy to get immersed into it.

It's important to keep in mind that the story goes at its own pace and it simply cannot be rushed. If you follow along, the journey rewards you with an excellent stories and side-stories, interesting characters and satisfying conclusions.

I can't think this book is for everyone though. It's a slow burn, the story is dense, the sentences aren't fast, some storeis are relevant some not, there are footnotes, there are conclusions and inconclusions. For some people, it can feel like a history book and be offputting. If you're not captivated by page 300, then I suggest not continuing. I did get into the book's mindset quite early on, so I enjoyed it.

Imagine my surprise as well, I had no idea that this author is also the author of Piranesi which I really enjoyed, but these two books aren't even remotely alike!

Title: Piranesi
Author: Susanna Clarke
My Review:
This is a story centered around solitude and loneliness in another world, which is why it really clicked with me. However I don't think this would be for everyone, so I won't recommend it, and at the same time what worked out for me was knowing nothing at all about the book, just going in blind. It is my favorite this year (so far).

Some descriptions and phrases used in the opening chapter were quite confusing and felt unnecessarily verbose. But as soon as it became apparent that the main character has been there for a while, a lot of it started to make sense. These were his words and his ways of describing things. That manner of description helps give this place a sense of otherworldliness, and at times it felt like like being in a dreamlike state, a very unique worldbuilding that I've not come across before. It's melancholic and cozy and haunting and mysterious at the same time.

I enjoyed most of all the feeling of quietness, being one of the few people there, and the character's love for this weird and imposing place, and his relationship with it. It's also helped along by their meticulous, diligent nature and their frank manner of speaking, which was refreshing.


The story takes place in this setting, and it becomes quite apparent quite quickly that there is a fascinating mystery in the background, revealed a little at a time, and sometimes an unexplained thing is dropped in a tantalizingly small dose. The story is unravelled over a short book and the author does it in a riveting way, presenting it, and the people behind the scenes, and the answers to all the mysteries. Really enjoyed this one.

Title: The Fall of Hyperion (Hyperion Cantos, #2)
Author: Dan Simmons
My Review:
I read this 7 years after the original Hyperion and it probably would have been better to read them together, but luckily it's not necessary. This book does drop in reminders about things that happened in the first book so it's not necessary to remember every detail.

I liked how the book gets larger in scope compared to the first, and there are a lot of physical, metaphysical, natural, and supernatural threads tied together to bring the story together.

There are three main threads here, the CEO, the poet, and the pilgrims (each with their sub-threads). All are pretty good to follow. The poet is a bit odd to follow at first, but it gets better and his purpose is explained. The CEO is always fun to follow as there are decisions to be made. And for each pilgrim, there's a bit of further exploration into their stories, and eventually showing how they are all linked to ongoing activities in the story.

The ending was a bit soppy at times, I'm not a fan of the bullshit clichéd "love is the greatest force in the universe even science can't understand it hurpy durpy durp" but thankfully not a lot of time was spent on that particular turd lined avenue.

A minor peeve was the way in which things contemporary to us readers is treated as 'arcane knowledge' that very few people know about in this futuristic universe, but just a few paragraphs later someone will use another contemporary reference that everyone seems to know about. Either let it be common knowledge, or just skip it.

Title: I Have No Mouth & I Must Scream
Author: Harlan Ellison

Title: The Rose and the Thorn (The Riyria Chronicles, #2)
Author: Michael J. Sullivan
My Review:
I should have learned my lesson from the previous in the series, but I held out hope that things would get better. They did not.

The story itself, and the world building, is decent. Enough to keep going and wonder, what happens next.

What spoils it (once again) is the awful, awful dialogue. The characters don't know how to talk properly. There is a heavy helping of modern American slang in there that it's jarring, and you often get expositionary philosophizing in the middle of urgent situations. While I was able to look past it for the first half, things progressively got worse in the second half, to the point that I was actually cringing. The whole plot seems centred around the characters being able to get their quips in, or reinforce their roles as walking cliches.

Most of it read like fanfiction, and it might have been, by the number of plot holes present and the poorly thought out 'scenarios'. Someone has been spreading bales of hay around the castle and nobody questions it, seriously? Could a fire be any more telegraphed than this.

But from what I can tell of other reviews, that is sort of the point. Most readers are reading it for the characters, the quality is a secondary point. This is a far cry from the Ryria Revelations series which was actually quite good.

Title: How a Realist Hero Rebuilt the Kingdom, Volume 1
Author: Dojyomaru

Title: 나 혼자만 레벨 업 1 [Solo Leveling] Novel
Author: Chugong
My Review:
The Solo Leveling series is unreservedly and unapologetically a wish-fulfillment power fantasy, which is quite common for the most popular light novels currently, and despite that it's still a fun read which manages to stay engaging. I've actually read through the series twice now, to pick up on anything I might have missed or to gain a further appreciation.

The story pacing is quite good, most of the plot doesn't feel dragged out and the action is doled out in generous doses. There's never a dull moment, so the plot wants to make you keep reading. Each chapter is short so the story doesn't feel interminable. Speaking overall it feels like the author had a rough idea of where he wanted the story to end up, which is good, though there is a bit of meandering at times, none of it is overdone.

I think the biggest (and for me most noticeable) let down in the series is the 'other' characters involved, they are pretty poorly written. They don't really exist to support the main character, which is why I wouldn't call them supporting characters, but 'side characters' is probably a better term. Instead of supporting, they exist to showcase how powerful the main character is.

There are certain parts when the story will cut over to them, but only to show how ineffective they are and how impotent their actions become in the face of crisis. Most of their time is spent observing the main character, and opening their jaws in surprise, swallowing dry saliva or wiping cold sweat off their brow and professing how great the main character is. Occasionally a very strong character is introduced but again they are only introduced to show their eventual lack of power against the main. If you've ever watched the Dragonball series, it's similar to the way Goku's friends spend most of their time gaping and commenting.

And so, sadly, this characterization flaw creeps its way into the villains as well. Each one is shown to be amazingly powerful, only to be shocked and surprised when they are defeated. Repeat ad nauseum. The overall story holds very little tension, you know that the main character has Level 9000 Plot Armor manufactured by Gary Stu Industries.

My Review:
A very middle-of-the-road conclusion to a great series.

The writing quality felt a bit off, compared to most of the previous in the series. It's like they were trying to experiment with a new approach in terms of perspectives, though I don't think it worked too well. I wasn't a fan of the 'metaphysical' interludes.

Storywise, it was overall quite predictable what would happen, and it must have been predictable to the main characters too. The first part of the book felt wasted in irrelevant and boring side stories, while our favorites were just hanging around waiting for their turn.

Overall the well done parts are well done, especially the character interactions and the teamwork. It's a good series to read and I'm glad it didn't overstay its welcome.

Title: Last and First Men: A Story of the Near and Far Future
Author: Olaf Stapledon
My Review:
Last and First Men is a speculative historical-fiction that takes place over billions of years. There are no individuals or characters or protagonists or antagonists. The entire 'story' is written almost as a documentary or history book narrated to you the reader, describing various significant events that took place over this time period. It's not a typical 'story' either - there is no character to relate to, it's just one person's imagination taking what he knew and going forward from there.

This book is definitely not for everyone, yet I found it very thrilling to read a story in this manner. The 'scale' at which the story takes place, both in terms of time as well as space, makes for something very vivid and grand to imagine. It's hard to describe or summarise it well, there's so much that happens, and so many references to different fields and topics.

It's one of those you-have-to-try-it type books. And because of the way it's written, it's also going to be one of those you'll-love-it-or-hate-it types. It reminded me very much of [b:The Three-Body Problem|20518872|The Three-Body Problem (Remembrance of Earth’s Past #1)|Liu Cixin|https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1415428227l/20518872._SY75_.jpg|25696480] which was again a similar theme of speculative history over vast amounts of time. If you liked that series, you'll like this one.

Side note: this book is guaranteed to increase your vocabulary. It's dense with large words so I found myself long pressing words somewhat frequently compared to other books.

Title: Rhythm of War (The Stormlight Archive, #4)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
This book felt very different from the first three in the series, and what surprised me the most was that I didn't enjoy it. I've never not enjoyed Stormlight Archive, I've even re-read the series even though I rarely ever re-read books. I've been reflecting a lot since finishing Rhythm of War, and today I realized something. The author does a fantastic job in any new series he starts; the characters, the world building, the magic, the plot, the mysteries. Until book 3. After that, all bets are off. The plot goes elsewhere, the characters take a hike, the story loses its way, something happens each time. And this book, Rhythm of War was not exception.

Where the first three in the series had lots of interesting world building, a varied cast of characters, and a well progressing story, this book takes a sudden turn. It wasn't enjoyable, the story dragged, the characters became uninteresting, and not much happened, but a lot of stuff gets explained with a great deal of repetition - this could easily have been half the length, maybe less. Rhythm of War feels like a YA book in tone; YAs aren't bad, they are just written differently with a different set of focus topics in mind.

What I noticed was, instead of telling a story, the author spends more time preaching modern societal morality and knowledge. What I mean is, it's quite common in fantasy-setting stories to have a few, just a few instances, where someone is highly progressive in a specific topic, or has a modern set of moralities that reflects that of the readers, or expresses modern scientific knowledge in their own framework of the world. (I wish I knew what this trope was called. Some kind of fantasy-setting-with-modern-englightened-beings.) These instances are sprinkled about sparingly, acting as a tap on the nose, a little icing on the cake. It's a little nod to the reader without being too overt. But no, in Rhythm of War, the author has made it the foundation, the layering, the icing, and empted an entire can of it all over and the can is slathered with it too, and the plate's made of it too... and then you're whacked on the nose and ears for good measure.

It's important to note that the topics are all relevant and important today, however, if you lay it on thick and start to shout the topics at me ad nauseum, it breaks immersion in the story, and I will start judging it based on my knowledge of those topics. Furthermore, if there are too many of said topics, then the disconnect between those thoughts and the rest of the world building is far too jarring. There's a reason for making it a nugget of wisdom, not an avalanche of revelations, but the author was perhaps too eager to show all the research they had done.

Moving on...

Kaladin spends most of his time brooding and wallowing in his angst over being unable to save everyone, briefly changing careers for some flimsy reason. I am convinced that the author hadn't a clue what to do with Kaladin so he just made him do something else for a while, namely working in a clinic, so that he could move on with other character arcs. Of course mental health is a hot topic currently, so of course Kaladin and Lirin just know that mental health needs to be treated differently than their 'prevailing' wisdom which of course the idiots around them subscribe to.

Navani has become every scientist in human history, all wrapped into one. The number of revelations and 'hypotheses' she comes up with in a span of a few days easily dwarfs what we normal humans have accomplished in a thousand years. It got so ridiculous, I actually started taking notes, and I never take notes! She hypothesises over the modern scientific method, the dual nature of light, electricity, magnetism, the standard model of particle physics, matter, anti-matter, space travel, quarks and nuclear power.

Jasnah, not to be left out, of course holds a modern view of how governments ought to work, completely in contradiction to the idiots she's surrounded with. After all, only the main characters in this series are the enlightened ones, everyone else is of course an idiot who could never comprehend what they are thinking. All of them come up with these ideas in complete isolation because they are enlightened.

Shallan, whose multiple characters I already found insufferable to begin with, are back and stronger than ever, and there's even more added into the mix. The people that surround her are completely accustomed to her changing characters, and now we are treated to dialogue and conflict between these characters. For most of the time she just hides away and does nothing, while her characters sketch in her notebook, waiting for the book to end.

In terms of 'screentime'. As before, Dalinar gets very little time compared to everyone else and just feels disconnected. I think he was mostly just staring into the distance. Szeth just stood next to him. Jasnah was also pretty much forgotten, with just a few chapters to herself.

There are a few redeeming moments, like the trial for Adolin which was mostly boring with a decent conclusion, and the story that Wit relates to Kaladin.

Overall, a slog. I forced myself to persist because this is (was) my favorite series to date. The payoff wasn't worth it. Following Goodreads' tooltips, it was OK at best.

Title: Advanced Penetration Testing: Hacking the World's Most Secure Networks
Author: Wil Allsopp
My Review:
A lot of these techniques covered are what we often see in postmortems and reports from after the fact in regular security news, and it's good to see these all in one place. The anecdotes interspersed between the techniques are interesting and some shocking, but all insightful.

The most important point I feel has been made here is that targeted APTs aren't the same as regular hackers. It requires patience, and a great deal of thought and research, and the regular security mechanisms that you put in place shouldn't be assumed to be an absolute defence, merely a first line.

I found this book difficult to hold, regardless of sitting position. I prefer the format of traditional paper books or digital books, rather than this cylindrical shape that the authors have chosen, which is neither. It does not fit well on a bookshelf, nor can I add it to my Calibre library.

It's quite clear that this is a spinoff and doesn't hold a candle to the original. You'll certainly not see me waxing poetic about this. The lack of content meant that I was done reading it, wick as a flash. Despite that, it didn't make much scents. I thought about giving it another go, but my interest has tapered.

Bad shape and poor story, why then was this created? I can't help but think that the author has some ulterior votives.

Title: Lonesome Dove (Lonesome Dove, #1)
Author: Larry McMurtry
My Review:
I don't normally read Westerns, and this will probably be the only one I'll ever read. The best way I'd describe Lonesome Dove is a Slice-of-Life in the backdrop of a journey out in the Wild West. Despite this bland description, it was a pleasure going through the story as it progressed at its own pace, there would be chapters of no real events, punctuated by moments in which a great many things of import happen.

The one thing I took away from this was how harsh life in the Wild West was, and this harsh, unforgiving nature is reflected in every aspect of the story, events, characters. There are no happy endings for most people, many wandered and eked out a survival, and the lucky ones may simply find a place that they can stay a while. The land in which they travelled was untamed, and was apathetic to their existence.

What made the story of course was the cast of characters, each character has a backstory which shaped them to be the way they are, none of them grand, and yet each one larger than life. All of them are together, but each one carries a loneliness with them. Gus, who just never shuts up, was someone I found annoying to begin with, and yet he just grew on me, to where I enjoyed his blabbering self. Call, the ever aloof, silent and disciplined. The recollection of... a person in Call's past was something I found to be one of the saddest passages I've read in a long time, I felt like I was experiencing the grief that he failed to acknowledge. And Blue Duck, someone we read very little of but is one of the most terrifying characters I've come across. His attack on July's camp left me with a sense of loss for what I had been hoping for the first real hint of happiness in July's life.

After finishing the book I thought about it for several days. There wasn't anything that particularly stood out, and everything felt memorable to me. It was just a story, but I wondered what the characters were up to now, where were they going and what were they feeling. It's strange to describe a book this way but considering that it made my tiny, frozen heart thaw ever so slightly was unexpected... it must mean it's quite something.
