Title: Blood Heir (Blood Heir Trilogy, #1)
Author: Amélie Wen Zhao
My Review:
The cover artwork caught my eye, and I thought to myself - this protagonist looks cool, she must be such a badass. It turns out she's just a dumbass.

Most of the story consists of her charging headfirst into new situations without thinking. She then proceeds to get into trouble, acting out of rage anger fury, almost losing her life several times. And in every case, she has to be rescued by someone at the last moment. Repeat ad nauseum. In other words, her mistakes are consantly being compensated for by the people around her. There's even one person brought in purely because there was nobody else around to help Ana in one of her life threatening situations, and they knew she was going to get into trouble! All of this would be fine, if she actually learned lessons from these situations (hint: she doesn't), much like I should learn not to judge a book by Goodreads reviews (hint: I didn't). And this dumbass wants to lead the nation...

But it also got me wondering he she managed to bribe her way in to prison in the opening chapter, as that would have required a degree of planning; perhaps she had a momentary lapse in her inability to think? I suppose that's what I had been hoping for - more of this planning on her journey to taking back what was hers.

The supporting characters don't help much either. They barely have any presence, or are barely given any time. The bad guys are walking cliches who must quip at every opportunity ("Ah I've been expecting you."). Something about the deaths require supporting characters to spout. One of the characters, 'May', goes through one of the cringiest death scenes I've ever encountered, who in her last moments keeps prolonging her life by dropping words of wisdom and poetry, you know, like any kid would. There is additionally a forced attraction between the two main characters; I know this due to the numerous references to his chiseled jaw, and the number of times Ana gets angry at him.

So while the story has a strong start, things just go downhill from there, spoiled by the characters, interactions and droll story. I kept reading as there seemed to be the promise of things picking up later, "Right, this dumb thing but then it's going to get better," but it never gets better. The final seal was when the emperor gets stabbed in the chest in front of everyone and nobody notices. I had to reread that part multiple times to see that I wasn't missing something. I wasn't.

And in the end, the whole 'journey' turned out to be a complete waste of time, as this was simply a flimsy pretext to turn the story to a series.

Title: The Prefect (Prefect Dreyfus Emergency, #1)
Author: Alastair Reynolds
My Review:
One of the best in the Revelation Space series. I'm now reluctant to read the second Dreyfus book for fear of spoiling this feeling.

There are multiple ongoing threads, each one seemingly unrelated, each one important in its own way. Different people with different agendas, different problems, backgrounds, stories. The main character Dreyfus is investigating a main mystery, while still thinking about other mysteries from his own past. All while there's an ongoing crisis in this part of the galaxy.

And though all of these things are seemingly unrelated or tenuously linked, the way they are brought together over the course of the story is nothing short of amazing.

This can be read standalone independently of the Revelation Space series, but it's good when read together. Revelation Space in itself is a great universe to get into, wholly recommended.

Title: Genius Doctor: Black Belly Miss Book #1 (Genius Doctor: Black Belly Miss, #1)
Author: North Night
My Review:
Nothing genius about this doctor, at all. There are no acts of genius, merely using 'magical' items that happen to be available. And there are no explanations (since no act of genius occurs). So it basically misses the most crucial aspect of 'genius' stories.

Sadly, this misleading title is what drew me in, I had been hoping for something intelligent. Instead I got chapter after chapter of descriptions of handsome men for no reason, punctuated by short stints of magical medicine, and surrounded by the male lead of the story constantly touching the female lead inappropriately.

Title: The Names of the Dead
Author: Kevin Wignall
My Review:
An 'OK' book in every aspect; the characters are OK, the plot devices are OK, the story is OK, but I wouldn't call it good. There are just far too many fortunate events and coincidences that push the story along.

The tone is set with the initial encounter with Mia, where for reasons still unexplained at the end of the story, she conveniently decides to accompany him as they pootle about various European tourist destinations seeking one loose thread or the other. It appears her purpose is to serve as nothing but a convenience function, who also happens to be, and I quote "I'm rich" - yeah, nobody says that unless they've just won a lottery.


The story, well, is just too convenient. Absolutely every hotel they visit on their hunt for information has the right people giving the right information at the right time remembering the right things or saying the right things. So that actually is a comment on the pacing; the pacing appears as though it's asking to be made into a TV series or movie, which takes away some of the enjoyment for me.

Title: Starsight (Skyward, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
I struggled immensely with this second in the Skyward series.

There is a sudden 'scene' shift and Spensa is now in an alien world surrounded by a diverse group of aliens. The premise is poor and boils down to "because reasons"; a series of convenience deus-ex-machinas arrive just in time to facilitate any logistical problems such as alien languages and adjusting to new never-before-encountered societies.

The problem - I just couldn't get over the poorly written aliens: they are basically humans with slightly different appearances and quirks. And they act just like humans, from mannerisms to motivations. I tried to look past it, but it was simply too jarring.

The first book's characters are pretty much done away with, to introduce a slew of new boring characters that I didn't care about, in a complex mire of inane alien politics which have no bearing on the first book's continuity.

This author's stories are normally well thought through and have fantastic continuity, just not this particular series. I am again wondering if this is representative of YA books and whether they need to be avoided entirely.

Title: Skyward (Skyward, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
The main character, Spensa, is pretty much an asshole. I had hoped that this was just a character flaw which would erode over the course of the story; and to be fair it does a bit, but she still remains an asshole in terms of personality and actions, the decisions she makes, the unnecessary behavior, callous disregard of others. A lot of such behavior would (pardon the pun) fly well in normal story settings, it just doesn't work in high-precision, high-speed, high-safety situations despite me trying to suspend disbelief.

The plot however is interesting enough, there is the usual mysterious world building with lost knowledge and hints dropping through every once in a while. An interesting cast of characters each with distinct, likeable personalities makes up for it and they really help carry the story forward.




tl;dr - Good story spoiled by asshole, propped up by supporting cast. I hope this is not representative of YA books.

Title: The Ciphers of Muirwood (Covenant of Muirwood, #2)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
Covenant #1 felt like a great introduction to the character Maia, there was a decent set of flashbacks and storylines showing how she got to where she was. She was scarred and had endured a lot of hardships, the strength of her character reflected that.

This, Covenant #2, felt weak. Maia has become a simpering fool, always on the verge of tears or happiness, and who drags out the story for the full length of the book in order to accomplish nothing. The author's writing is still good, so it will be worth looking at Covenant #3 to see if something does actually happen. However this one, #2 is... #2.

Title: The Banished of Muirwood (Covenant of Muirwood, #1)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review: As usual in the Muirwood series, the world building and storytelling is great.  The tragic twists keep coming for the protagonist and it's just one seemingly inescapable fate after the other.  Though I did find the ending a bit jarring, everything is neatly wrapped up in a few pages.  I'm hoping books 2 and 3 don't follow a similar formula.

Title: Red Sister (Book of the Ancestor, #1)
Author: Mark  Lawrence
My Review:
Cookie cutter characters in a generic young-adult fantasy setting. Forced rivalries between walking clichés and way, way too much exposition. I really, really tried to like this one.

Also how do you confuse geography and geology?

“Geography is like history. History is the story of mankind since we first started to record it. The story and the understanding of that story. Geography is the history of the world beneath our feet. The mountains and the ice, rivers, oceans, land, all of it recorded in the very rocks themselves for those with the wit to read what’s set there.”


Nope. Geology rocks, geography's where it's at.

At the time of writing it's heavily overpriced for something so miniscule.

I don't recommend it until it's on sale.

Title: 球状闪电
Author: Liu Cixin
Publisher: 科幻世界·中国科幻基石丛书
My Review:
This is a new author for me but I'm liking the inherent approach - the entire story is actually a long thought experiment that is explored on delicious detail, while the people involved are merely the props that keep events moving. If you're looking for character development, those isn't it.

Ball Lightning takes a look at... ball lightning... Going into experiments, weaponization, approach, histories, attempts. The best parts are the Russian experiments and the moment when an experiment succeeded because there was an observer unaccounted, that was a chilling moment.

However towards the end the story felt a bit stretched and there was too much attention on Li Yun, where I was happy with the bland psychopathic personality, the fleshing out felt unnecessary and uninteresting.

Title: The Wandering Earth
Author: Liu Cixin
Publisher: Beijing Guomi Digital Technology Co., Ltd.

Title: All This I Will Give to You
Author: Dolores Redondo
My Review:
Got this as part of Kindle First. Overall it's an OK mystery, the setting explores a romanticized vision of Galicia, its locales and communities. The mystery that needs unraveling is done slowly over the course of a meandering story and each piece of information is drip-fed by the characters with perfectly clear recollection of events occurring decades ago. It's excruciatingly slow, so don't expect a fast paced thriller, it's meant to be more of an exposition and experience with a mystery thrown in.

Also there are a lot of BMWs.

Title: Only Human (Themis Files, #3)
Author: Sylvain Neuvel
My Review:
Remember that massive, heavy hand discovered in Book #1?

It's finally put to use here to lay out the social and political commentary.

This comes at the expense of good storytelling, as the author attempts to cram everything that's wrong with the world today, sweeping aside what actually made the series good to begin with.

IMO the first two of the series are worth reading, this can be skipped.

Title: Le Manoir de l'horreur, Tome 1 (Le Manoir de l'horreur, #1)
Author: Ochazukenori

Title: Hild (The Hild Sequence, #1)
Author: Nicola Griffith
My Review:
I actually bought this based on the cover, something I don't often do, but the simple cover conveyed a lot. Just by looking at it, I felt - historical fiction, the early days of Britain, and her role in all this.

Initially, the language feels authentic and rich and paints a nice world to imagine. I read on hoping that some of the aspects of the story would be clarified or explained in some way. But it never happens. Words are introduced and in a way that make them a vital part of the story; and I believe this is where the digital editing falls flat. The publishers have simply 'published' a book with no effort at making some of the details accessible. The glossary should be at the front in this case - the reader then knows to bookmark and jump back and forth. Glossary aside, the publishers have made no effort to incorporate Kindle X-Ray information to assist the reader. This book needed these features to help. Either that, or the author needed to tone down the rapid fire a few notches.

From the middle of the book onwards I struggled to keep track of the relevant and irrelevant characters and though I did my best to follow along I was merely skimming the surface.

A decent atmospheric story overall, let down by overzealous pedantry.

Title: Magician: Master (The Riftwar Saga, #2)
Author: Raymond E. Feist
My Review:
The first book, [b:Magician: Apprentice|13812|Magician Apprentice (The Riftwar Saga, #1)|Raymond E. Feist|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1408317983s/13812.jpg|15983] was a beginner's introduction to the world and in fact felt quite amateurish. This sequel, Master, read a lot better. The story really picks up in meaningful ways, and several threads are connected to each other. The 'otherworlders' are nicely introduced and having Pug/Laurie's stories is a great way to view their way of life and structure.

Very pleasant to read this new 'uplifted' story.

Title: Magician: Apprentice (The Riftwar Saga, #1)
Author: Raymond E. Feist
My Review: Interesting premise. Having read [b:Daughter of the Empire|589979|Daughter of the Empire (The Empire Trilogy, #1)|Raymond E. Feist|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1404668411s/589979.jpg|2960453] long before this, I only recently discovered it's part of a larger world.  This is an interesting look at the 'original' side of the rift.  The world is well introduced as are the 'mysterious' aliens from the other side.

Title: Iron Gold (Red Rising Saga, #4)
Author: Pierce Brown
My Review: Sad to say, this just didn't work. The new characters introduced were simply not interesting to me. It was an immense struggle to focus on their stories, in fact it took half a month. Eventually finished but a valuable lesson learned - don't be afraid to stop reading a book no matter how fond of the series your are

Title: Star Wars: Darth Vader, Vol. 1: Vader
Author: Kieron Gillen

Title: Persepolis Rising (The Expanse #7)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review:
This one caught me by surprise - I had no idea a new Expanse book was ready. And so much had changed. If the Goodreads awards actually took place at a non-idiotic, somewhat-sensible time (end of the year) this likely deserved a place there. Unfortunately it's likely this book will be overlooked in the next cycle.

James Holden is now Olden! The time period has shifted decades since the last book and the human universe looks a lot different than it did in the past. And the Roci's crew is older, wiser. The years have made them comfortable with each other in a way of a family.

There's now a face to a more powerful enemy than before - the Laconians. I actually liked a lot of the people from their side. Singh, with his inexperience, sent in as nothing more than a symbolic scapegoat. They knew full well he would fail at his job. Trejo, he just exudes warmth and villainy. And above all, Duarte - his way of thinking big and long term.

Most of the story is the crew of the Roci now on Medina station, fighting back against the cruel authority and working on their escape plan. All the while fighting their own inner battles, it was quite insightful to see how unhinged Amos was getting, Bobbi with her brief taste of captaincy, Naomi+Jim and their inability to escape saving people again. We see a lot of people at their prime, especially Naomi, Bobbi and their planning; despite knowing how the plans would go, it was still a thrill to read the planning and execution. To see these old timers working here felt like them performing their swan song (albeit across the next 3 books)

What I liked most was the way the Expanse 'universe' had been set up for us in all the previous 6 books but it gets upended in a smooth, logical way to something I hadn't expected at all. Further, I greatly disliked #6 (Babylon's Ashes) and it seems like a lot of the slowness there was just a goodbye to the 'younger' crew and making way for the 'older' more experienced.

Title: Sleeping Giants (Themis Files, #1)
Author: Sylvain Neuvel
My Review:
Enjoyable in terms of concept but the whole interview/conversation or report style really didn't work. A lot of conversations occurred that simply wouldn't in such scenarios. Some parts of it did work, except when they had to describe something that was happening. "Oh no I fell down, now I am lying in such-and-such position"

Did keep reading it though, for the scifi/alien story which was kept sufficiently mysterious and interesting.

Title: Provenance (Imperial Radch)
Author: Ann Leckie
My Review:
Enjoyable if you go in with the right expectations. In the same universe as the Radch series, this is a much lighter/somewhat humorous story set in a specific, limited area. There's a lot of talk and a minor bit of action, best not go in expecting the 'larger' scope of story as the Radch series did.

Overall found it enjoyable, and the main protag - Ingray - was pleasant to read, and her companions are each distinct and entertaining in themselves.

Title: All Systems Red (The Murderbot Diaries, #1)
Author: Martha Wells
My Review:
Nice charming intro to the Murderbot; it's a short story but packed with insights into its personality. Its dislike of people, attempts at hiding its emotional reactions, and even its deductive abilities.

Short, quick read, definitely worth picking up.

Title: The Dispossessed: An Ambiguous Utopia
Author: Ursula K. Le Guin
My Review: This story is actually more of a discussion on the various aspects, advantages disadvantages, beauty imperfections, hypocrisy debauchery... of anarchy, democracy, capitalism, socialism and everything in between. It will feel slow if you're expecting a paced sci-fi. There's no real climax and no real conclusion, keep that in mind and you'll enjoy this one

Title: Diplomatic Immunity (Vorkosigan Saga, #13)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review:
At last another great Miles story after the poor [b:Komarr|61884|Komarr (Vorkosigan Saga, #11)|Lois McMaster Bujold|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1322572043s/61884.jpg|1129294] and [b:A Civil Campaign|61899|A Civil Campaign (Vorkosigan Saga, #12)|Lois McMaster Bujold|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1386924032s/61899.jpg|1093445] -
I'm glad I didn't abandon the series there. Miles is back in form this time, not the bumbling Auditor he was in Komarr, but the original diplomat with his fast thinking, reasoning and his care for everyone, the guy in charge. I believe this has been one of his best performances and looking at the publication order and the gap till the next, the author may have been deciding to end this at a high for him.

It feels full circle as this time the story takes place in the Quaddie's zone, reminiscent of how everything first started in [b:Falling Free|61915|Falling Free (Vorkosigan Saga, #4)|Lois McMaster Bujold|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1386922931s/61915.jpg|2277408] - and there was a reference to Silver and Leo in the ballet as well! It's great to see a closure of sorts for Bel. Ekaterin was slightly useful this time too, mostly by being out of the way, for which I was grateful.

Title: Children of Time (Children of Time, #1)
Author: Adrian Tchaikovsky
My Review:
Either you know what a monkey is or you don't know what a monkey is. Stay consistent!

This novel was marred by a single moment. A single, completely unnecessary moment. It was meant to be minor, maybe even lighthearted, but it basically spoiled the rest of the story as I was then stuck with the stupidity of that moment throughout the book.

That moment is this - at one point, the crew of a ship did not know what a monkey was. Yep, just that. It was just casually thrown however if it had been a piece of forgotten information, that should have reflected throughout the book. It wasn't reflected. The crew used it a few times as an epithet (these monkeys...) demonstrating an understanding of monkey mannerisms, they knew of the verb to ape, at one point an oblique ancestry is mentioned (distant monkey descendants...). Proofread. Stay consistent in your backstory. If you are truly going to pretend nobody knows what they are, then remove references to it. If they have just discovered what they are, spend some time with the crew's reactions to this distant cousin.

The crew knew everything else though, somehow they knew ants and spiders and clowns. Clowns. In the context of the story, a lot of things could have been forgotten, I would expect clowns to be forgotten before monkeys.

That's why it was a 'fly in the delicious pudding' - it was completely unnecessary and the story could have done simply without it. Monkeys were mentioned, move on. Pudding is good.

That aside, it's overall very imaginative and ambitious scifi with a satisfying ending.

Title: We Are Legion (We Are Bob) (Bobiverse, #1)
Author: Dennis E. Taylor
My Review:
Cleverly written with a good dose of humor, it's scifi that doesn't take itself too seriously. And despite that there are some thought provoking scenarios that are presented in a very accessible way; space battles were a big one, the author did a good job of describing the distances and times involved, and the abilities of the replicants to work in milliseconds made it all the better. Further challenges were the global 'earth' problems and solutions, the manufacturing, isolation of other replicants and how they evolved among themselves. Really good range of topics.

Only negative - I didn't enjoy the excessive StarTrek/BSG/StarWars references, I think that could have been toned down.

Also wanted to point out that IPv8 wasn't necessary - the IPv6 address space can cover far more than every galaxy and at that point in time the IANA would no longer be relevant, so address space allocation would be at Bob's discretion.

Title: Mirror Dance (Vorkosigan Saga, #8)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review:
This felt like the darkest in the series so far, it's a bit about Mark and a bit about Miles, and some major changes to our well known characters. The initial introduction to Mark makes him feel loathsome and towards the end, your feelings towards him have completely changed. He redeems himself to himself and everyone else. That made for some pretty good writing.

Does a great job of showcasing the differences between the two. Ending felt a bit soppy but so far it's one of the best in the entire series

Title: Komarr (Vorkosigan Saga, #11)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review:
I'm now of the opinion that the previous book in the chronology - [b:Memory|61880|Memory (Vorkosigan Saga, #10)|Lois McMaster Bujold|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1460274588s/61880.jpg|3036720] - should have been the end of this saga. The old Miles that we knew is absent, so is the scifi/space-opera aspect. The investigation going on in this book is merely a side-act; the characters involved in that investigation exude stupidity. The author does not normally write characters this half-baked and I wonder if the series has run its course or if they are trying to reinvent everything.

The quality of characters has been compromised to bring to the forefront a character that I absolutely did not care about - Ekaterin - who is going to be an important part of Miles life. The presence of Ekaterin in the story really dampens Miles' role and and I feel restrains him from being his usual great self.

A bigger decision for me now is whether to continue the series - and keep this spoiled taste in my mouth - or stop and let my Memories (hah!) remain about one of my fondest series.

Title: Memory (Vorkosigan Saga, #10)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review:
Slowest of the Vorkosigan series - a lot of nothing happens, though it leads to the second half of the story, which was absolutely riveting.

But there's a lot more to this book - it's a big crossroads in the series. A lot of major changes happening, our cast of characters are growing older, more mature and moving on with the new directions in their lives.

Miles was fired from ImpSec. Galeni, still under the label of Komarran, has to wade his way through prejudice. Emperor Gregor is getting married. Illyan is no longer ImpSec, his subordinate sabotaged his memory chip, but ever-brilliant Miles (who was on a long, utterly boring introspection leave) figured things out. And became Imperial Auditor. That probably ends his dealings with the Dendarii fleet... who will also be missed

The next book, I think, will be crucial in terms of the Vorkosigan story - I will subconsciously (or consciously...) be comparing it with his time with the fleet and if found lacking, I'll attempt to forget anything happened after this.

Could have been 4 or 5 stars, if not for the filler and introspection going on.

Title: Death's End (Remembrance of Earth’s Past, #3)
Author: Liu Cixin
My Review:
This is for the trilogy as a whole. Like many others are finding, it's hard to describe. It starts with [b:The Three-Body Problem|20518872|The Three-Body Problem (Remembrance of Earth’s Past #1)|Liu Cixin|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1415428227s/20518872.jpg|25696480] of a few people and small scope of mostly just Earth. It then moves to [b:The Dark Forest|23168817|The Dark Forest (Remembrance of Earth’s Past, #2)|Cixin Liu|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1412064931s/23168817.jpg|42713958] with more people involved and a larger scope of the solar system, nearby local cluster. And finally it arrives at the finale of this journey with an absolutely massive scope. However - just like the first book - it's not for everyone and a lot of it comes down to characterization. None of the characters have any meaning, despite there being a protagonist, they are all props. The real story is happening all around, and this is not a common concept in many other books, so this story can feel very dismal. It is a bit of a mind shift and once accustomed to the author's tone, everything falls into place.

This third book reads more as a documentary than as a story like the first two books. Yet it's the most gripping of the three, and to be honest it's also the most terrifying. Each new idea or concept that emerges is interesting and the author manages to turn it into yet another reason to fear everything.

The main protagonist here, Cheng Xin, is a moron. There isn't really a better way to put it, but for some reason it didn't seem to matter; the people just don't matter in the overall scheme of what's actually happening.

What's most enjoyable about this is the fresh, complicated ideas crammed in every chapter. It's like reading some Asimov for the first time, a new world of ideas and concepts opens up, those ideas are built upon, torn down, resurrected in new ways... there isn't a way to recreate it afterwards. But the feeling lingers and it's enjoyable.

I'll be having a look at some of the other offerings by this author but won't be expecting another journey like this one.

Title: The Three-Body Problem (Remembrance of Earth’s Past, #1)
Author: Liu Cixin
My Review:
This isn't going to be for everyone, I could tell right away it's going to be a marmite. It feels like ideological debates wrapped up inside a hard-scifi story.

Character development is not a prime concern here, the characters are merely the props, the bigger story is happening at a larger scale. I find this far more preferable - while authors always need characters to serve a 'purpose' in a story, quite often they will wrap the character up with some cringe inducing personality. There are no qualms here, everyone is just an idea and the real focus here is the grand interstellar story.

Most enjoyable is the thought process - people thinking in long terms, decades, centuries; actions and consequences. Deciphering and understanding what may seem like initially vague words or actions into concrete explanations.

I've not read something like this before which made it very interesting. A lot of concepts used as part of strategies were very cleverly woven together, but enjoying them does require a bit of understanding up front, although the author did sometimes make an effort to put on a bit of exposition for concepts that weren't always understood.

The most interesting bit was the initial exclamation at sending two protons to Earth, to the actual process and explanation of their construction and their purpose on Earth. It was both fascinating and terrifying at the same time.

Furthermore, confirmed from seeing other reviews, listening to the audiobook for this one is a mistake.

Title: The Dark Forest (Remembrance of Earth’s Past, #2)
Author: Liu Cixin

Title: The Long Way to a Small, Angry Planet (Wayfarers, #1)
Author: Becky Chambers
My Review:
A crew of diverse happy happy species wander the galaxy in their happy happy ship, taking comfort in their diversity and quirkiness and happy happy camaraderie; accomplishing almost nothing related to the plotline but that's OK because they're all super besties! A lot of subtext and conversations revolve around the concept of being yourself or figuring out who you are, at the expense of the actual story.

Kizzy, I feel, is one of the most unlikable characters I have encountered in a long time; a zero responsibility adult who is, like, so quirky, but like such a zany nerd, like a really quirky nerd, you are reminded of the quirkiness every other sentence.

Rosemary, one of the main characters, feels like a background character. Even her reveal, halfway through the book, felt forced and contrived.

For some reason, while reading this book I kept thinking of the phrase "safe space". This book takes place in a safe space instead of outer space.

Title: The Positronic Man (Robot, #0.6)
Author: Isaac Asimov
My Review:
At the heart of it, this is a discussion or debate around what it means to be human. This story was quite far from the rosy picture that the movie Bicentennial Man had painted, a lot more of it was around Andrew's pursuit of recognition and what he believed in.

It's all hypothetical of course and would such a thing would never happen, I'd still be conflicted about what the right answer is around the questions that Andrew managed to raise time and time again.

I felt sad for Andrew at times, especially towards the latter half as he was essentially alone even at death (despite Hsing being there).

Title: The Blight of Muirwood (Legends of Muirwood, #2)
Author: Jeff Wheeler

Title: The Wretched of Muirwood (Legends of Muirwood, #1)
Author: Jeff Wheeler

Author: Frank Goldammer

Author: Miles  Cameron

Title: The Red Knight (The Traitor Son Cycle, #1)
Author: Miles  Cameron
My Review:
The frequent and numerous switching POV really breaks the storytelling. The chapters felt completely meaningless as each chapter was divided into these disjointed POVs - either do away with the chapters or respect their boundaries.

Despite the early promising start, the entire narrative lost its cohesiveness and simply splattered into confusion like diarrhea.

Title: The Paper Menagerie and Other Stories
Author: Ken Liu

Title: Candide

Title: A Hero Born (Legends of Condor Heroes #1)
Author: Jin Yong

Title: The Core (The Demon Cycle, #5)
Author: Peter V. Brett
My Review:
A decent ending to the series, though not particularly satisfying if you were looking for a good explanation or answers to some of the mysteries involved. I'd stop short of calling it a deus-ex though it did approach something close to it...

Part of the problem in here is now the sheer number of characters. The scope of the story is now wider than before, and that wideness makes it a bit shallow in terms of storytelling. The original main character, Arlen, is still now one-of-many. I understand the necessity of this - more people need to have their actions shown - but he still receives very little time.

Some threads get tied up pretty well - It's good to see the various squabbling factions putting their differences aside out of necessity, or at least resolve them for a little while. The looming threat's importance is made quite clear to everyone.

While it's always great to see strong female leads in a story, it needs to be balanced out properly to give it some context. In my opinion, this series has not done well in that aspect and has gone for the easier approach of "woman smart, man dumb" trope - the male leads are either gone or relegated to background roles; those that stick around are constantly being put down or shouted at. Reminds me of the Wheel of Time series - minus the braid tugging and sniffing.

The 'tension' of the previous books is gone. The humans have gotten better at fighting the demons so the original fear that pervaded demon encounters was now a matter of just getting the encounter over with while everyone draws wards faster than breathing. However this was to be expected, after all it was Arlen and Rojer's purpose to make people stronger by giving them the necessary tools.

The conversations between Jardir and Arlen were well done - the constant undercurrent of challenge and rivalry was well written as their stories progressed. They have matured well through their experiences over time and with each other. But as I said before - not much screen time or development! It's not enjoyable when a series goes from 1 protagonist to 20, much more preferable when this is done from book 1 rather than book 3, because the expectation is usually set early on.

Overall - nowhere near the hyped 5* reviews this book is currently receiving, but not so bad either. A good simple series to read.

Title: La Belle Sauvage (The Book of Dust, #1)
Author: Philip Pullman
My Review:
Serves as a prequel to the His Dark Materials trilogy, found the story to be slow but engaging.

The good parts, nicely written characters and minor hints and developments. The supporting characters are pretty well done too. The relationships between the characters and their daemons is always a pleasure to read. It's great to revisit the world of dust, witches, gyptians, daemons, Steam punk and magic.

The not so good parts, the story leans on references to the original trilogy quite a bit and there are several appearances by characters which I felt served no real purpose, and could have been done without. The middle of the story drags on and at times felt interminably repetitive.

Though I'm interested in the next in the series, considering the semi cliffhanger this ended on I suggest to my future self - wait for the series to compete

Title: The Death of Ivan Ilyich (Russian Texts)
Author: Leo Tolstoy
My Review:
Great writing, made me actually feel some of the suffering that Ivan was going through. It made me thoughtful enough to re-evaluate my own life, hope that it's one I'll be satisfied with.

Genuinely felt sorry for poor Ivan.

Don't worry Ivan, I hate your family too. I am glad you found peace.

Title: Oathbringer (The Stormlight Archive, #3)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
tl;dr - Gripping story with fantastic revelations, spoiled by too much Shallan and not enough of anyone else.

Story-wise, I'm glad to have re-read the previous books just before release date. It greatly helped with picking up on references which would have been lost otherwise, there's so much going on it's easy to forget. The war is now a real thing, it's begun and hands are being revealed, even more mysteries are raising questions.

Dalinar was... amazing. The flashbacks combined with the finale, deftly woven together and blended in to the overall story, that writing felt like a piece of art in itself - well done to the author. Of everyone in there, his development was the most enjoyable. Around him, the story flowed and was truly brought to life. Though not a king, he felt grander than one.

Shallan was annoying. Sad to say I didn't enjoy reading her parts. She's doing too much, all the time. One moment she's lamenting herself, the next she is playing multiple people, multiple powers, multiple quests, multiple achievements, multiple interests. The result is that her part in the story is stretched-out, shallow and ultimately felt meaningless to me. It's lucky that she was surrounded by others who progressed at a better, more meaningful rate.

Kaladin was reduced. Though featured, it sometimes felt like he was added in as an afterthought, with not enough 'meat'. He fulfilled some roles but spent time running around. In the afterglow of finishing the book, his story was the least distinct. Hmm. I've seen this in other series before - the author starts ignoring one of the main characters, bringing others to the front and I sincerely hope this does not carry on in the next book. I do half worry that at some point BranSan will simply kill him off. Or worse, forget about him.

Jasnah was ignored - she returns from the dead and... nothing? I would have thought her relationship with her ward would have been explored further, but again, due to Shallan's superhero status, this part just falters.

Szeth felt fresh - had not expected such a turnaround, and I feel his 'conflict' with everyone else will come to the fore in the next book, looking forward to it. After all, the assassin is here, in the middle of the thing he started!

There are others who became a bit more interesting this time - Navani, Renarin. And Wit.

Aside from the characters, something that really surprised me - the number of typos and spelling/grammatical mistakes. Perhaps the proofreaders were enjoying themselves too much to notice? Luckily - Kindle has a report content feature, so hopefully this made its way back to the publishers. Or not.

Overall - compared to the first two, this third book isn't as fast paced, nor does it have as many moments where you're experiencing this world for the first time. Instead - the world building is pretty much done, people are now being moved into place and stories, conflicts and plots are progressing.

As always, my favourite series. I hope I am not dead by the time the 10th book is out.

Title: The Case of the Famished Parson (Chief Inspector Littlejohn #15)
Author: George Bellairs

Title: A Quiet Life in the Country (Lady Hardcastle Mysteries, #1)
Author: T.E. Kinsey

Title: The Way of Kings (The Stormlight Archive, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
Despite being one of the best books I've ever read, this book receives a low rating from me. Here's why: book 1 came out in 2010. Book 2 is coming out in 2013. This series is planned to be 10 books long. Which means, if everything is alright and there are no unexpected developments or surprised, at the absolute very least, it will take around 25 to 30 years for it to complete.

There's no way this can last. There are too many variables involved, especially for someone as busy as this particular author is. The author may lose interest, or I might, or it might take longer. I might be dead before this series is over. So I could end up going to go to my grave not knowing how this ends.

As for the story itself, it's fantastic - there are twists and turns constantly and the best part is how they are almost always completely unexpected. My favorite part is how nothing in the story is wasted. Every seemingly insignificant detail is significant and in some surprising way. The history, lore, flora, fauna, traditions, eccentricities are all thought out and explained well.

I'd definitely recommend this but only if at least 5 books of the series are already out and the storytelling hasn't faltered or gotten lost.

But until then, low rating.

Title: Child of the Flames (The Seven Signs, #1)
Author: D.W. Hawkins
My Review:
I found one of the protagonists, Shawana, was too jarring to read. She starts out as the victim, struggling, but is later revealed to be a complete asshole who spends most of the time shouting, glaring, staring, scolding and just being a general condescending prickleboar.

The other two are overpowered wizards and it's completely who put up with her.

There is an ok story with very black and white characters. The villains are evil and the good guys are the shining beacons of virtue in this ugly world.

Title: A Column of Fire (Kingsbridge, #3)
Author: Ken Follett
My Review:
It's always been great to read about this little part of England with its people, their squabbles and the way the threats and evildoers tend to hang over people's happiness for decades.

Although this is third in the Kingsbridge series, I wouldn't consider it part of this series; the town which has featured so prominently in the previous two now serves as a minor backdrop.

Instead the scope of the story is spread across several countries/cities which weren't Kingsbridge. It felt like there were a series of historical places, names and events which were being included for the sake of being ticked off a list, not annoying but at times it felt a bit gratuitous and may have contributed towards a less tightly-knit tale.

The main characters were as strong and memorable as ever. Ned, Margery, Sylvie, Alison, Pierre, Rollo, Barney, Bart. Well developed in good measure and necessary to the overall story. The geographic span of the story however caused events, plots and villains to feel vast and distant.

What I liked most was the insight into the religious conflicts and what drove the hatred and motivations of people at the time. Why the countries went to war and cared so much about who the monarch was; why the people cared about who the monarch was. It's easy to take a lot of today's freedoms for granted but this glimpse into the past does put it into perspective. It's not perfect in this day and age but is certainly better.

As a standalone historical story, it can stand on its own and is pretty entertaining overall.
As a Kingsbridge story, it doesn't hold any of the charm and fascination that the #1 and #2 did, it was just out-of-place.

Title: The Murder of Roger Ackroyd (Hercule Poirot, #4)
Author: Agatha Christie

Title: ジパング　深蒼海流（８） (モーニングコミックス) (Japanese Edition)
Author: Kaiji Kawaguchi

Title: The Stone Sky
Author: N.K. Jemisin
My Review:
A decent ending to the trilogy overall, though by no means the amazing gushfest that the reviews would lead me to believe. However it's as satisfying as trilogies go.

We're finally told the backstory of how the world came to be, though I feel it would have been better if it didn't go into too much detail; there are times when the author needed to talk about objects from the point-of-view of a civilisation that has lost technology, so many things were described in vague uncertain terms which broke the prose and immersion. (A thing started glowing and another thing started glowing but differently near this first thing...).

Essun and Nassun on their respective quests do eventually meet and it is melancholy and satisfying, seeing the gulf between them and the eventual conclusion. Their journeys were well done and illustrated nicely just how their motivations had been shaped simply due to circumstances and environments.

Now that all 3 books are out, recommended reading.

Title: A Civil Campaign (Vorkosigan Saga, #12)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review:
Too much soap.
Not enough space.

Title: Einstein's Beetle: Newton's Laws of Motion and Gravity, and Einstein's Theory of Relativity An Explanation for Peasants by a Peasant who Understands
Author: Mark Southworth

Title: MASTERキートン 1 完全版 (Master Keaton kanzenban, #1)
Author: Hokusei Katsushika
Additional Authors: Naoki Urasawa, Takashi Nagasaki, 浦沢直樹, 勝鹿 北星, 長崎尚志

Title: The Wolf of the North (Wolf of the North #1)
Author: Duncan M. Hamilton

Title: Beren and Lúthien
Author: J.R.R. Tolkien
My Review:
It's more of a collection of snippets and passages around the story of Beren/Luthien than it being one continuous story. The author goes on to show how the tale evolved over time and it's a great insight once more into the mind of JRRT. It's somewhat nostalgic reading about middle earth again, and his steady, familiar writing style.

I would have removed "Beren" from the title as Luthien appears to be doing all the work.

There are also quite a few poems in here, of which I'm not really a fan so I slogged through it.

Title: Tower Lord (Raven's Shadow, #2)
Author: Anthony Ryan
My Review:
Going from one of the best books I've read in a while to one of the biggest let-downs in a sequel, I can at last experience the very same intensity of the disappointment that my parents must feel for me.

I can't really understand what must have happened after the writing of the first book and before the writing of this one; the first was well written, tight storyline and a great main character whose story you wanted to follow. Was it marketing pressures? Was it some rabbit-hole of an idea with blinker vision? Publishers forcing their views on the author?

The supporting cast were interesting in [b:Blood Song|13569581|Blood Song (Raven's Shadow, #1)|Anthony Ryan|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1421573407s/13569581.jpg|19148922], but what is important to note is that they were entirely defined by their interactions with Vaelin. They were interesting only when observed and dealing with Vaelin. There was absolutely no doubt about this being Vaelin's story through and through.

Here, with Vaelin fulfilling his role as a cameo, they become a set of walking cliches and Mary Sues gallivanting across the continent spouting poor dialogue.

Taking them out of that context and putting them center-stage, it felt awkward, the flow and prose of the original story is broken and can no longer be recovered.

This actually reminded me of Joe Abercrombie's [b:Half a King|18666047|Half a King (Shattered Sea, #1)|Joe Abercrombie|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1389378321s/18666047.jpg|25641726] and its sequels. A very interesting character with a strong compelling story, who's relegated to the sidelines and the background while other uninteresting meatbags bumble their way around us.

Title: The Grace of Kings (The Dandelion Dynasty, #1)
Author: Ken Liu

Title: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone (Harry Potter, #1)
Author: J.K. Rowling
My Review: Everyone is really obsessed with house points so they can win the house cup at the end of the year. Meanwhile a bunch of other stuff happens.

Author: Yoshihiro Yamada
My Review: It's a historical fiction and a focus on tea ceremony and the aesthetes of the late 1500s in Japan (around the time of Nobunaga).   Overall it's quite a unique manga but understandably not well known - the story is simple but the details are interesting.

Title: アポカリプスの砦 1 [Apocalypse no Toride 1] (Fortress of the Apocalypse, #1)
Author: Yuu Kuraishi

Author: Bella Forrest
My Review: Flimsy premise with poor foundations on the existence of the two sides. Dull characters, turned even worse when this turned into a basic generic YA piece.

Author: Jim  Butcher

Title: A Time to Kill
Author: John Grisham
My Review: Interesting view of race and prejudices in the backdrop of a small-town event with realistic small-town people. It's a good mixture of serious with a few bits of kindness and humor in between, overall a decent read.

Title: A Crucible of Souls (Sorcery Ascendant Sequence, #1)
Author: Mitchell Hogan

Title: Fate of Perfection (Finding Paradise #1)
Author: K.F. Breene
My Review: This was part of Amazon Kindle first, marketed as science fiction. While it does have elements of sci-fi present, most of the plot revolves around a particularly manly man, with a manly voice and manly shoulders. His particular manliness is so manly that I continued reading until the regretful end. I'm certainly not the target demographic for this one.

Title: Half a War (Shattered Sea, #3)
Author: Joe Abercrombie
My Review:
Far removed from the original direction of the first, this third book now focuses on a few new characters and their roles in the greater war. Which is all well and good, except that the original hook, the reason for being for this story, is gone. Yarvi is now a background character, his schemes and motivations are unknown, his vengeance receives very little time. If this was supposed to be a multi character series the entire time, it really should have been so from the first, not halfway through.

Also, shitty romance persists. The author really needs to... not do romance. His war and gore and battle and politics and story twists are his strengths.

Title: Half the World (Shattered Sea, #2)
Author: Joe Abercrombie
My Review: Pretty good sequel to Half A King, but not with Yarvi as the main; instead you have two younger "fighters" starting out on their paths, and their stories intertwining with the originals. A bit of Hollywood tropes rears its ugly head, with a cringer of a romance shoved in - it's one of those dumb ones where nobody speaks during a misunderstanding which could have resolved the whole thing and not wasted our time but half the entire story relies on this. Hopefully we will not be seeing another in the third part of this series.

Title: The Woman Who Breathed Two Worlds (Malayan #1)
Author: Selina Siak Chin Yoke

Title: Grunt: The Curious Science of Humans at War
Author: Mary Roach

Title: Crimes Against Magic (Hellequin Chronicles, #1)
Author: Steve McHugh
My Review:
I snorted when i saw the hubris of this passage:

" It was about vampires and werewolves and the love of a good woman. Apparently it had a lot of fans. I wasn’t amongst them. About thirty pages in and I’d already come to the conclusion that it was shit, but I figured it could only get better. I’d managed another twenty or so pages, with a solidifying belief that I’d been right all along,"

Also thanks to this book, I learned of a trope I've encountered frequently but didn't know a name for: A Marty Stu - http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MartyStu

Author: Stephen        King
My Review:
A sort of 'time travel' story, about Jack Epping who goes back in time to try and stop the JFK assassination. But the main story is about him and his time spent in the US from 1958 till 1963, the people he meets and the lives he intersects. More importantly, the choices he makes. Overall it's a very 'human' story.

Normally I don't enjoy Stephen King's books, and as usual I felt the book - at times - felt a bit longer than it should have been; it would go on and on uselessly at times, but the storytelling and overall backdrop just seemed to work really well in this case, so I didn't mind the rambling or the romance either. It worked well.

Title: World Without End (Kingsbridge, #2)
Author: Ken Follett
My Review:
After enjoying 'Pillars of the Earth', it was good to get back into that world once more. A lot of things felt quite familiar - there were the usual small town folk with their petty ways, the lechery, the manipulative clergy, the forward thinkers and the absolute villains.

In this book however, I found the characters a lot more likable - the villains included. It was quite good to see their motivations, deceptions and deviousness, thoroughly enjoyable. It was also a treat to see the never ending adversities faced while our various protagonists and antagonists went about their goals. And the construction involved too.

In a similar vein, we watch the fates of an entire generation centered around a town.

Sometimes the messages the author was inserting were a bit too obvious and at times immersion-breaking. Some of the characters thought and spoke in a manner similar to people today, even some of the expressions were very weird to encounter. One example of language is 'piss off' - which was first used in the early 1900s. Not getting to deep into other examples but you'll know them when you see the gay rights, the social changes, the 'forward thinking'... not in a bad way, just in a weird way.


Good enjoyable read - if you liked Pillars of the Earth and the environment around it, this one's perfect to get back into it

Title: The Moon is a Harsh Mistress
Author: Robert A. Heinlein
My Review:
This story was pretty much a meta view of a revolution - a few core characters and events while large scale events happen and are spoken of, not usually seen. It has a few other interesting things, namely the ideological discussions, interesting characters (Mike above all), tensions between Moon and Earth and just how the revolution would take place. It's all a big game where you already know what's going to happen, the interesting bit is learning how it happens.

I wasn't going to read it as I've not enjoyed any of this author's other books but the preview seemed interesting enough.

Title: As The Crow Flies (DI Nick Dixon, #1)
Author: Damien Boyd

Title: Rage (Teodor Szacki, #3)
Author: Zygmunt Miloszewski
My Review:
Labeled as a crime/thriller, it has elements I don't see often in other of the same category. It has refreshing doses of humor in between the dark subject matter. The book manages to not take itself too seriously but at the same time keeps things level.

Cliches are at a minimum - you can't write one of these without a bunch of rinsed and repeated devices, but there aren't the annoyingly ubiquitous ones, like the washed out detective who's tired of life, with the only recourse to drown in alcohol.

Although this is 3rd in a series, it's modular enough so that you don't need to know about the previous ones.

Some parts of the narrative felt unnecessary, such as some people being described as 'a person' with an entire chapter talking about what this person is doing, without actually naming them. With enough instances of these, it was at times a bit confusing. Eventually it gets resolved and you realize who they are but I'm not a fan of this kind of 'switch' of narrative.

Despite that, I did enjoy the story; the city with 11 lakes, flawed characters and all.

Title: 海の御先 12 (ジェッツコミックス) (Japanese Edition)
Author: Kou Fumizuki

Title: The Wheel of Osheim (The Red Queen's War, #3)
Author: Mark  Lawrence

Title: A Court of Mist and Fury (A Court of Thorns and Roses, #2)
Author: Sarah J. Maas

Title: The Queen's Poisoner (Kingfountain, #1)
Author: Jeff Wheeler
My Review:
Nice, easy read with likeable characters. Recommended.

The world building is done at a gradual pace, and the 'magic' isn't overwhelming or over-the-top. It's nice and subtle, with bits of intrigue and twists.

Strangely, the only annoying bit I found was the book's namesake - the Queen's Poisoner - I found her to be the flattest, most boring character of all. Her only purpose, it seemed, was to look sad and pale and graceful and to be hugged by Owen and to hug Owen and tussle his hair and smile and continue being sick and sad.

And to speak to him like an idiot. "Do you know what an idiot means, Owen?" And Owen, who normally is quite a clever boy, would shake his head like an idiot. And she would look sad and smile and be pale and tussle his hair and he would hug her and she kissed his forehead - JUST STOP ALREADY

For this reason, I noticed that I didn't care too much for her 'part' in the story, despite it being the most important.

That was the only negative but it didn't really feel like it spoiled the overall book.

Title: The Shadow of the Wind (The Cemetery of Forgotten Books, #1)
Author: Carlos Ruiz Zafón
My Review:
Too much literature. Not enough story.

A perpetually libidinous protagonist attempts to solve a mystery in the midst of a colorful cast of characters; the plot meanders between the quirky lives of the inhabitants of this town and glimpses of the investigation in the backdrop. Despite pages and pages of reading though, I often felt that not much happens. More time was spent on the colorful writing style and not enough on actually resolving anything.

Title: Sharp Ends
Author: Joe Abercrombie
My Review:
The first chapter references Glotka. That's a teaser.

The rest of the book does not reference Glotka. That's a disappointment.

Overall OK, some of the characters are hilarious (Shev and Javre), most felt like a miss.

Title: The Shadow of What Was Lost (The Licanius Trilogy, #1)
Author: James  Islington
My Review:
I struggled with the story here - a set of actually very interesting and likable characters in a somewhat disjointed and mysterious storyline. The mysteriousness felt forced, like the book was written geared for an episodic TV show rather than a book; as a result there were a lot of people who know things but feel like they shouldn't explain it. Instead they will say something like 'do this' or 'follow me' - you'll understand when we get there, or some day, somesuch.

The whole book felt like this pretty much

Title: A Shadow in Summer (Long Price Quartet, #1)
Author: Daniel Abraham
My Review:
This is a book about posing with bits of a story of some sort mixed in.

Each character spends a lot of time communicating by posing. Unfortunately while it may have been meant to convey a 'different' kind of civilization where things were formal and graceful, it was just a bit too much. There was one page where a character took on three different poses, each one more elaborate than the last.

So I could not read through all the posing without imagining things like...

He took a pose of affirmation with an undertone halfway between accusation and reluctance



Unfortunately for me, between the several made up words and over-the-top posing, any enjoyment was spoiled.

Title: The Shadow of the Torturer (The Book of the New Sun, #1)
Author: Gene Wolfe
My Review:
Very good prose.
Barely any plot.
Meh/5

Title: Saint's Blood (Greatcoats, #3)
Author: Sebastien de Castell
My Review:
This book has one of the best openings I've ever read. Not in terms of first 'memorable' lines - I mean in terms of introducing you into the story. A memorable first line is something to spout at pseudointellectual battles or classrooms; a memorable first chapter is something that you experience and that sets the tone for the rest of the book. This had the perfect blend of humor as well as a gradual, expansive scene being set. Very well done.

This third book, Saint's Blood, is as serious and humorous as the series has ever been. The action doesn't stop and neither do the twists, revelations and insurmountable odds. Falcio, Kest and Brasti are tired, and you can feel it, but they keep going because it's what they must do - sounds like a dreary topic but it's very well presented. The world has been well built, there is an evil scheme afoot and plans are revealed, odds are stacked against these three and their companions; the companions aren't flat or boring, each one is distinct and nobody's presence felt like a chore, not even the Cogneti (sp?). The interjection of duelling amidst the revelations was a refreshing touch as well.

Some of the questions you'll have had in the first two books are addressed here, though not all. That's reserved for the fourth book, Tyrant's Throne (which was confusingly the working title for this book before it was changed).



Only one criticism:
Falcio is overly-coddled. Everyone else in this book knows exactly what he's thinking and the deep, hidden meaning behind his actions and they bend themselves around him to accommodate his despair and actions, wherein he will by virtue of plot armor go against the odds and win in the end anyway. In other words, it was getting a bit predictable (to me anyway).

Title: Saga, Volume 1
Author: Brian K. Vaughan
My Review:
(For ch 1 - 32)

Good art and compact storytelling in just a few frames. Towards the later volumes, some of the focus seems to be lost and a lot of characters tend to become 'exhibitions of badassery' rather than parts of the story. Overall still a good read and hopefully will get even better.

Title: The Speed of Dark
Author: Elizabeth Moon
My Review:
I am sitting on a green chair. I have finished reading this book. I should probably rate it because that's what normal people would do. But I am not a normal person. I don't need to rate a book, everyone should just understand. But I will do it anyway because normal people expect that and their faces get shiny when I don't.

I can make my kneecaps click at certain angles. Goodreads says I have to decide on a number of stars. Why do people use stars, stars are balls of incandescent gas, billions of miles away. But they are using gas to indicate how they felt about a book. That's like showing an upward thumb when you approve of something. An upward thumb should only be used to determine the direction of a magnetic field around a current, but normal people are strange like that, always doing one thing but meaning another.

I should find other ways to highlight how not normal I am. I wonder if that's something I do a lot.

I need to cut my fingernails. It is difficult to rate this book, it has a strange smell. I like to smell things and people near me, but it is hard to grasp this one. I wonder if normal people smell books, they probably don't. How can normal people read books without smelling it?

Sweat is trickling down my ass crack. I am unsure how to proceed. Goodreads says I should rate a book 1 star if I didn't like it. But that would be giving points to something I don't like. This is not right, Goodreads should not act like a normal person and say one thing but do another it is supposed to be a neutral ground of logic. I am looking at what others are doing nothing makes sense everyone is giving 5 stars to books even if they don't read it normal people are strange I am not normal I am very smart.

I have chosen three incandescent balls of gas in the heavens. These balls are not light, they are the absence of darkness. Now I should justify my rating because normal people's ears start oscillating if I don't and it is the polite thing to do.

The protagonist.

The protagonist is very smart and the author reminds us of how clever and not normal they are. The normal people are normal and not everyone understands the protagonist because he is very clever and not normal.

The others.

The others are caricatures. I would say they are black and white but they are in color, so they cannot be black and white. Television displays used to be black and white. Anyway they are all normal and everyone is either very good or very evil.

I do not understand the protagonist's motivation towards the end. It is rushed and of little import. Why do normal authors do this if I were an author I would not do this but I am not normal I am smart.

The story reminded me of Flowers for Algernon probably because it was very similar but I could not relate to the protagonist much. I am not normal.

Title: The Light of the Fireflies
Author: Paul Pen
My Review: Interesting premise, messed up story about a messed up family living in a basement.  Liked it.

Title: Gone to Sea in a Bucket (Harry Gilmour, #1)
Author: David            Black

Author: Nobuyuki Fukumoto

Title: Longitude: A journey through time, astronomy, and horology
Author: Dava Sobel

Author: 小山ゆう

Title: Blood River: A Journey to Africa’s Broken Heart
Author: Tim Butcher

Title: The Emperor's Blades (Chronicle of the Unhewn Throne, #1)
Author: Brian Staveley
My Review:
The story peaks at the prologue.

Too many of the characters are 'badass' and shown as distant/aloof/too-cool-to-talk-like-a-normal-person. The trouble is, when everyone's a badass character, nobody's a badass character, just a moody jerk.

Kaden, the heir, has a decent story around why he's a monk in training.

Valyn, the second brother, is part of the Kettrel, who act and speak like Marines, it's cringeworthy in the context.

Adare, the sister, is shown as an airhead who gets emotional and flustered over everything. The narrative takes every opportunity to remind the reader that she cannot sit on the throne because she is a woman.

Title: The Lords of the North (The Last Kingdom, #3)
Author: Bernard Cornwell

Title: 211 Things a Bright Boy Can Do
Author: Tom Cutler

Title: Ancillary Justice (Imperial Radch, #1)
Author: Ann Leckie
My Review:
Unexpectedly interesting. The book consists of a lot of talking and it can get slightly philosophical at times but the sentences are well constructed, conversations are well balanced and purposeful. It's confusing to begin with but understanding is gained over time in a rewarding fashion. One of the nice things is that some characters are able to deduce great implications based on minor actions of other characters, makes for good reading.

In the backdrop is the gigantic 'civilization' of the Raadchai, their aggressiveness, annexations, petty politicking. Above all refreshing to see them as the bad guys (sort of) with some good guys.


I couldn't understand Seivarden's purpose, perhaps it was only to get Breq into the palace?

And the ending was a bit, meh - Breq wanted to kill Anaander, regardless of the feebleness of the cause, and to expose the ongoing split in Anaander - nothing really happened.

Title: Seveneves
Author: Neal Stephenson
My Review:
A three part book, feels like a massive hypothetical "What if" scenario played out over five thousand years. The first two parts were too much interpersonal politics and bickering and back stories.

The resulting third part then because too much tech and history in between the protagonists taking two steps. Didn't work too well for me, the people of the time were simply too aware of themselves, yet at the same time did things according to their phenotypes... and far too much time was spent on the fraught origins of this dystopia.

Overall an interesting concept but an ok execution.

Title: The Last Voyage of Sigismund Skrik
Author: Karsten Flohr

Title: The Three Musketeers
Author: Alexandre Dumas
Additional Authors: Richard Pevear, Philip Bates, William Barrow, August Zoller, Marisa Zini, Moshe Ukle, Pierre Toutain-Dorbec, John      Lee, Jacques Georges Clemenc Le Clercq, Natalie Montoto, S.M. Sheley, Daniel Rasmusson, Louis Jourdan, Walter Covell, Michael Page, Michael Hugh Johnson, Sylvie Thorel-Cailleteau, Milo Winter, Bill Homewood, Arthur Paul John Charles James Gore Sudley, S.N. Rizvi, Giorgio Manganelli, William Robson, Isabel Ely Lord, Александр Дюма
My Review: Needs revision by author. There are more than three Musketeers and they do not use muskets. It should be The Four Sabers.

Title: ワンパンマン 1 一撃 [One Punch Man 1: Ichigeki]
Author: ONE

Title: The Skull Throne (Demon Cycle, #4)
Author: Peter V. Brett
My Review: Didn't hold any of the interest that the first three books did; the book spent too much time on characters backstabbing, fighting and getting angry over every slight to their pride. Abban's role is as interesting as ever, as is Inevera's.  Leesha and Rojer's parts are dull, and Arlen and Jardir's parts are veering on the aloof.  Hoping that in the next book, something actually happens.

Title: House of Suns
Author: Alastair Reynolds
My Review:
There are a lot of initially disjointed story threads which all end up related. There are the two incestuous shatterlings, the protagonists. The rest of the shatterlings who seem to shit on Purslane and Campion all the time. And other races including a machine race. There's the Vigilance, a group of weird aliens who take years to do anything, in pursuit of knowledge. There's the Absence, where the Andromeda galaxy is no longer visible from the Milky way. An elephant like race whose stardam (which Gentians maintain) malfunctioned and an entire civilization was wiped out.

The machine race discover that the Gentian line committed genocide against a previously arisen machine race and had erased a lot of evidence related to it. Purslane's ship has a stardam opener for a very special stardam - one that doesn't contain a star but a wormhole to the Andromeda galaxy where the first machine people had fled to. Two machine people kidnap Purslane and hijack her ship to head for this stardam, the rest of the remaining shatterlings in chase. There's also a robot Hesperus on board who is a friend to the shatterlings.

It's unbelievable but the climax of the book takes place over 60,000 years. Lots of bits in this book take place over massive scales.

They go through to Andromeda anyway and it turns out the first machine people had fled even that, all that was left was Hesperus who protected Purslane as a final act.

I felt almost sad being a human, as though I had a hand in the genocide. It was very well presented and even the conclusion makes me wonder what happened. The scales... the scales of time, space, distance, all are absolutely massive. They talk in massive time scales and meta terms, rather than individualistic. I also like how everyone is able to deduce actions and far reaching implications based on minor incidents, actions or observations. Very good scifi.

Title: Legion (Legion, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
Main character (Stephen Leeds) has a funny cast of hallucinations who help him solve mysteries. Each hallucination/character is nicely fleshed out and given a personality. Overall story is also quite good with the usual Branderson twists. This one takes them to Jerusalem where they are chasing the inventor of a camera that can take photos from the past (such as George Washington shaving). He finds the inventor, captured by a Filipino rebel group, ultimately they escape. And the secret was that the flash was the secret to taking photos from the past.

Among all this, there's also a photo of someone called Sandra which upsets Leeds, that will probably be explained in another book. Unusually, a few passages go into the foundations of faith and beliefs. Overall entertaining.

Title: Talion: Revenant
Author: Michael A. Stackpole
My Review:
Overall average story with average characters and average plot. Follows two threads, a present day one and flashback chapter. Nolan and friends make their way through the Justice League. They are the best and everyone is jealous of them. Nolan wants to be the best Justice ever. Nothing happens for the first half of the book, then he has to go and protect the king that destroyed his hometown. Also Marana, the girl he stole from Lothar (who inexplicably shows up at the end and then dies) is said to be dead but is predictably still alive.

Magic and lore unexplained, everything is just set. His friends, though important, are too flat. Lothar acts as the stereotypical friend who is a noble but turns out to be a haughty noble all along, completely black and white.

Definitely had a lot of potential and the adventures of the Justice League could have been a series of some sort.

Completely rushed, pointless ending. Marana just shows up and acts crazy because she is carrying his child. OK then.

Title: Dark Eden (Dark Eden, #1)
Author: Chris Beckett
My Review:
I'm a fan of this 'lost knowledge' kind of story, where the people are somewhat aware of some of the things we have today (electricity, radio, spaceships...) without fully understanding it, with their knowledge of things becoming fuzzier over time.

The story is told from several POVs, though mostly from John's POV, the one who breaks the mould and tries to discover what's beyond. The writing is well paced enough to have kept me reading. Several functions of human society that we take for granted today also exist in their world, fables, storytelling, councils, traditions and dissenters.

The only negative is the how it reminded me of The Demon Cycle, with its depiction of women, who are treated as little more than walking wombs.

Despite this, looking forward to the sequel, [b: Mother of Eden|22926605|Mother of Eden|Chris Beckett|https://d.gr-assets.com/books/1423737964s/22926605.jpg|40752165] to see how the new societies evolve.

Title: ブラッディ・マンデイ ラストシーズン 1 [Bloody Monday: Last Season Vol 1]
Author: Ryō Ryūmon

Title: Furies of Calderon (Codex Alera, #1)
Author: Jim  Butcher
My Review:
This is possibly one of the most unimaginative fantasy stories I've ever read.

Flat, undeveloped characters that read like cliches, so there was no reason to care about them. The characters themselves are inconsistent in behavior and have almost no explanation. There is no world building, whatever context is around the main conflict is kept at a distance.

When Tavi, the protagonist, meets the stereotypically aggressive Marat for the first time, it was full of dumb, aggressive brutes. At this, I actually said to myself "there's going to be a trial of blood or somesuch isn't there...". Just five pages later, there was a trial of blood.

Title: Daughter of Sand and Stone
Author: Libbie Hawker
My Review:
Being somewhat familiar with Zenobia's references (having lived in the area and read of her), this was definitely a good take the events surrounding her rise to power and 'rebellion' against the empire. Zenobia is portrayed as an ambitious and determined riser, she manages to turn bad situations around and make the most of what she can. The pacing isn't hurried, it's just well enough to enjoy every aspect of her maturity and rise.

I didn't like the 'fall of Zenobia', where she practically gives up the empire to run towards the child she's been neglecting for several years; it made her appear uncharacteristically weak. Combined with the chance meeting in an oasis with Farulia who happened to have her son there... and her suddenly becoming motherly on the ship ride back to Rome. The whole thing just felt soppy, rushed, and out of character. Quite disappointing.

I think a better job could have been done with the events surrounding her fall, especially considering that her and Aurelian's forces did actually meet in battle, where her forces were crushed and they fled. That scenario is ripe for plucking.

I'd recommend this read, I haven't read many historical-fictions with strong female leads, so it felt quite refreshing. There's an afterword by the author at the end of the book, do read that bit too.

Title: The Liar's Key (The Red Queen's War, #2)
Author: Mark  Lawrence
My Review:
Less comedic than the first, a bit more serious. But Jalan stays his true self (selling out, complaining, cowardly). They travel a lot, in fact most of the book is just traveling, so not as interesting as the first.

Jalan gets to revisit his town where things have changed and the allures of before are gone. And on the way has visions realizing the roles Alicia (Red Queen), Silent Sister and Garyus have. He rescues them from a prison. They eventually get to Kelem's cave. Defeat Kelem using Aslaug. Open Death's Door. Go in. Jalan tried to avoid going in but Snorri drags him in.

Title: Aus der Oberpfalz : Sitten und Sagen (German Edition)
Author: Franz Xaver von Schönwerth

Title: Prince of Fools (The Red Queen's War, #1)
Author: Mark  Lawrence
My Review:
Very witty writing, I haven't seen anything similar to this yet, though other authors sometimes try similar things. A good blend of seriousness and doses of humor. There's Prince Jal the prince who wants to have fun and Snorri the serious Viking. They get bound together by a spell and travel north to 'rescue' Snorri's family. It turns out they're part of a bigger plan to stop the Dead King who's raising unborns. They eventually stop the Unborn Captain by clasping hands (he was light, Snorri was dark) and there's some kind of explosion. Snorri's family has been all fucked up and he never gets to rescue them. Jal also finds out that the Silent Sister is his uncle Garyus' twin. The Red Queen (his grandma) has some awareness of this but it wasn't clear from the book.

At the end Snorri has the key that can open anything and the Red Queen mentioned earlier that there was an actual physical door to death. Presumably this key can open the door, but I'm not sure why.

Title: Hounded (The Iron Druid Chronicles, #1)
Author: Kevin Hearne
My Review: Struggled to get through this. It's a teen paranormal harem fantasy of sorts. Based around mythological entities, there is the obligatory cocky 'young' male character, who knows absolutely everything there is to know about everything, surrounded by beautiful women who love and hate him. Yeah... k.

Title: Ready Player One (Ready Player One, #1)
Author: Ernest Cline
My Review:
Takes place in a virtual world.

Way, way too many 80s references. 80s shows, actors, games, stories.

Cringeworthy at times, especially with his soppiness towards Artemis. The future movie may be presented better but this was somewhat regrettable.

Title: I Am Pilgrim
Author: Terry Hayes
My Review: Mystery/Thriller story of super duper mega awesome elite agent - who's retired of course but is brought back - on the hunt for a bioterror agent. Interestingly woven together when the cliches aren't getting in the way of the narrative.

Title: Knight's Shadow (Greatcoats, #2)
Author: Sebastien de Castell
My Review:
Far better than the first in the series. A lot more twists in almost every chapter and it's always unpredictable.

This felt like it should have been the end of the whole story, despite Trin still being alive, the duke's still scheming and an uncertain year ahead with a 'temporary' regent in place. It's a pretty big resolution to the omniscient king's quest.

I really liked how gritty and despairing the whole book was, but it was spoiled by the ending - too soppy and feel-good and everyone laughing at Brasti, like some stupid teen special.

The best bit in this was when Falcio (fal-key-oh) is tortured and goes through 8 deaths, and relives his wife's murder. Felt like something of a rebirth in a Greatcoat's own way. Also the red Kest bit. And the Dariana revelation - she had been sent in as a spy at the age of 14, like a sleeper agent

Title: Nemesis Games (The Expanse, #5)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review:
Reminder to self for when Expanse #6 comes out.

Presumably, this story was a way to add more people to the 'core' of Jim's crew. Each member (Alex, Amos, Naomi, Jim) go off and have their own stories, when disaster strikes various stations and Earth too. They all come back a bit different and a few come back with an extra person. Clarissa Mao from her prison on Earth; Bobbie Draper - the powersuit lady. Naomi visits her ex and her son who were attacking various stations and throwing massive rocks at Earth. However it turns out that their plan was too 'well structured' and likely someone else was behind it. Somewhere in there the protomolecule gets stolen.

Expanse 6 will be out around Jan 2016.
