Title: An American geological railway guide [microform]: giving the geological formation at every railway station : with altitudes above mean tide-water, notes on interesting places on the routes, and a description of each of the formations
Author: James MacFarlane
My Review:
For a long time, I had been searching for American geological railway guides in microform, giving the geological formation at every railway station with altitudes above mean tide water, notes on interesting places on the route and a description of each of the formations.

This is hands down the best book on this specific subject.

My favorite parts of the book were where it would describe various geological formations at railway stations. It was also quite helpful by mentioning the altitudes above mean tide water. Occasionally there would be notes on interesting places on the route too along with the descriptions of the formations.

Despite my favorable review of this book, I feel that the movie adaptation of this book did a far better job.

Title: 不安の種 1 (Fuan no Tane, #1)
Author: Masaaki Nakayama
My Review:
It's a creepy manga that's done well enough to give you the creeps. It is, however, extremely formulaic.

Person is doing something.
Person notices something nearby.
Distorted ghost face appears.
Repeat ad nauseam.

Title: A Memory of Light (The Wheel of Time, #14)
Author: Robert Jordan
My Review:
It's a shame that the hype around the end of this series is detracting from objective reviews. In fact, there were dozens of reviews months before the book had even come out declaring it to be the greatest book of all time.

I don't think so - subjectively seen, this is an attempt at saving the series and salvaging it in general. Brandon Sanderson had the onerous task of picking up where Robert Jordan left off. But I don't think that should factor in anywhere; years from now someone else picking up this series should not really care whether someone began writing it and someone else finished it. It also shouldn't matter that the ebook is going to come out months later, quite possibly a calculated move to maximize revenue, I found it extremely disappointing. What matters is that the core of a series, any series, is the story.

There's the part in a series, when the various threads, subplots and mysteries are resolved - the denouement. This is the goal of the entire series. You accompany the characters on their journeys and allow the little mysteries accrue around them, being promised their resolutions. And so you persevere and you carry on.

What often happens is this - the author (RJ) gets so lost in their world that they end up creating too much. They get carried away and the original goals are forgotten. There are a few ways to deal with this. One is to turn metaphysical and absolve responsibility (see: Lost finale) , another is to ignore all previous threads and create a climax unrelated (see A Memory of Light). Here we get all the characters over the past series in a series of tepid battle scenes. However, that is all they are. There is no denouement.

None of the attributes which drew us to the characters have any relevance. They are simply present in an endless series of permutation cameos to please all fans. We learn that everything before this has very little meaning; not everything, you can scrape the barrel a bit and there will be a few meaningful lines followed. Yet the multitude of threads and subplots remain frayed and ignored. The divisions, diversions, directions, diversions, quests, all of it, almost meaningless. Bloody and bloody ashes, even death is a temporary paragraph in the chaotic, loosely coupled story segments thrown about as the battle goes on. It's tough, having to fit all these characters and all these people into one part of a 14 part series. Each person gets a small amount of screen time and you're left with quantity over quality.

But the series stays true to its roots. Braids are tugged, men are put down, Rand feels woolheaded around all three of his lovers (as you do) and the women bicker right through the final battle.

Overall it's somewhat satisfactory, knowing that it has actually ended. It isn't satisfactory knowing that this was going to happen eventually. The saving grace in all of this is the style of Brandon Sanderson's writing, who manages to keep the pace fast and does his best to keep you interested enough to keep reading.

Title: おもいでエマノン [Omoide Emanon] (Emanon, #1)
Author: Shinji Kajio
Additional Authors: Kenji Tsuruta, 梶尾真治, 鶴田謙二

Title: The Soulkeepers (The Soulkeepers, #1)
Author: G.P. Ching
My Review:
Mildly interesting but suffers from too many clichés, the new boy being picked on, me against the world, mysterious villains, mysterious benefactors, beautiful girl with no friends except him, obligatory high school bullies out of movie land with no direction or purpose and the typical absolute divide between good and evil.

I hadn't checked but could tell that this was aimed at a young audience with a somewhat theological agenda.

The story was ultimately predictable once you got past a certain point but it became too long drawn. Still a few interesting characters and concept.

Title: The Phoenix Conspiracy (The Phoenix Conspiracy, #1)
Author: Richard L. Sanders
My Review:
The story is fast, keeps you interested and the mystery overarching the storyline is intriguing. The first half of the book keeps a very good pace and progression of the story.

The second half is where it all falls down. First, there appears to be some kind of obsession with Summers Presley, wherein we are reminded of just how gorgeous she is on every page. The bickering and in-fighting and to-ing-and-fro-ing of power on the ship that the story descends into has no purpose at all. At the end, there were no consequences of the actions that both sides took, it felt more like a filler. The whole in-fighting could have been cut out of the story and no difference would have been made.

I also feel this book makes a big mistake towards the end. We are told about a mysterious organization and strange forces working behind the scenes, but instead of being given a big plot-piece or any good details to keep us looking towards the second book of the series, we are given a bland conversation in which Raidan repeats, seemingly to the reader, "Trust me, it's big. You really want to buy the second book. I might tell you something there."

Title: Three Feet of Sky (Three Feet of Sky, #1)
Author: Stephen Ayres

Title: The Heroes
Author: Joe Abercrombie
My Review:
Did you know that this book takes place in the world of Logen Ninefingers? In case you didn't, it is pounded into your head about 53 times just in case the thickness of your skull prevents you from absorbing this fan-inspiring fact.

While alluding to the fact that this story takes place in the world of Logen Ninefingers, the characters in this particular book fail to come across as strong and enigmatic as those that the books with Logen Ninefingers in it. Instead they are reduced to quirky behaviors and overreaching grandioseness. This book is generally favored on Goodreads but I feel that you may enjoy it more if you have just read the First Law trilogy. I read those books 5 years ago, so the gap has taken its toll.

Title: Endgame (Sirantha Jax, #6)
Author: Ann Aguirre
My Review:
I walked into this one - I saw it on a sci-fi popularity list and started reading it without knowing anything about it, especially not knowing that:


  • * it's actually the 6th book in a series

  • * it's actually a romance



In fact, I should have taken a hint when I saw the opening line.

This is not a love story.

This should have set off alarm bells, but I chose to trust the narrator and that statement. Turns out it is a love triangle, and an inordinate amount of time is spent exploring relationships, thoughts, feelings and reminiscing. I felt that it weakened and diluted the actual sci-fi, the actual plot ends up jumping around a lot and results in a messy ending.

Without having read the series, my guess would be that Jax and her relationships have always been the sole focus of the entire series.

Title: The Next Big Thing: A Rough Guide to things that seemed like a good idea at the time (Rough Guide Reference)
Author: Rhodri Marsden
My Review: Presented century or decade wise, this book goes over the absurdities that each period engaged in. Most interesting was what we do today that could become fodder decades from now, like 160 character messages, paying money to not go to a gym and ugg boots, among many others.

Title: The Long Earth (The Long Earth, #1)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review:
An interesting premise is set up. Protagonists go on an adventure. Protagonists discuss various theological and philosophical implications of events and observations. All is good up to now.

Then suddenly, nothing happens for a long time. Also suddenly, the overarching mystery is explained with a half hearted attempt that flies in from left field and snacks you in the face.

Book ends with attempt at setting up a series of similar books.

Title: Neozoic (1)
Author: Paul Ens
Additional Authors: J. Korim, Jessie Lam, Troy Peteri

Title: ONE OUTS 1
Author: Shinobu Kaitani
My Review:
One of the best manga I've ever read, by the same author of Liar Game, another favorite.

The manga's first 80-ish chapters aren't translated. I'd recommend watching the anime and then reading the manga at chapter 82 where the story continues.

The only downside is that the manga is ongoing, so you have to wait weekly for new chapters. However, the story is still very good and keeps you waiting.

Title: Paw Tracks in the Moonlight
Author: Denis O'Connor Staff
My Review: This is like "Marley and me," feline edition - that means it's more interesting. It only covers one year of the cat's life and packs in a lot of details in an easy manner. There were no unnecessary distractions in the book, and assuming it's true, the author has done a good job of paying tribute to his cat.

Title: Speak Swahili, Dammit !
Author: James Penhaligon
My Review:
Unatombwa Unafirwa.

Thsi story takes place in an idyllic backdrop.

Kumamayo, Mavi, Mapumbu

It's about a young white boy who grows up more native than European.

Nenda Kukutomba Basher

He thinks Swahili, speaks Swahili and lives the local lifestyle. He is so fluent at Swahili that he nonchalantly insults people to their faces when they don't understand him. It's really quite funny.

Mama yako ananyonya mboo ya farasi

This book documents his struggle and coming to terms with living in both worlds.

Hawa mavi ya punda

Overall, I'd recommend this but it would definitely appeal to you if you've grown up somewhere in that region of the world, to really relate to it.

Title: The Great Gatsby
Author: F. Scott Fitzgerald
My Review: Rich people having parties. The end.

Title: And the Mountains Echoed
Author: Khaled Hosseini
My Review:
This story revolves around the lives of several people connected to another by virtue of having come into contact at different points in their lives. In the author's typical style, it covers the tragedies, failures and shortcomings of each person as they deal with their circumstances.

The opening to the story is one I really liked and it really makes you feel for the brother and sister. I'd almost say that it's one of the best tear jerking openings to a story that I've ever read.

I felt that the strong beginning, however, made the rest of the stories not as "beautiful", and by comparison fell short of the expectations set. Some of the stories could have been done away with.

It does recover in the end and lead to a bittersweet ending, but a bit too late, I was only looking forward to ending it.

In summary, it's not a unique concept or an amazing story but an enjoyable read anyway.

Read this if you're a fan of the author or either if his other books.

Or you could just wait until this is turned into a movie as it inevitably will.

Title: ギョ 1 [Gyo 1]
Author: 伊藤潤二
Author l-f: 伊藤潤二, 伊藤潤二

Author: Philip K. Dick

Title: Basilisk: The Kouga Ninja Scrolls, Vol. 1
Author: Masaki Segawa

Title: Stations of the Tide
Author: Michael Swanwick
My Review: Extremely difficult to follow narrative and poor grammar and prose.  It feels like the book is trying to hard to be something but in today's context, doesn't work well. On the plus side, a quick read.

Title: Percepliquis (The Riyria Revelations, #6)
Author: Michael J. Sullivan
My Review:
A staple in any fantasy novel is subplots, myths and legends, bits of history, minor characters. It's common to have the author introduce them to make their fantasy world 'more real'. What authors don't do is tying up those loose ends, explaining any legends or histories. Their main focus is the final conflict which ends and everything else is forgotten.

This is the first series I've read where all of these subplots, myths, legends, histories and minor characters are actually part of the story. What's more, small references made in book 1 are important in book 6. A sentence that someone said in passing becomes important too. The legends and histories are all part of the story. Reading all 6 of these books, you see that no sentence, person, statement or story is wasted. Absolutely everything is relevant. So it's absolutely satisfying to see the way everything comes together (everything).

It's as though the author planned all 6 books in advance and actually stuck to the plot and ideas formed as far back as book 1. For this sheer amount of planning and effort, this series gets 5 stars.

Title: Galactic North
Author: Alastair Reynolds
My Review: A few short stories.  Some were interesting, the one with the secret to the Conjoiner Drives was *very* interesting.

Title: Babel-17
Author: Samuel R. Delany
My Review: Too much time spent on the characters marveling at their own technology.  Needed more story time.

Title: Darwin's Radio (Darwin's Radio, #1)
Author: Greg Bear
My Review:
Interesting premise. Interesting core concept. Plausible biological concepts.

But damn, the execution was worse than a rusty guillotine's.

Title: The Warded Man (The Demon Cycle, #1)
Author: Peter V. Brett
My Review:
This was a difficult book to judge. On one hand, it has excellent prose and an intriguing storyline, the occasional grit of human nature, little details which reveal the nature of the world, little by little, to keep you interested. The protagonists are an interesting bunch that you want the best for.

On the other hand, everyone else is made out to be cliches - the most adulterous village on the planet, the Arab city of warriors (a complete copy of perceived Arab culture, without saying the word Arab), the over the top side characters, subplots and villains, and a final 'scene' designed for a feel good movie - break from what could have been a very good series.

Also, it got annoying very fast, being constantly reminded that the only purpose women existed for in this entire world was child bearing, and all they wanted was to get married and have children. Seriously, grow up.

Title: The Hundred-Year-Old Man Who Climbed Out of the Window and Disappeared (The Hundred-Year-Old Man, #1)
Author: Jonas Jonasson
My Review: I would give this exactly two point five stars. This is because one half of the book is entertaining and keeps you interested in all of the characters and their stories. The other half is an add-on that exists for no reason and the story would have been just fine without it. The attempts at making another Forrest Gump like character was too obvious, and I don't think it worked at all.

Title: The Republic of Thieves (Gentleman Bastard, #3)
Author: Scott Lynch
My Review:
Previous books have always been about the big game, details of its implementations and all the subterfuge, twists and turns; combined with the dry wit and scathing humor, it's always an excellent package.

This book turns our favorite characters into mopish dullards. Everything takes a backseat to Locke and Sabetha's 'romance'. I put romance in quotes because it is more of an unending series of inane conversations of meta-analysis wherein Locke mopes and Sabetha tries to explain why they can't be together, and then running away every so often for reasons known only to her. The author is trying very hard to say "Look! Our Locke is fascinated by her but she is alluring and mysterious and out of his grasp and it's unrequited love! I'll make it all happen again just in case you missed it the first time! Unrequited love!"


Compound this with the dual-story narrative. The old world where all the youngsters were together at an important point in their lives. The new world where it's Locke vs Sabetha in a game of politics. While still mingling and continuing their Unrequited love!

I found the old world weird. It had a few cult-ish ceremonies (think back to the temples) which felt like reading a B-movie. A few interesting threads of the wit we come to expect, but mostly a lot of moping and sulking for no real reasons other than to set the basis of their Unrequited love!

The new world could have been better. Though it is a Locke vs Sabetha contest, there isn't much to speak of about it. It was OK. It happens in the background. A few mentions are made. Again, because it isn't the focus of the narrative, it is something happening behind the scenes and some things take care of themselves. As a result, in trying to tie things together, a lot of things happen for no reason but hey don't forget the Unrequited love!

It also feels too movie like. It's trying to play like a movie where there is more attention on getting characters into various situations and the reasons aren't important even if they sound silly. Scenes are left half finished and just in case I haven't mentioned it, Unrequited love!

The big 'reveal' about the Bondsmagi felt more pointless. The big 'reveal' about Locke's past felt pointless, it was a deus ex out of nowhere just to further intensify their Unrequited love!

Overall the book is not what you expect from one in the series, it tries to do too much and be too much and it lacks excitement because of that. I feel some of the story elements should have been done away with, made it more streamlined and maybe dealt with the other elements later. Maybe even do away with the Unrequited love!

While it was a mostly lacklustre read, some parts do still stand out as gems and so the 2 star rating instead of 1.

By the way in case you missed it, Unrequited love!

Title: Firefight (The Reckoners, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
Hmm. I can't say I enjoyed this very much and I can't see what other reviewers are raving about. It didn't feel like a Brandon Sanderson novel or even a Reckoners story; this one felt flat and one-dimensional, like a young adult/juvenile fantasy.

I was constantly reminded how 'nerdy' David was (who wasn't). I was constantly reminded how 'real' or 'cute' Mizzy was (meh). The running gag about the bad metaphors was simply cringeworthy. New worldbuilding-physics was introduced but without much of a preamble, it simply 'just was' and nobody could explain it. A lot of time was wasted as David just mopes, the villains make vague threats and Megan is her usual beautiful, mysterious self. Sparks, I was constantly reminded how 'beautiful' Megan was. That David, such an awkward nerdy geeky slontze. (just stop)

Every character had one 'quirk' or grudge about something, and several of them played like cliched or poorly written side characters in superhero movies.

The core story itself was quite good but it felt spoiled by the interpersonal interactions. I'll still read the next in the series - Calamity - to find out if any of the mysteries are explained (also just because Brandon Sanderson).

Title: The Spirit Thief (The Legend of Eli Monpress, #1)
Author: Rachel Aaron

Title: The Code Book: The Science of Secrecy from Ancient Egypt to Quantum Cryptography
Author: Simon Singh

Title: The Curse of Chalion (World of the Five Gods, #1)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold

Title: Paladin of Souls (World of the Five Gods, #2)
Author: Lois McMaster Bujold
My Review:
Having read this directly after the Curse of Chalion, it wasn't as entertaining as the first, but interesting in its own way. Ista as a protagonist definitely works.

Would have liked to read more Cazaril though.

Title: Cibola Burn (The Expanse, #4)
Author: James S.A. Corey
My Review:
Another James Holden and crew adventure, which is always well written and well paced. This time the story has been written in a way where almost all the characters are as gray as it gets; I personally felt that they were all bad guys and that made it more interesting, the author does a great job of depicting humanity at its ugliest.

There is still no progress made into explaining where the protomolecules came from or what destroyed everything, only hinting at a greater force by constantly saying "something worse". I'm hoping that the ships disappearing in Nemesis Games goes into the details of this. But without going all metaphysical. A lot of series tend to do that when it comes to talking about 'greater' forces.

Title: Traitor's Blade (Greatcoats #1)
Author: Sebastien de Castell
My Review:
The three main characters are all well thought out, entertaining and there's a refreshing sense of humor around the narration that keeps this book interesting. The world building is done quite well, as are the flashbacks towards the past.

The bad stuff:
I found at two major parts of the story, the author had to rely on something like a deus-ex (or should I say deu-sex?) to move the story along. After being tortured, he meets Ethalia who miraculously cures him. No explanation. She just can. And towards the end, The Tailor just happens to know everything. No explanations are given, they just are and if you question them you don't need to know so shut the hell up, it just is. She just knows.


I think it'll probably depend on what goes on in Book 2 to see if there really is some story behind it, or that stuff was just a bit of rushed writing.

Aside from that, overall an entertaining read and it definitely reminds me of the Gentlemen Bastards series, while the writing feels as good as Brandon Sanderson's.

Title: Pride and Prejudice
Author: Jane Austen
My Review:
A collection of shallow elites with nothing better to do than talk about each other behind their backs, interfere with each other and plan their marriages. The story takes the pace of a snail crawling through peanut butter as chapters of nothing happen, one paragraph of significance occurs and we come back to the usual meaningless drivel of characters postulating, attending balls, dancing, analyzing each others' actions and behaviors and writing letters with massive run-on sentences.

The writing style shifts between conversations and descriptions of conversations. The inconsistencies between paragraphs in this way is quite jarring and kills anything that could evoke interest.

While this may have been excellent social commentary 200 years ago, I fail to see why it appears on so many "best books ever" lists today. It has no relevance now and only imparts poor moralities to the people who read it today, implying that you should be judged by your fortune and class and connections. The very notions of honor and nobility that are attributed to characters then are not the same now.

But hey - I am just one disagreeing voice in millions, I'll leave my lone star here and move on to better things.

Title: Sabriel (Abhorsen, #1)
Author: Garth Nix
My Review:
Generic fantasy plot. So generic, I found myself staring at the kindle progress bar on every other page turn. It tries to pack many popular fantasy plot devices in and creates a hodgepodge of slow paced adventure, uninteresting characters and no real direction.

That's the main thing missing for me. There's no clear purpose for the journey, it's more of a companion gathering phase followed by a solving the problem phase.

The "rules" of the fantasy world's magic are introduced at awkward times and nothing is adhered to.

There's no real character development, just a lot of "look at me, I'm mysterious and I have this piece of knowledge that you didn't expect me to." Well done.

It's after reading reviews that I've find out that this is a book for adolescents and preteens, which explains a lot. I'm just not the target audience and picked this up purely due to its rating.

Title: Bad Science
Author: Ben Goldacre
My Review:
Everything you know isn't a lie - it's bullshit.

It took me a while to finish reading this book as I took the time out to research the various claims and assertions put forward. They checked out, so I liked the book. In fact, I liked it so much, I recommended it to everyone.

I think it's really important to understand how science news is distorted and sensationalized in the media and this book explains it well. A lot of the TV personalities and pop culture people are people I haven't heard of but whom I realize have a huge influence on the way people perceive medicine and science.

Title: A Universe from Nothing: Why There Is Something Rather Than Nothing
Author: Lawrence M. Krauss

Title: The Pillars of the Earth (Kingsbridge, #1)
Author: Ken Follett
My Review:
This story revolves around a set of characters in the Kingsbridge/Shiring area and their stories with and against each other. The concept and historical context are quite interesting overall, especially the community factor and details around the building of the Kingsbridge Cathedral.

Where it lacks, though, is the black and white nature of the characters themselves. There are good and bad people but very little in between.

Good people are absolutely good and just and the bad people are the devil incarnate. The bad people keep tormenting the good people and the good people keep suffering. And it's in all small ways as well as big so it all adds up to create a community of the most unfortunate people on the planet.

And just when you think things can't get any worse, they do get worse. Maybe the unending strings of unfortunate incidents was part of the story style to make the reader feel endless despair, but a thousand pages of this is a bit too much. And it just goes on and on and on. I felt that the story could have been cut shorter.

Title: 名探偵コナン 1 [Meitantei Conan 1]
Author: Gosho Aoyama
My Review:
While the premise of the overall manga is good, it's turned into an infinite loop without progressing the storyline much. It's reached some 600+ chapters with the same basic series of events each time:

* Conan and co. happen to be at a specific location

* Someone dies

* Conan reveals the mystery through someone else


I don't think the fact that these central characters are almost constantly surrounded by death is really addressed anywhere.

Title: Nearly Departed
Author: Max Patrick Schlienger
My Review:
Light, humorous read. I think it could have been a bit longer though, as a lot of interesting subplots were started but seem to have been dropped towards the end. The relationship with the protagonist's wife was a bit 'off', she felt more like a prop for typical 'wife' like behavior and the added element of tension but it wasn't quite there.

Overall, good humorous writing and I'd say it's worth a read. It's free on Smashwords!

Title: Heroes Die (The Acts of Caine, #1)
Author: Matthew Woodring Stover
My Review:
'Heroes Die' is an actual mix of science fiction and fantasy in a very nice and almost believable way (the mix is driven by entertainment in the future rather than the collective goodwill of humanity). I'd say it's more towards the fantasy side as a larger part of the story is focused there. But the premise of this mix opens up a lot of possibilities.

The characters themselves are a few but quite strong and distinct. And there's a good story. The author isn't afraid to experiment with the characters, their fates, their injuries or their lives.

Author: Kenji Sakaki

A certain remark, passing reference or person in one part of the story comes into play later as an important part of the plot, so it rewards readers who are paying attention.  The first story arc was extremely well done and left me wanting more.  This is more of a 3.5-3.8 rather than 3, but I don't like rounding up.

Title: The World Without Us
Author: Alan Weisman
My Review:
This book forgot to talk about the "world without us" bit. Other than that it was alright.

However, I very specifically wanted to read about the "world without us" bit, and I had assumed from the title that it would talk about the "world without us". Much like a book about String Theory will talk about String Theory, I would think that a book entitled "world without us" would talk about "world without us".

This book fails spectacularly to talk about the "world without us" and spends an inordinate amount of time talking about how the world used to be (the world with us), and small histories about various places, meandering all over the map and time until it reaches a conclusion that nobody asked for.

While I understand the idea behind it - present a bit of the past so that we can better understand the "world without us" - it seemed as though the author was getting distracted and getting more and more engrossed in the past, completely forgetting to talk about "world without us".

A few attempts are made at actually talking about "world without us", but again these very quickly lead to the same tangential diatribes. Perhaps a demonstration in his in-depth knowledge of historical events and contexts, albeit of no useful purpose.

The worst bit, in my opinion, was the attempts at prose. Describing a flight taking off or sun setting against a quiet backdrop, these weren't relevant at all to the topic at hand (in case you've forgotten, the topic was "world without us"). It's as though the whole book was written with a documentary targeted in mind already. The author seems to be describing the scenes as he would like them filmed for the inevitable documentary. That's a bit presumptuous, why would I want to watch a documentary based on this book that fails to talk about "world without us"?

FTS.

Title: The Unlikely Pilgrimage of Harold Fry (Harold Fry, #1)
Author: Rachel Joyce
My Review:
This is a light read and the story reminded me of The Straight Story, in which a person travels a long distance, in a basic/rustic method, to see someone despite the existence of more convenient means of transportation.

The story focuses on the journey itself, the effects it has on the characters involved and the 'human' experience with people he meets along the way, both good and bad. There is also a lot of self-reflection.

The story takes place in the UK and comes with the charm of a plain, British setting where the characters are reserved, polite and diverse in so many little ways.

The author does a good job of keeping the interest going throughout the journey, though there were a few brief pages where it felt a bit flat.

Title: The Killing Moon (Dreamblood, #1)
Author: N.K. Jemisin
My Review:
This is one of those times when XKCD is relevant.



I felt this book had a great concept, but it's ruined by the details and execution of plot. And distractingly, all the made-up words.

The fantasy world that the author creates for this book is given too much detail, and a lot of it was unnecessary, or just there for the sake of being there. It kept repeating to the reader, "Look at how different this world is! It's like a perfect society of dream and magic! Everyone does things differently here!". There's no gradual buildup, instead the details are dumped on you almost all at once.

It also has way too many rules that felt superfluous and hollow in what is supposed to be a near idyllic society where everyone is happy and nobody has doors in their houses and nobody is corrupt and nobody hides their thoughts from each other and if you do it's rude. ◔_◔

Of course the plotline is based around the existence of corruption in this perfect society. Some of the protagonists simply can't believe it and spend an inordinate amount of time reeling in shock over the implications of this.

Overall the characters felt too clean-cut, lack any depth, and the storyline failed to pull me in.

Title: The Fabric of the Cosmos: Space, Time, and the Texture of Reality
Author: Brian Greene
My Review:
tl;dr:
+5 for great physics
-1 for shitty analogies

Review:
This is actually one of the best popular physics books I've ever read. I'd place it a level above the basic popular-science books such as A Brief History of Time and A Short History of Nearly Everything and The Elegant Universe. The best parts are bringing together the behavior of quantum mechanics to the early stages of the universe leading to why we observe certain properties of spacetime the way they are. It was also written a few years ago making it more modern and bringing in the latest advancements in physics. It was however written shortly before the LHC opened up, but it does reference the Higgs Boson being one of the main goals of the LHC and what it would mean if it was found.

The only negative is the analogies. Wow, the analogies are bad. They are stale, outdated, forced and detract from the point that the author is trying to make. In fact, they're so bad, the author has to explain it again right after the analogies. I feel the analogies may have made sense to the author and the editors at the time but it was obvious, or should have been obvious, that these would not stand the test of time. Perhaps it was an attempt to connect with a certain audience by referencing their TV shows all the time, but that won't last and won't make sense. It's just... BAD.

Title: Red Seas Under Red Skies (Gentleman Bastard, #2)
Author: Scott Lynch
My Review:
So, why do we read this series? We want more of the clever plans and schemes that Locke and Jean concoct and see through. Just as in the first book, there is a vast, elaborate plan in place in order to steal something - which is just what we want, it's why we read this series in the first place.

Unfortunately, this is where it falters and diverges.

First - the vast, elaborate plan has too many 'silences'. It's those things which the author deliberately doesn't reveal to the reader to save it for the end. Whoa - the protagonist just whispered something to that other person. And they talked about that thing. Oh and then he went out and bought a whole bunch of mysterious things. Then he told another person and they were surprised and said, "What a crazy plan! You'll never pull it off!" but they went ahead with it anyway! WHOA. The immediate problem there is that it's obviously being held back and gets irritating when that 'silence' is referred to again and again. Even more infuriating is if the revelation of this 'silence' is a lacklustre, underwhelming piece of information of no consequence. That's what happens here, the secrets are all for naught.

Second - there were too many threads. Too many things were happening and we lose focus of the main threads. Instead, they are all diluted, none of the imminent victories are savoured and there is no focus, there is nothing to look forward to. This proves itself in the climax when everything is rushed together towards the end and everything somehow resolves itself. It was a meh moment.

And finally, the most important bit, where we want our heroes to accomplish the task they set out for. Putting a twist on the reader is OK, no, it's good. Catches us by surprise. But when the twist becomes this underwhelming, festering, stale piece of garbage, appearing to be a twist for the sake of being a twist - no. Just no. What the hell are you doing. What was all this time and emotional investment for? Nothing.

So overall, the main story, the actual meat of it - it's stale and boring.

What does shine through is the writing. Some genuinely good writing, a good sense of clever, sly humor. Great character development. I even had a few laugh out loud moments. This whole book is about Jean and Locke, through and through.

But damn, the story was shit.

This is an unfortunate characteristic of series that gain popularity. The author may have had an overarching storyline in mind, but the immense success of the first causes the author to overthink and overreach. We end up with way too much in subsequent novels and nobody's expectations are met.

I can only imagine that this disappointment I am experiencing is the same feeling I have given to many women over the years.

My Review:
I wouldn't call this a fantasy story, more of an autobiography with a sprinkling of fantasy elements in it. Just in the right amounts at the right time to keep you interested. But it is mostly the story of Kvothe, written in a well paced and immersive way.

It's unlike any other fantasy novel I've read, so there isn't a point comparing it to anything else. I'm also thankful that the author didn't fall back on the most common, trite, overdone, overused and laziest of plot devices - dragons - and focused instead on solid story arcs.

Title: The Black Prism (Lightbringer, #1)
Author: Brent Weeks
My Review:
Starts off with a strong, interesting premise. However, the storyline is weak and poorly held together.

Gavin and Dazen are the only interesting characters and enough time is given to them in the book.

The problem is with the other characters; Kip is confident and brash one minute, puissant and blubbering the next minute. It's extremely inconsistent and distracting.

The storyline makes it fall apart, though:

Liv joins the 'other' side based on a simple misunderstanding and nothing more than a speech from the enemy. An enemy she met simply because she decided to follow Kip.

Kip, who decided he could take on the king after drafting one ball of luxin. That's it. He performs one bit of magic and decides that he is ready. Even reckless heroes will go through a bit of training before setting off on their quest.


I also found the author's obsession over the superiority of blonde hair and blue eyes a bit unsettling. One character even laments the lack of blonde hair and blue eyes.

Title: Assassin's Quest (Farseer Trilogy, #3)
Author: Robin Hobb
My Review:
This review is for the entire trilogy - the story is continuous so I figured that the third book should represent the culmination of the storyline.

There were some good things about this book
There are strong, likeable characters in here. Molly, Kettricken, Fool, Burrich, even Will and Regal in their hatred.

The author has a nice writing style which is engrossing at times.

But there a lot of things that make this trilogy a bad one

A lot of questions were introduced, a lot of story points, but none of the questions were answered. It seems like the author got lost in his own fantasy world and had to hurriedly wrap up the story and tie up any loose ends.

I've seen this far too often in the past when reading other series, and the patterns are usually recognizable: nothing significant happens until the last few chapters and BAM! suddenly there is a superpower and everything is resolved and back to normal and the enemies are defeated and people are happy and peace and prosperity return and there is smiling and dancing and joy.

In this case, nothing happens for two whole books until the very end, but instead our blundering hero makes his way across the land, getting beat up at every turn and living inside his obliviousness to obviousness.

This obliviousness to obviousness extended to other characters too. Let's see, Shrewd is being poisoned, which is obvious, but let us do nothing. Why? Chade says that nothing should be done about this. But why? Because Chade said so. Also, Molly had to 'take care of someone else' - which was an obvious reference to her being pregnant. But Fitz doesn't realize this.

Poor threads and subplots

Why were the red ships attacking the coast? Some flimsy pretence in the last chapter about black stones being a source of power... An afterthought by the author. I felt insulted at this. The whole premise of the story was the mysterious enemy harassing the coastline. All we get at the end is one paragraph about it. ONE paragraph. And if they were truly sources of power, why hold a ransom about returning them or killing them? Why does the ransom matter at all?

Why were the 'old blood' introduced only to be dismissed and never heard from again? "Hey Fitz, we're just like you. Look at how amazing and in control we are. We can help!" Fitz just says no, and that's the end of that. I think they were there just to add some intrigue into the story but it didn't go anywhere.

Elderlings are dragons. Oh look, it's this plot device again. When all else fails, add dragons to your story. Have your protagonists rely on the supernatural power of the dragons to solve all their problems. But even before that's revealed, it's spoiled by the cover of the book. Why would you refer to the mysterious Elderlings and then slap it on the cover of the book and give it all away? That's like the Chinese version of Sixth Sense, called "He's a ghost".

About Fitz...

I also think this series shouldn't have been named around assassins as it leads to a false sense of what Fitz really is. He is not an assassin. You see, an assassin assassinates. Fitz, well, Fitz just blunders. He gets involved in court intrigue and nobility and plotting and scheming even though he may deny it. Sure, he might take part in the occasional killing. But he is not an assassin.

Also, he sleeps a lot. I lost count of the number of chapters that ended with him falling asleep and chapters that started with him waking up, having had a dream that he did not fully understand.

The ending does matter

I've often heard that it is the journey that matters, not the ending. I invite you to book a flight to Singapore and turn back as soon as you reach Changi Airport. I disagree of course - the ending is more important to me, if not as important as the rest of the story. I would conceive that the author has some idea of an ending before starting the story and not lead us the way that Robert Jordan did. Don't get me wrong, I did enjoy reading the style of writing here, but it didn't go anywhere. If you've ever been friendzoned, then this is it, in the most literary sense.

Other series do manage to pull off a good ending. For me, these are LOTR, Mistborn, Northern Lights, First Law, Saga of the Seven Suns, Daughter of the Empire. Those are thought out, well contained storylines.

I found it somewhat frustrating, having spent a significant chunk of emotional time into a series, led onwards with the lure of an ending worthy of being remembered, only to see such a lacklustre ending.

Book 1 - 3 stars

This is the best book of the series as it is young and fresh and there is a lot of potential set up.


Book 2 - 3 stars

This has a more mature Fitz and it keeps you interested throughout just enough to start reading the third book.

Book 3 - 1 star
The story takes a completely different direction, there are new characters, a meaningless quest, and suddenly every woman is hitting on Fitz. Oh, to be Fitz.

Final rating

System.Math.Floor((3+3+1)/3) = 2 stars.

Title: Cities in Flight (Cities in Flight, #1-4)
Author: James Blish
My Review:
The best way to approach this book is to think of it as the Foundation series. It's a series of short stories related to each other and spanning millennia. It's also full of extremely intelligent characters who are able to grasp in an instant long term implications and meanings of thoughts and actions.

It's surprisingly well written in terms of scifi-science and the cultures, economies and history that those circumstances would lead us to.

The first story which takes place around this time in history is the least exciting one of all but is an important one as it is the setup for everything that follows. I guess it could've been a bit shorter but it wasn't so bad.

Definitely a hard scifi book I would recommend

Title: Inheritance (The Inheritance Cycle, #4)
Author: Christopher Paolini
My Review:
Overall, the book is better than the previous in the series. It's a bit more serious, well written and has a better storyline.

I found myself enjoying the Roran chapters a lot more than any of Eragon's feats. It somehow seemed more heroic to be able to accomplish and do everything he did, compared to the all-powerful Eragon who has a dragon and a magical belt and some mysterious book and amazing rings and a supernatural sword and all these powerful friends. Further, because of his limitations in the context of that world, Roran had a tougher task(s) to perform. I feel that Roran himself could be the protagonist of a series of his own.

The inevitable climactic confrontation wasn't very exciting, it felt rushed and cliched, with a slight hint of deus-ex thrown in. The confrontation that everyone was rushing towards wasn't really all that, it was too short and seemed to pass by with very little impact.

The ending was morose and left me with a feeling of sadness. I'm glad it wasn't a perfect 'everyone lived happily ever after' ending, it wouldn't have been appropriate.

Ultimately though, there seem to have been too many threads from previous books for the author to tie up and he did a good job of trying to keep the mystery alive with a semi-open end.

Title: Realms Unreel
Author: Audrey Auden
My Review:
Unique concept, made for an interesting storyline involving two very different entities. That's the best way i can put it, as it's hard to describe exactly what this is. It's mythology, science fiction, fantasy, history and drama. I'd be hard pressed to put this in just one category, instead it's a blend of all of them.

The thing I liked most, and am particular about, is computers and technology in books. I liked that the author did her research or is familiar with computers enough to make the technological accomplishments believable and not cringe-inducing.

The story itself takes a bit to get started and once it does, it'll have your attention.

The protagonists were likeable and i particularly enjoyed falsens, then emmie. The antagonist felt a bit cliched but wasn't large enough to become an eyesore.

It's a good short read, I'd definitely recommend this.

My Review: The book starts out really well and the main character seems believable as well as likeable. What spoiled it for me were the projected alpha male scenarios which I thought could have been done more tastefully and without making the women appear like tools. The main story was good overall and makes the book a good short read. It even has some genuinely fantastic moments, my favorite involving the one with the tourist...
